@verbose 0.1.0

-- Verbose-in-Verbose expression PARSER, brick 7 of the self-hosting arc.
--
-- Brick 7 adds two LITERAL kinds to parse_primary: boolean literals (`true` /
-- `false`, lexed as keywords codes 9/10, parsed to AstBool carrying 1/0) and
-- string literals (`"..."` with the closed escape set \n \r \t \\ \", lexed by
-- a new string_run scanner into a Str token, parsed to AstStr identified by its
-- source span). Booleans carry an arithmetic value (eval true=1, false=0) and
-- compose in and/or/not/comparisons; strings have no value without an
-- environment, so eval_ast returns 0 and correctness is proven by shape_ast
-- (dedicated bands AstBool=1000000, AstStr=10000000). The string scanner is the
-- tokenizer-reopening part: a backslash starts a 2-byte escape (LENIENT — this
-- is a token-boundary scanner, not an escape validator), so an escaped quote
-- \" does NOT terminate the string; an unterminated string runs to end-of-source.
--
-- Brick 2 (vtokenstream.verbose) materialized the token stream as a cons-list.
-- Brick 3 consumed that stream and built an arithmetic-expression AST in the
-- arena, WITH operator precedence, then evaluated it. Brick 4 EXTENDED that
-- ladder to the FULL expression precedence: logical or/and, comparisons, and
-- prefix unary (not / negation). Brick 5 grew `primary` to identifiers, function
-- calls, and field access. Brick 6 adds a CONDITIONAL EXPRESSION as the highest-
-- level alternative in `primary`: `if cond then thn else els`, the single-line
-- form (there is no INDENT/DEDENT in this tokenizer, so the multi-line block is a
-- later brick). The grammar (mirroring src/parser.rs, lowest to highest):
--
--   parse_expr = or_expr
--   or_expr    = and_expr ('or'  and_expr)*                 -- left-assoc, kw 'or'
--   and_expr   = cmp_expr ('and' cmp_expr)*                 -- left-assoc, kw 'and'
--   cmp_expr   = add_expr (('==' '!=' '<' '>' '<=' '>=') add_expr)?  -- non-assoc, <=1
--   add_expr   = mul_expr (('+' | '-') mul_expr)*           -- left-assoc  [brick 3]
--   mul_expr   = unary    (('*' | '/' | '%') unary)*        -- left-assoc  [brick 3 + %]
--   unary      = ('not' | '-') unary | primary              -- prefix, right-recursive
--   primary    = 'if' parse_or 'then' parse_or 'else' parse_or  -- brick 6, single-line
--              | '(' parse_or ')' | NUMBER | IDENT trailer       -- bricks 3 + 5
--
-- Each of the conditional's three sub-expressions is a FULL parse_or, so the
-- else-branch absorbs trailing operators: `if 1 then 2 else 3 + 100` parses the
-- else as `3 + 100` (and evaluates to 2, the then-branch). The if-expression is a
-- primary, so it nests in arithmetic via parens: `1 + (if 1 then 2 else 3)` = 3.
--
-- '*' '/' '%' bind tighter than '+' '-', which bind tighter than comparisons,
-- which bind tighter than 'and', which binds tighter than 'or'. Binary operators
-- are LEFT-associative (10-2-3 = 5; 2<3 and 4<5 = 1). Prefix unary is
-- right-recursive (not not 0 = 0; - -3 = 3). Calls, fields, and strings are
-- later bricks; this is the operator precedence ladder in full.
--
-- ============================================================================
-- AST OP-CODE MAP (the AstBin op field; chosen to avoid any collision).
-- ============================================================================
--   arithmetic   +  = 13   -  = 14   *  = 15   /  = 16   %  = 17  (tokenizer op_codes)
--   comparison   == = 1    != = 6    <  = 19   >  = 20   <= = 5   >= = 4   (tokenizer op_codes)
--   logical      and = 30  or = 31   (DEDICATED — kw codes 5/2 would alias <=/?, so remapped)
-- Unary uses its own variants (AstNeg / AstNot), no op code needed.
-- The three bands {13..17} {1,4,5,6,19,20} {30,31} are pairwise disjoint.
--
-- ============================================================================
-- POSITION THREADING (the hard part) — option (c): Parsed{node, next}.
-- ============================================================================
-- A recursive-descent function conceptually returns (ast, new_position): the
-- parsed node AND how far it consumed. A Verbose rule returns ONE value, so
-- each parse rule returns a `Parsed` arena node = { node: Ast, next: number }.
-- The caller reads `.next` to know where to resume and `.node` for the subtree.
-- This threads position cleanly through the arena and uses the group-field ABI
-- shipped in 9529277 (a recursive native rule can take a group-concept field).
--
-- ============================================================================
-- LEFT-ASSOCIATIVITY with single-return rules (no loops in Verbose).
-- ============================================================================
-- Classic recursive descent loops: `lhs = mul(); while op in {+,-}: lhs =
-- Bin(op, lhs, mul())`. Verbose has no loops — only recursion. The loop becomes
-- an accumulator recursion: parse_add parses the FIRST mul operand, then hands
-- (acc = that node, pos = after it) to add_rest. add_rest peeks the operator;
-- if it's +/-, it parses the next mul operand, folds Bin(op, acc, rhs) — acc on
-- the LEFT — and recurses with the new acc and new pos. Folding the accumulator
-- on the left at each step is exactly what makes the tree left-associative.
-- mul_rest does the same for * and /.
--
-- ============================================================================
-- TERMINATION
-- ============================================================================
-- The precedence rules form a cycle: parse_add -> parse_mul -> parse_primary
-- -> parse_add (through parentheses). No `decreasing`/`increasing`/`structural`
-- proof fits a precedence parser (position advances but not by a literal k, and
-- the input is a plain group-field record, not a structurally-shrinking group
-- value at every call). So these rules declare bound-only termination and
-- ACCEPT the mandatory native recursion breadcrumb — same posture as brick 2's
-- tokenize. Runtime backstops: the token list is FINITE (every parse step that
-- recurses has consumed at least one token, so pos strictly grows toward Eof),
-- the arena `max_nodes` is bounded, and every list access is Eof-guarded.
--
-- Oracle: src/parser.rs's parse_add_expr / parse_mul_expr / parse_primary.

-- ============================================================================
-- Arena sizing (the cap). The arena holds EVERY node: the token stream from
-- brick 2 (Token values + TokenList cons cells, ~2N+3 nodes for N tokens) AND
-- the AST (Parsed wrappers + Ast nodes). For an expression of N tokens the AST
-- has ~N/2 leaves and ~N/2 internal nodes plus a Parsed wrapper per parse-rule
-- return. max_nodes: 4000 covers the deepest test ("1+2+3+...+15" style and
-- "(((1+2)*3))" nesting) with wide headroom; max_depth: 256 matches brick 2.
-- Over the cap a VariantConstruct hits the arena bounds-check and the binary
-- exits 1 (fail-closed) rather than corrupting memory.
-- ============================================================================
concept_group VExpr [max_depth: 4096, max_nodes: 65535]
  @intention: "Tokens, a token cons-list, an arithmetic AST, and a parse result"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:1

  concept Token
    @intention: "One classified lexeme: kind + source span / value"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:1
    variants:
      Ident of (start : number, len : number)
      Keyword of (start : number, len : number, kw : number)
      Num of (value : number, len : number)
      Op of (code : number, len : number)
      -- A string literal token. start = the byte offset of the OPENING quote;
      -- len = the TOTAL byte length of the token INCLUDING both quotes (so
      -- token_end advances past the closing quote naturally). The span is the
      -- string's identity (like Ident / AstVar): brick 7 does not decode the
      -- bytes — that needs an environment — so a Str node's correctness is proven
      -- STRUCTURALLY by the shape walk, never by an evaluated value.
      Str of (start : number, len : number)
      -- A line-boundary token (brick 8a). pos = the byte offset of the newline
      -- byte (10) in the source. The tokenizer no longer STOPS at a newline (the
      -- pre-8a flat scanner classified byte 10 as Eof and tokenize halted at the
      -- first line break); instead next_token recognizes byte 10 — after skipping
      -- INLINE spaces (byte 32 only) — as a Newline token, token_end advances
      -- exactly 1 past it, and tokenize conses it like any other token and keeps
      -- scanning the next line. This lifts the "stops at first newline" limit so a
      -- multi-line source tokenizes into a flat stream WITH Newline tokens marking
      -- line boundaries. Brick 8a emits Newline FAITHFULLY: consecutive newlines
      -- (blank lines) emit consecutive Newline tokens — collapsing blanks and the
      -- INDENT/DEDENT column-stack logic are brick 8b. Brick 8a computes NO
      -- indentation, columns, INDENT, or DEDENT.
      Newline of (pos : number)
      -- Brick 8b: structural block tokens woven into the stream by the line
      -- driver (tokenize_indent). Indent marks entering a deeper block (one per
      -- deeper level, pushed onto the column stack); Dedent marks leaving a block
      -- (one per popped level, emitted on a shallower line AND flushed at EOF for
      -- every still-open level). IndentErr is the fail-closed error token: a
      -- Verbose rule is TOTAL (it cannot abort mid-evaluation the way
      -- src/lexer.rs returns a LexError), so the reference's tab-rejection and
      -- inconsistent-indentation errors become a distinguished token in the
      -- stream that the downstream self-hosting parser treats as a hard stop.
      -- pos = the byte offset of the offending line's content start.
      Indent
      Dedent
      IndentErr of (pos : number)
      Eof

  concept TokenList
    @intention: "Cons-list of tokens: the materialized token stream"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:1
    variants:
      Cons of (head : Token, tail : TokenList)
      Nil

  concept Ast
    @intention: "Expression AST: number leaf, binary op node, or unary op node"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:1
    variants:
      -- A numeric literal leaf
      AstNum of (value : number)
      -- A binary operator node: op is the AST op-code (see the op-code map at
      -- the top — arithmetic 13..17, comparison 1/4/5/6/19/20, logical 30/31),
      -- lhs/rhs are sub-expressions
      AstBin of (op : number, lhs : Ast, rhs : Ast)
      -- Prefix arithmetic negation: -inner
      AstNeg of (inner : Ast)
      -- Prefix logical not: not inner (-> 1 if inner == 0 else 0)
      AstNot of (inner : Ast)
      -- A bare variable reference, identified by its source SPAN (start byte
      -- offset + byte length). The span is the node's identity: two different
      -- identifiers necessarily occupy different (start) offsets, and carrying
      -- len as well distinguishes a short ident from a longer one that happens
      -- to start at the same place (impossible in one source, but the pair is
      -- the honest identity and what src/parser.rs's Expr::Ident name stands in
      -- for). Brick 5 does not resolve the name to bytes — that needs an
      -- environment; here the span IS the variable, proven structurally.
      AstVar of (start : number, len : number)
      -- Field access: base.field. The accessed field is a span (fstart, flen);
      -- base is the sub-expression being accessed. Chains nest left-deep:
      -- a.b.c parses to AstField(AstField(AstVar(a), b), c).
      AstField of (base : Ast, fstart : number, flen : number)
      -- A function call: callee identified by its span (callee_start,
      -- callee_len), args a cons-list (ArgList) of argument sub-expressions.
      -- f() has args = ArgNil; f(x) = ArgCons(AstVar(x), ArgNil); f(x, y) =
      -- ArgCons(AstVar(x), ArgCons(AstVar(y), ArgNil)).
      AstCall of (callee_start : number, callee_len : number, args : ArgList)
      -- A conditional expression: if cond then thn else els. All three are
      -- sub-expressions (each a full parse_or). eval_ast evaluates cond, then
      -- the SELECTED branch only (the language's lazy if, so the dead branch's
      -- eval_ast never runs). Brick 6: single-line form only — there is no
      -- INDENT/DEDENT in this tokenizer, so the multi-line form is a later brick.
      AstIf of (cond : Ast, thn : Ast, els : Ast)
      -- A boolean literal leaf: value is 1 for `true`, 0 for `false`. Brick 7.
      -- Unlike AstStr/AstVar, a boolean DOES carry an arithmetic value, so
      -- eval_ast returns it directly (true -> 1, false -> 0), and it composes in
      -- and/or/not/comparisons exactly as a 1/0 number would.
      AstBool of (value : number)
      -- A string-literal leaf, identified by its source SPAN (start = opening
      -- quote offset, len = total bytes including both quotes — copied from the
      -- Str token). Brick 7. A string has no arithmetic value without an
      -- environment to decode its bytes, so eval_ast returns 0 and correctness
      -- is proven STRUCTURALLY by shape_ast (a dedicated band), exactly like
      -- AstVar / AstCall / AstField.
      AstStr of (start : number, len : number)
      -- An error/placeholder leaf (unexpected token); evaluates to 0
      AstErr

  concept ArgList
    @intention: "Cons-list of call-argument AST nodes (like TokenList but for args)"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:1
    variants:
      ArgCons of (head : Ast, tail : ArgList)
      ArgNil

  concept Parsed
    @intention: "A parse result: the AST built plus the index where it ended"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:1
    variants:
      -- node = the subtree parsed; next = token index just past it
      Mk of (node : Ast, next : number)

  concept ParsedArgs
    @intention: "A call-argument parse result: the ArgList built plus the end index"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:1
    variants:
      -- args = the argument cons-list parsed; next = token index just past ')'
      MkArgs of (args : ArgList, next : number)

  -- Brick 8b: the column stack. A cons-list of open-block indentation widths,
  -- mirroring src/lexer.rs's `indent_stack: Vec<usize>`. Push(width, rest) is a
  -- level opened at column `width`; Empty is the file's outermost (column-0)
  -- sentinel level that is never popped (top_width returns 0 for it). The stack
  -- lives in the arena exactly like TokenList; the line driver threads it as one
  -- of its two group-concept fields (the multi-group-field recursive ABI,
  -- commit 9529277 — verified to compile by the design note's probe).
  concept ColStack
    @intention: "Indentation column stack: open-block widths (Empty = column-0 sentinel)"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:27
    variants:
      Push of (width : number, rest : ColStack)
      Empty

  -- Brick 8b: the multi-DEDENT result. The shallower-width pop is a recursion
  -- over ColStack that must return THREE things at once (a Verbose rule returns
  -- one value): the stack AFTER popping every level whose width > the target
  -- (`popped`), the NUMBER of levels popped (`count` = the number of Dedent
  -- tokens to emit), and an inconsistency FLAG (`err` = 1 iff after popping the
  -- new top width does not exactly equal the target — i.e. the line's width
  -- matches no enclosing block, src/lexer.rs:227-236). Packed into one concept.
  concept DedentResult
    @intention: "Result of a multi-DEDENT pop: new stack + dedent count + inconsistency flag"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:27
    variants:
      MkDed of (popped : ColStack, count : number, err : number)

  -- Brick 9: a cons-list of let-bindings in the arena. Each cell carries the
  -- bound name as a SOURCE SPAN (name_start, name_len) — the same identity model
  -- as AstVar / a Str token (brick 9 does not resolve the name to bytes; that
  -- needs an environment, which is the OPTIONAL bonus eval below). `value` is the
  -- binding's right-hand-side expression (a full parse_or subtree). `rest` chains
  -- to the next binding; BNil terminates the list. Mirrors src/parser.rs's
  -- ordered `lets: Vec<(name, expr)>` on a logic block, in arena cons-list form.
  concept Binding
    @intention: "Cons-list of let-bindings: bound name span + RHS expression + rest"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:28
    variants:
      BCons of (name_start : number, name_len : number, value : Ast, rest : Binding)
      BNil

  -- Brick 9: a parsed statement block — the ordered binding list plus the final
  -- out-expression. Mirrors src/parser.rs's logic block (a sequence of let
  -- bindings followed by `out = <expr>`): `binds` is the BCons chain in source
  -- order, `result` is the final out-statement's RHS expression subtree.
  concept Block
    @intention: "A parsed statement block: ordered let-bindings + the final out-expression"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:28
    variants:
      MkBlock of (binds : Binding, result : Ast)

  -- Brick 9: a block parse result — the Block built plus the token index just
  -- past it. Same Parsed-threading shape as `Parsed` (Mk) / `ParsedArgs`
  -- (MkArgs), one level up: parse_block / parse_stmts thread `next` so a caller
  -- could continue after the block (e.g. a sibling block at the same level).
  concept ParsedBlock
    @intention: "A block parse result: the Block built plus the end token index"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:28
    variants:
      MkPB of (block : Block, next : number)

  -- Brick 10: the evaluation ENVIRONMENT. A cons-list mapping a bound name —
  -- carried as a SOURCE SPAN (name_start, name_len) exactly like a Binding cell
  -- or an AstVar — to its ALREADY-COMPUTED numeric value `val`. Distinct from
  -- Binding (which carries the unevaluated RHS Ast): Env carries the resolved
  -- number, so a variable reference is one byte-compare + one slot read, with no
  -- re-evaluation of the binding's expression on each lookup. `rest` chains to
  -- the enclosing scope; ENil is the empty environment. build_env conses the
  -- newest binding onto the FRONT, and env_lookup walks front-to-back, so the
  -- MOST RECENT binding of a name wins (shadowing: `let x = 1` then `let x = 2`
  -- resolves x to 2). The name's identity is its bytes in the source text, so
  -- env_lookup byte-compares the query span against each entry's span via the
  -- shared `src`.
  concept Env
    @intention: "Evaluation environment: name span -> already-computed number, innermost first"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:29
    variants:
      ECons of (name_start : number, name_len : number, val : number, rest : Env)
      ENil

  -- Brick 11: a parsed top-level RULE declaration. `name_start` / `name_len` are
  -- the rule NAME's source span (the same identity model as a Binding name or an
  -- AstVar — brick 11 does not decode the name to bytes; it is proven by the span
  -- length in rule_shape). `body` is the rule's `logic:` block, reusing the
  -- brick-9 Block exactly (a binding list + the final out-expression). Mirrors
  -- src/parser.rs's Rule { name, logic } restricted to the tractable subset:
  -- name + logic block only (no intention / source / input / output / proofs —
  -- those are later bricks). RuleDecl lives in this group because it carries a
  -- group-typed field (body : Block), and cross-group references are rejected.
  concept RuleDecl
    @intention: "A parsed top-level rule declaration: its name span + its logic block"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:30
    variants:
      MkRule of (name_start : number, name_len : number, params : ParamList, body : Block)

  -- Brick 12: a parsed PROGRAM — a cons-list of top-level rule declarations in
  -- source order. RCons carries one RuleDecl head and the rest; RNil is the empty
  -- program (end-of-input). Same cons shape as TokenList / Binding / Env, so the
  -- same arena machinery and the same structural-recursion proof apply. Mirrors
  -- src/parser.rs's Program = Vec<Rule> restricted to rule-only items (no
  -- concept / use / @attributes — those are later bricks).
  concept RuleList
    @intention: "A parsed program: a cons-list of top-level rule declarations"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:31
    variants:
      RCons of (head : RuleDecl, tail : RuleList)
      RNil

  -- Brick 12: a rule-declaration parse result that THREADS its end position — the
  -- RuleDecl built plus the token index just past its body (the same Parsed-
  -- threading shape as ParsedBlock's MkPB). parse_rule_decl_pos returns this so
  -- the program loop knows where one rule decl ends and can resume scanning for
  -- the next `rule` keyword. `next` comes from the body block's pb_next (just past
  -- the final out-expression); the trailing DEDENT(s) that close the logic + rule
  -- bodies sit at/after `next` and are consumed by the program loop's separator
  -- skip, not by the rule-decl parser.
  concept ParsedRule
    @intention: "A rule-decl parse result: the RuleDecl built plus its end token index"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:31
    variants:
      MkPR of (rule : RuleDecl, next : number)

  -- Brick 16: a rule's PARAMETER list — a cons-list of parameter NAMES, each a
  -- source span (name_start, name_len), in source order. Same identity model as a
  -- Binding name or an AstVar (the param is its bytes in the source text, never
  -- decoded). PNil terminates the list (zero params — `rule f()` or `rule f`).
  -- Mirrors src/parser.rs's Rule.params (the formal parameter names). Brick 20 adds
  -- a `ty` field per param: the declared type code (0=number, 1=bool, 2=text — the
  -- same codes brick 19 uses), defaulting to 0 (number) when a param is untyped.
  -- An untyped `x` carries ty=0; a typed `x : bool` carries ty=1. Lives in the
  -- group because it is the same cons-list family as ArgList / Binding.
  concept ParamList
    @intention: "Cons-list of a rule's formal parameters (each a source span + declared type code)"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:34
    variants:
      PCons of (name_start : number, name_len : number, ty : number, rest : ParamList)
      PNil

  -- Brick 16: a parameter-list parse result — the ParamList built plus the token
  -- index just past the closing ')' (or the unchanged start index when there are
  -- no parens at all). Same Parsed-threading shape as ParsedArgs's MkArgs.
  concept ParsedParams
    @intention: "A parameter-list parse result: the ParamList built plus the end index"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:34
    variants:
      MkPP of (params : ParamList, next : number)

  -- Brick 23: a STRUCTURED diagnostic. Brick 22's check_program collapses the whole
  -- program to a single error COUNT — useful as a pass/fail gate, useless for
  -- telling the operator WHERE the program is wrong. A Diag localizes the first
  -- failure: `rule_index` is the 0-based position (in source order) of the first
  -- rule that fails any analysis, and `category` is WHICH analysis failed first
  -- (1=undef-var/use-before-def, 2=undef-callee, 3=arity, 4=ill-typed, 5=arg-type;
  -- 0=clean). A fully clean program is reported as MkDiag(9999, 0) — 9999 is the
  -- sentinel "no bad rule" index (no real program here reaches 9999 rules, the
  -- ProgramState pos field caps at 512). Single-variant "record-like" group concept,
  -- exactly like RuleDecl (MkRule) / Block (MkBlock) / Parsed (Mk): it lives in the
  -- group because find_diag is a recursive rule that RETURNS one (same group-return
  -- ABI as find_rule returning a RuleDecl, or build_env returning an Env), and a
  -- number driver reads a field off it via the bare-group accessors diag_index /
  -- diag_cat (same idiom as rd_body / block_binds). Brick 26 widens MkDiag with two
  -- more number fields — span_start / span_len — so the located full report points AT
  -- the offending token for undefined-variable diagnostics (category 1). For every
  -- other category (2-5) and every sentinel, the span is MkSpan(9999, 0)'s shape
  -- (span_start 9999, span_len 0): "not located". diag_span_start / diag_span_len are
  -- the matching bare-group accessors.
  concept Diag
    @intention: "A structured diagnostic: the failing rule's 0-based index, its error category, and the offending name's source span"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:41
    variants:
      MkDiag of (rule_index : number, category : number, span_start : number, span_len : number)

  -- Brick 24: a cons-list of Diags — the COMPLETE diagnostic report. Brick 23's
  -- find_diag returns ONE Diag (the first failure). This brick generalizes it to a
  -- list: one Diag per (rule, failing-category) pair, in program order, ascending
  -- category within a rule. DCons carries one Diag head + the rest; DNil is the
  -- empty report (a fully clean program yields DNil, NOT MkDiag(9999,0) — the
  -- sentinel was brick 23's single-Diag convention; an empty LIST needs no
  -- sentinel). Same 2-variant cons shape as Binding (BCons|BNil) / ArgList
  -- (ArgCons|ArgNil) / RuleList (RCons|RNil), so the same arena machinery and the
  -- same structural-recursion proof apply. It lives in the group because rule_diags
  -- / diag_append / prog_diags are recursive rules that RETURN one (same group-return
  -- ABI as build_env returning an Env), and the number drivers read off it via
  -- diag_count / nth_diag_rule / nth_diag_cat (the cons-walk idiom).
  concept DiagList
    @intention: "A cons-list of Diags: the complete diagnostic report (one Diag per rule-category pair)"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:42
    variants:
      DCons of (diag : Diag, rest : DiagList)
      DNil

  -- Brick 25: a source SPAN — the (start, len) byte range of a token in the source
  -- buffer. Where brick 13/14 COUNTED undefined-variable references, this brick
  -- finds the FIRST one and returns its name span, so a diagnostic can point AT the
  -- offending token instead of merely tallying. Single-variant "record-like" group
  -- concept, exactly like Diag (MkDiag) / RuleDecl (MkRule) / Block (MkBlock): it
  -- lives in the group because the undef_span_* family are recursive rules that
  -- RETURN one (same group-return ABI as find_diag returning a Diag), and the number
  -- drivers read a field off it via the bare-group accessors span_start / span_len
  -- (same idiom as diag_index / diag_cat). The sentinel "no undefined variable" span
  -- is MkSpan(9999, 0) — 9999 is the same out-of-range marker find_diag uses for the
  -- rule index, so span_or recognizes "no result" by testing span_start == 9999.
  concept Span
    @intention: "A source byte range: the (start, len) span of a token's name in the source text"
    @source: vexprparse.intent:43
    variants:
      MkSpan of (start : number, len : number)


-- ============================================================================
-- Brick 2 reused verbatim: the tokenizer. (Copied so bricks 1-2 stay pristine;
-- the Token/TokenList concepts above are identical to brick 2's, just sharing
-- this program's single concept_group as the native one-group cap requires.)
-- ============================================================================

concept ScanState
  @intention: "Scanner position in source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:2
  fields:
    source : text [..256]
    pos : number [0, 256]


rule skip_spaces
  @intention: "Advance past spaces"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:3
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let len = length(s.source)
    out = if s.pos >= len then s.pos else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 32 then skip_spaces(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: s.pos + 1 }) else s.pos
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : [skip_spaces]
    termination:
      bound : 256
      increasing : pos


rule digit_run
  @intention: "Count consecutive [0-9] bytes from pos"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:4
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let len = length(s.source)
    out = if s.pos >= len then 0 else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) >= 48 and byte_at(s.source, s.pos) <= 57 then 1 + digit_run(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: s.pos + 1 }) else 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : [digit_run]
    termination:
      bound : 256
      increasing : pos


rule pow10
  @intention: "10^n for small n (digit-position weight)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:5
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = if s.pos == 0 then 1 else 10 * pow10(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: s.pos - 1 })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : [pow10]
    termination:
      bound : 256
      decreasing : pos


rule num_value
  @intention: "Decode the decimal value of the digit run starting at pos"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:6
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let len = length(s.source)
    let rl = digit_run(s)
    out = if rl == 0 then 0 else (byte_at(s.source, s.pos) - 48) * pow10(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: rl - 1 }) + num_value(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: s.pos + 1 })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos, s]
      calls : [digit_run, pow10, num_value]
    termination:
      bound : 256
      increasing : pos


-- Length of an identifier-continue run [a-zA-Z0-9_]* starting at pos. Brick 4
-- needs identifiers because the logical keywords (and/or/not) lex as identifier
-- runs first, then get a keyword code. (Brick 3 had no idents — arithmetic only.)
rule ident_run
  @intention: "Count consecutive [a-zA-Z0-9_] bytes from pos"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:7
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let len = length(s.source)
    out = if s.pos >= len then 0 else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 95 then 1 + ident_run(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: s.pos + 1 }) else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) >= 48 and byte_at(s.source, s.pos) <= 57 then 1 + ident_run(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: s.pos + 1 }) else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) >= 65 and byte_at(s.source, s.pos) <= 90 then 1 + ident_run(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: s.pos + 1 }) else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) >= 97 and byte_at(s.source, s.pos) <= 122 then 1 + ident_run(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: s.pos + 1 }) else 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : [ident_run]
    termination:
      bound : 256
      increasing : pos


-- two-letter keywords (brick 4 only needs `or`, but mirror brick 1/2's codes
-- exactly: if=1, or=2, of=3 — so a future brick lexing the rest agrees).
rule kw2
  @intention: "Classify a 2-byte identifier run as a keyword (0 if none)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:7
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 105 and byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 1) == 102 then 1 else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 111 and byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 1) == 114 then 2 else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 111 and byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 1) == 102 then 3 else 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 32


-- three-letter keywords: let=4, and=5, not=6 (brick 1/2 codes; brick 4 uses
-- and=5 and not=6).
rule kw3
  @intention: "Classify a 3-byte identifier run as a keyword (0 if none)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:7
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 108 and (byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 1) == 101 and byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 2) == 116) then 4 else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 97 and (byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 1) == 110 and byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 2) == 100) then 5 else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 110 and (byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 1) == 111 and byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 2) == 116) then 6 else 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 48


-- four-letter keywords: then=7, else=8 (brick 6 — `if`/`then`/`else` as an
-- expression), true=9 (brick 7 — boolean literal). Codes 7/8/9 don't collide
-- with the existing 1-6 (if/or/of/let/and/not). `then` = t(116) h(104) e(101)
-- n(110); `else` = e(101) l(108) s(115) e(101); `true` = t(116) r(114) u(117)
-- e(101).
rule kw4
  @intention: "Classify a 4-byte identifier run as a keyword (0 if none)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:7
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 116 and (byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 1) == 104 and (byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 2) == 101 and byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 3) == 110)) then 7 else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 101 and (byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 1) == 108 and (byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 2) == 115 and byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 3) == 101)) then 8 else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 116 and (byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 1) == 114 and (byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 2) == 117 and byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 3) == 101)) then 9 else 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 64


-- five-letter keywords: false=10 (brick 7 — boolean literal). The only 5-byte
-- keyword so far; longer-or-other 5-byte identifier runs stay plain idents
-- (kw == 0). `false` = f(102) a(97) l(108) s(115) e(101).
rule kw5
  @intention: "Classify a 5-byte identifier run as a keyword (0 if none)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:7
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 102 and (byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 1) == 97 and (byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 2) == 108 and (byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 3) == 115 and byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 4) == 101))) then 10 else 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 80


-- Dispatch keyword classification by identifier-run length. Brick 6 added the
-- 4-byte keywords (then / else); brick 7 adds the 4-byte `true` and the 5-byte
-- `false` alongside the 2- and 3-byte keywords (or / and / not). Other-length
-- identifier runs lex as plain identifiers here (kw == 0) and are handled by
-- later bricks.
rule keyword_code
  @intention: "Numeric keyword code for the identifier run at pos (0 = plain ident)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:7
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let rl = ident_run(s)
    out = if rl == 2 then kw2(s) else if rl == 3 then kw3(s) else if rl == 4 then kw4(s) else if rl == 5 then kw5(s) else 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s]
      calls : [ident_run, kw2, kw3, kw4, kw5]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- str_content_len: scan a string's CONTENT starting at `pos` (the first byte
-- after the opening quote) and return the number of bytes from `pos` up to AND
-- INCLUDING the closing quote. Escape handling is LENIENT (this is a token-
-- BOUNDARY scanner, not an escape validator — the reference lexer rejects
-- unknown escapes, but here the only goal is to find where the token ends): on a
-- backslash (92) the next byte is part of a 2-byte escape and is skipped
-- unconditionally, so an escaped quote (\") does NOT terminate the string. The
-- closed escape set the language cares about (\n \r \t \\ \") all fit this
-- 2-byte-skip rule; an unknown \x is simply two literal bytes here.
--
-- UNTERMINATED: if the end of source is reached before a closing quote, the run
-- stops and the bytes scanned so far are the token's content length (no closing
-- quote is counted). Fail-closed: every byte_at is guarded by the pos >= len
-- check, and the backslash branch checks pos + 1 < len before skipping the
-- escaped byte (a trailing lone backslash counts as 1 and stops).
--
-- Termination: pos strictly increases by 1 or 2 each step toward len, so the
-- `increasing : pos` proof holds; bound 256 caps the source length.
rule str_content_len
  @intention: "Bytes from pos to the closing quote inclusive (lenient escapes, unterminated stops at end)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:8
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let len = length(s.source)
    out = if s.pos >= len then 0 else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 34 then 1 else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 92 then (if s.pos + 1 >= len then 1 else 2 + str_content_len(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: s.pos + 2 })) else 1 + str_content_len(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: s.pos + 1 })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : [str_content_len]
    termination:
      bound : 256
      increasing : pos


-- string_run: total byte length of a string token whose OPENING quote is at
-- `pos`, INCLUDING both quotes. = 1 (the opening quote) + the content length up
-- to and including the closing quote (str_content_len from pos + 1). For an
-- unterminated string the closing quote is absent, so the result is 1 + bytes-
-- to-end — token_end then advances to the end of source and tokenize stops.
rule string_run
  @intention: "Total byte length of the string token at the opening quote (both quotes included)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:8
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = 1 + str_content_len(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: s.pos + 1 })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : [str_content_len]
    termination:
      bound : 256


rule op_code
  @intention: "Operator/punct class code at pos; two-char before one-char"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:7
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let len = length(s.source)
    let c0 = if s.pos >= len then 0 else byte_at(s.source, s.pos)
    let hasnext = if s.pos + 1 < len then 1 else 0
    let c1 = if hasnext == 1 then byte_at(s.source, s.pos + 1) else 0
    out = if c0 == 61 and (hasnext == 1 and c1 == 61) then 1 else if c0 == 61 and (hasnext == 1 and c1 == 62) then 2 else if c0 == 58 and (hasnext == 1 and c1 == 58) then 3 else if c0 == 62 and (hasnext == 1 and c1 == 61) then 4 else if c0 == 60 and (hasnext == 1 and c1 == 61) then 5 else if c0 == 33 and (hasnext == 1 and c1 == 61) then 6 else if c0 == 58 then 10 else if c0 == 44 then 11 else if c0 == 46 then 12 else if c0 == 43 then 13 else if c0 == 45 then 14 else if c0 == 42 then 15 else if c0 == 47 then 16 else if c0 == 37 then 17 else if c0 == 61 then 18 else if c0 == 60 then 19 else if c0 == 62 then 20 else if c0 == 40 then 21 else if c0 == 41 then 22 else if c0 == 123 then 23 else if c0 == 125 then 24 else if c0 == 91 then 25 else if c0 == 93 then 26 else 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 80


rule op_len
  @intention: "Byte length of an operator code (2 for two-char ops, 1 otherwise)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:8
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let code = op_code(s)
    out = if code >= 1 and code <= 6 then 2 else 1
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s]
      calls : [op_code]
    termination:
      bound : 8


rule next_token
  @intention: "Recognize and classify the next core lexeme at the position"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:9
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : Token
  logic:
    let len = length(s.source)
    let p = skip_spaces(s)
    let isnl = if p >= len then 0 else if byte_at(s.source, p) == 10 then 1 else 0
    let isalpha = if p >= len then 0 else if byte_at(s.source, p) == 95 then 1 else if byte_at(s.source, p) >= 65 and byte_at(s.source, p) <= 90 then 1 else if byte_at(s.source, p) >= 97 and byte_at(s.source, p) <= 122 then 1 else 0
    let isdigit = if p >= len then 0 else if byte_at(s.source, p) >= 48 and byte_at(s.source, p) <= 57 then 1 else 0
    let isstr = if p >= len then 0 else if byte_at(s.source, p) == 34 then 1 else 0
    let irun = ident_run(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: p })
    let drun = digit_run(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: p })
    let srun = string_run(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: p })
    let kwc = keyword_code(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: p })
    let opc = op_code(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: p })
    let opl = op_len(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: p })
    let nval = num_value(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: p })
    out = if p >= len then Token::Eof else if isnl == 1 then Token::Newline { pos: p } else if isalpha == 1 then (if kwc > 0 then Token::Keyword { start: p, len: irun, kw: kwc } else Token::Ident { start: p, len: irun }) else if isdigit == 1 then Token::Num { value: nval, len: drun } else if isstr == 1 then Token::Str { start: p, len: srun } else if opc > 0 then Token::Op { code: opc, len: opl } else Token::Eof
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s]
      calls : [skip_spaces, ident_run, digit_run, string_run, keyword_code, op_code, op_len, num_value]
    termination:
      bound : 256


rule token_end
  @intention: "Byte offset just past the next token (post-skip start + width)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:10
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let len = length(s.source)
    let p = skip_spaces(s)
    let isnl = if p >= len then 0 else if byte_at(s.source, p) == 10 then 1 else 0
    let isalpha = if p >= len then 0 else if byte_at(s.source, p) == 95 then 1 else if byte_at(s.source, p) >= 65 and byte_at(s.source, p) <= 90 then 1 else if byte_at(s.source, p) >= 97 and byte_at(s.source, p) <= 122 then 1 else 0
    let isdigit = if p >= len then 0 else if byte_at(s.source, p) >= 48 and byte_at(s.source, p) <= 57 then 1 else 0
    let isstr = if p >= len then 0 else if byte_at(s.source, p) == 34 then 1 else 0
    let irun = ident_run(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: p })
    let drun = digit_run(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: p })
    let srun = string_run(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: p })
    let opc = op_code(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: p })
    let opl = op_len(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: p })
    out = if p >= len then p else if isnl == 1 then p + 1 else if isalpha == 1 then p + irun else if isdigit == 1 then p + drun else if isstr == 1 then p + srun else if opc > 0 then p + opl else p
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s]
      calls : [skip_spaces, ident_run, digit_run, string_run, op_code, op_len]
    termination:
      bound : 256


rule tokenize
  @intention: "Scan the whole source into a cons-list of tokens (trailing Eof)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:11
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : TokenList
  logic:
    let len = length(s.source)
    let p = skip_spaces(s)
    let endp = token_end(s)
    out = if p >= len then TokenList::Cons { head: Token::Eof, tail: TokenList::Nil } else if endp <= p then TokenList::Cons { head: Token::Eof, tail: TokenList::Nil } else TokenList::Cons { head: next_token(s), tail: tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: endp }) }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s]
      calls : [skip_spaces, token_end, next_token, tokenize]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- Token-stream access helpers (brick 2's drop_cells / head_tok generalized to
-- the parser's needs). The parser peeks tokens by absolute index into the full
-- token list.
-- ============================================================================

concept Nth
  @intention: "A token list plus an index into it"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:12
  fields:
    lst : TokenList
    n : number [0, 512]


rule drop_cells
  @intention: "The token list with its first arg.n cons cells removed"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:12
  input:
    arg : Nth
  output:
    out : TokenList
  logic:
    out = match arg.lst:
      Cons(head, tail) => if arg.n == 0 then arg.lst else drop_cells(Nth { lst: tail, n: arg.n - 1 })
      Nil => TokenList::Nil
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [arg.lst, arg.n]
      calls : [drop_cells]
    termination:
      bound : 512
      decreasing : n


rule head_tok
  @intention: "Head token of a list (Eof for Nil)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:13
  input:
    lst : TokenList
  output:
    out : Token
  logic:
    out = match lst:
      Cons(head, tail) => head
      Nil => Token::Eof
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [lst]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Kind code of one token, mirroring brick 2: Eof=>0, Ident=>100,
-- Keyword=>200+kw, Num=>300+value, Op=>400+code, Str=>500 (brick 7). The Str
-- kind has no value/code suffix (its identity is the source span), so 500 is a
-- flat sentinel — but a structural test (tok_is_str / peek_is_str) is preferred
-- in the parser, mirroring tok_is_num / tok_is_op, since the Num band (300+value)
-- can overflow into 500 for value >= 200.
rule tok_kind
  @intention: "Kind code of one token"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:13
  input:
    t : Token
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match t:
      Ident(start, len) => 100
      Keyword(start, len, kw) => 200 + kw
      Num(value, len) => 300 + value
      Op(code, len) => 400 + code
      Str(start, len) => 500
      Newline(pos) => 600
      Indent => 700
      Dedent => 800
      IndentErr(pos) => 900
      Eof => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [t]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- The numeric value carried by a token (the literal value for Num, else 0).
-- Used so a NUMBER leaf gets its real value, not the kind code.
rule tok_value
  @intention: "The literal value of a Num token (0 for any other token)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:13
  input:
    t : Token
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match t:
      Ident(start, len) => 0
      Keyword(start, len, kw) => 0
      Num(value, len) => value
      Op(code, len) => 0
      Str(start, len) => 0
      Newline(pos) => 0
      Indent => 0
      Dedent => 0
      IndentErr(pos) => 0
      Eof => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [t]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- 1 iff the token IS a Num, structurally (independent of its value). The kind
-- code packs Num as 300+value, which OVERFLOWS into the Op kind band (400+code)
-- once value >= 100; so a magnitude-based `300 <= k <= 399` test would misread
-- a literal like 100. This structural test matches the Num variant directly.
rule tok_is_num
  @intention: "1 if the token is a number literal, 0 otherwise (value-independent)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:13
  input:
    t : Token
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match t:
      Ident(start, len) => 0
      Keyword(start, len, kw) => 0
      Num(value, len) => 1
      Op(code, len) => 0
      Str(start, len) => 0
      Newline(pos) => 0
      Indent => 0
      Dedent => 0
      IndentErr(pos) => 0
      Eof => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [t]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- 1 iff the token IS an Op, structurally. Same value/kind-band overflow
-- hazard as tok_is_num: a Num literal whose value lands in 13..16 packs to a
-- kind (413..416) that aliases the +,-,*,/ operator kinds. The fold rules use
-- this structural test to decide "is the next token an operator" before reading
-- its code, so a number is never mistaken for an operator.
rule tok_is_op
  @intention: "1 if the token is an operator/punctuation, 0 otherwise"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:13
  input:
    t : Token
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match t:
      Ident(start, len) => 0
      Keyword(start, len, kw) => 0
      Num(value, len) => 0
      Op(code, len) => 1
      Str(start, len) => 0
      Newline(pos) => 0
      Indent => 0
      Dedent => 0
      IndentErr(pos) => 0
      Eof => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [t]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- The operator code carried by an Op token (0 for any other token).
rule tok_op_code
  @intention: "The operator code of an Op token (0 for any other token)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:13
  input:
    t : Token
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match t:
      Ident(start, len) => 0
      Keyword(start, len, kw) => 0
      Num(value, len) => 0
      Op(code, len) => code
      Str(start, len) => 0
      Newline(pos) => 0
      Indent => 0
      Dedent => 0
      IndentErr(pos) => 0
      Eof => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [t]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- 1 iff the token IS an Ident, structurally (kind 100). The keyword tokens
-- and/or/not pack to 200+kw, so they are NOT idents here — exactly what brick 5
-- wants (a primary IDENT is a variable/callee name, never a logical keyword).
rule tok_is_ident
  @intention: "1 if the token is an identifier, 0 otherwise"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:13
  input:
    t : Token
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match t:
      Ident(start, len) => 1
      Keyword(start, len, kw) => 0
      Num(value, len) => 0
      Op(code, len) => 0
      Str(start, len) => 0
      Newline(pos) => 0
      Indent => 0
      Dedent => 0
      IndentErr(pos) => 0
      Eof => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [t]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- The source-span START offset of an Ident token (0 for any other token).
rule tok_start
  @intention: "The start byte offset of an Ident token (0 for any other token)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:13
  input:
    t : Token
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match t:
      Ident(start, len) => start
      Keyword(start, len, kw) => 0
      Num(value, len) => 0
      Op(code, len) => 0
      Str(start, len) => 0
      Newline(pos) => 0
      Indent => 0
      Dedent => 0
      IndentErr(pos) => 0
      Eof => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [t]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- The source-span LENGTH of an Ident token (0 for any other token).
rule tok_len
  @intention: "The byte length of an Ident token (0 for any other token)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:13
  input:
    t : Token
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match t:
      Ident(start, len) => len
      Keyword(start, len, kw) => 0
      Num(value, len) => 0
      Op(code, len) => 0
      Str(start, len) => 0
      Newline(pos) => 0
      Indent => 0
      Dedent => 0
      IndentErr(pos) => 0
      Eof => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [t]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- 1 iff the token IS a Str, structurally (brick 7). Mirrors tok_is_num /
-- tok_is_op: a magnitude test on tok_kind (== 500) would misread a Num literal
-- whose value is 200 (kind 500), so the parser uses this structural test to
-- decide "is the next token a string literal" before reading its span.
rule tok_is_str
  @intention: "1 if the token is a string literal, 0 otherwise (value-independent)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:13
  input:
    t : Token
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match t:
      Ident(start, len) => 0
      Keyword(start, len, kw) => 0
      Num(value, len) => 0
      Op(code, len) => 0
      Str(start, len) => 1
      Newline(pos) => 0
      Indent => 0
      Dedent => 0
      IndentErr(pos) => 0
      Eof => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [t]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- The source-span START offset of a Str token (0 for any other token). For a
-- Str this is the opening-quote byte offset.
rule tok_str_start
  @intention: "The start byte offset of a Str token (0 for any other token)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:13
  input:
    t : Token
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match t:
      Ident(start, len) => 0
      Keyword(start, len, kw) => 0
      Num(value, len) => 0
      Op(code, len) => 0
      Str(start, len) => start
      Newline(pos) => 0
      Indent => 0
      Dedent => 0
      IndentErr(pos) => 0
      Eof => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [t]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- The source-span LENGTH of a Str token (0 for any other token). For a Str this
-- is the total byte length including both quotes.
rule tok_str_len
  @intention: "The byte length of a Str token (0 for any other token)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:13
  input:
    t : Token
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match t:
      Ident(start, len) => 0
      Keyword(start, len, kw) => 0
      Num(value, len) => 0
      Op(code, len) => 0
      Str(start, len) => len
      Newline(pos) => 0
      Indent => 0
      Dedent => 0
      IndentErr(pos) => 0
      Eof => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [t]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Peek the kind code of the token at absolute index `arg.n` in `arg.lst`.
rule peek_kind
  @intention: "Kind code of the token at index n (0 = Eof / past end)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:14
  input:
    arg : Nth
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = tok_kind(head_tok(drop_cells(arg)))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [arg]
      calls : [tok_kind, head_tok, drop_cells]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Peek the literal value of the token at absolute index `arg.n`.
rule peek_value
  @intention: "Literal value of the token at index n (0 if not a Num)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:14
  input:
    arg : Nth
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = tok_value(head_tok(drop_cells(arg)))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [arg]
      calls : [tok_value, head_tok, drop_cells]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Peek whether the token at index `arg.n` is a number literal (structural).
rule peek_is_num
  @intention: "1 if the token at index n is a number literal, 0 otherwise"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:14
  input:
    arg : Nth
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = tok_is_num(head_tok(drop_cells(arg)))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [arg]
      calls : [tok_is_num, head_tok, drop_cells]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Peek whether the token at index `arg.n` is an operator (structural).
rule peek_is_op
  @intention: "1 if the token at index n is an operator, 0 otherwise"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:14
  input:
    arg : Nth
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = tok_is_op(head_tok(drop_cells(arg)))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [arg]
      calls : [tok_is_op, head_tok, drop_cells]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Peek the operator code of the token at absolute index `arg.n` (0 if not Op).
rule peek_op_code
  @intention: "Operator code of the token at index n (0 if not an operator)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:14
  input:
    arg : Nth
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = tok_op_code(head_tok(drop_cells(arg)))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [arg]
      calls : [tok_op_code, head_tok, drop_cells]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Peek whether the token at index `arg.n` is an identifier (structural).
rule peek_is_ident
  @intention: "1 if the token at index n is an identifier, 0 otherwise"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:14
  input:
    arg : Nth
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = tok_is_ident(head_tok(drop_cells(arg)))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [arg]
      calls : [tok_is_ident, head_tok, drop_cells]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Peek the Ident source-span start offset of the token at index `arg.n`.
rule peek_start
  @intention: "Source-span start offset of the Ident token at index n (0 if not an Ident)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:14
  input:
    arg : Nth
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = tok_start(head_tok(drop_cells(arg)))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [arg]
      calls : [tok_start, head_tok, drop_cells]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Peek the Ident source-span length of the token at index `arg.n`.
rule peek_len
  @intention: "Source-span length of the Ident token at index n (0 if not an Ident)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:14
  input:
    arg : Nth
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = tok_len(head_tok(drop_cells(arg)))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [arg]
      calls : [tok_len, head_tok, drop_cells]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Peek whether the token at index `arg.n` is a string literal (structural).
rule peek_is_str
  @intention: "1 if the token at index n is a string literal, 0 otherwise"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:14
  input:
    arg : Nth
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = tok_is_str(head_tok(drop_cells(arg)))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [arg]
      calls : [tok_is_str, head_tok, drop_cells]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Peek the Str source-span start offset (opening-quote byte) of the token at
-- index `arg.n`.
rule peek_str_start
  @intention: "Source-span start offset of the Str token at index n (0 if not a Str)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:14
  input:
    arg : Nth
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = tok_str_start(head_tok(drop_cells(arg)))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [arg]
      calls : [tok_str_start, head_tok, drop_cells]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Peek the Str source-span length (both quotes included) of the token at index
-- `arg.n`.
rule peek_str_len
  @intention: "Source-span length of the Str token at index n (0 if not a Str)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:14
  input:
    arg : Nth
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = tok_str_len(head_tok(drop_cells(arg)))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [arg]
      calls : [tok_str_len, head_tok, drop_cells]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- ============================================================================
-- THE PARSER. Precedence recursive descent over the token list.
-- ParseState carries the FULL token list `toks` plus the current index `pos`.
-- Each parse rule returns a Parsed{node, next}.
-- ============================================================================

concept ParseState
  @intention: "The whole token list plus the current parse index"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:15
  fields:
    toks : TokenList
    pos : number [0, 512]


-- Accessors for a Parsed result. A block-form `match` is only legal in the
-- FINAL `out = match ...` position (not as a `let` RHS — see the language gap
-- noted in vexprparse.intent), so destructuring a Parsed is factored into these
-- two tiny rules and called wherever a parse rule needs the node or the index.
rule parsed_node
  @intention: "The AST subtree from a parse result"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:15
  input:
    p : Parsed
  output:
    out : Ast
  logic:
    out = match p:
      Mk(node, next) => node
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [p]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


rule parsed_next
  @intention: "The token index just past a parse result"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:15
  input:
    p : Parsed
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match p:
      Mk(node, next) => next
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [p]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- A fold-step state: the token list, the current index, and the accumulated
-- left-hand AST node built so far. add_rest / mul_rest carry this.
concept FoldState
  @intention: "Token list + current index + the left-associative accumulator"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:15
  fields:
    toks : TokenList
    pos : number [0, 512]
    acc : Ast


-- A join state: a fold accumulator plus the operator and the freshly-parsed
-- right operand (as a Parsed). add_join / mul_join consume this to fold the
-- accumulator one step left-associatively, then continue the fold.
--
-- WHY a separate join rule (and not a let): Verbose `let` bindings are EAGER,
-- but `if` only evaluates the TAKEN branch. The recursive descent into the next
-- operand MUST be guarded — if it ran eagerly (in a let) it would fire even
-- when there is no operator, recursing forever (parse_add -> parse_mul ->
-- parse_primary -> parse_add ...). So the next-operand parse is placed inside
-- the `then` branch (lazy), and its Parsed result is handed to a join rule that
-- extracts node+next ONCE. add_join <-> add_rest and mul_join <-> mul_rest are
-- mutually recursive; both live in the parser's recursion cycle, so the Parsed
-- group-field input compiles natively (the group-field ABI, commit 9529277).
concept JoinState
  @intention: "Fold accumulator + operator + the parsed right operand"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:15
  fields:
    toks : TokenList
    acc : Ast
    opcode : number [0, 64]
    rhs : Parsed


-- A unary-wrap state: the token list, a flag selecting not (1) vs negation (0),
-- and the Parsed inner operand. parse_unary parses the operand LAZILY in the
-- matched branch and hands it here; unary_wrap builds the AstNot / AstNeg node.
-- In the parser cycle (called only from parse_unary), so the Parsed field
-- compiles natively.
concept WrapState
  @intention: "Token list + not/neg selector + the parsed unary operand"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:18
  fields:
    toks : TokenList
    isnot : number [0, 1]
    inner : Parsed


-- Brick 9: the let-statement continuation state. Carries the token list, the
-- bound name SPAN (name_start, name_len), and the already-parsed RHS value (as a
-- Parsed). stmt_let_join consumes this — extracts the value node + its end index,
-- recurses parse_stmts on the rest of the block, and conses the binding. Lives in
-- the brick-9 parse cycle (called only from parse_stmts's let-branch), so its
-- Parsed group-field input compiles natively (the group-field recursive ABI).
concept LetJoinState
  @intention: "Token list + bound name span + the parsed let-RHS value"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:28
  fields:
    toks : TokenList
    name_start : number [0, 256]
    name_len : number [0, 256]
    value : Parsed


-- A paren-close state: the token list plus the Parsed inner expression. Used to
-- consume an optional ')' after a parenthesized sub-expression. In the parser
-- cycle (called only from parse_primary's paren branch), so the Parsed field
-- compiles natively.
concept ParenState
  @intention: "Token list + the parsed inner expression of a parenthesis"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:15
  fields:
    toks : TokenList
    inner : Parsed


-- An arg-cons state: the token list plus a freshly-parsed argument (as a
-- Parsed). args_cons consumes this — extracts the arg node + its end index —
-- peeks for a ',' (continue: parse the next arg via parse_args) or ')' (stop),
-- and prepends the arg to the resulting ArgList. Lives in the parser cycle
-- (called only from parse_args), so the Parsed group-field input compiles
-- natively (the group-field ABI, commit 9529277).
concept ArgConsState
  @intention: "Token list + one parsed call argument (continuing the arg cons-list)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:15
  fields:
    toks : TokenList
    first : Parsed


-- An arg-prepend state: the head argument's AST node plus the already-parsed
-- REST of the argument list (as a ParsedArgs). args_prepend consumes this —
-- conses the head onto the rest's ArgList, carrying the rest's end index. A
-- single-input rule (the language allows one input per rule), so the head node
-- and the rest are packed into this one state. In the parser cycle (called only
-- from args_cons), so the ParsedArgs group-field input compiles natively.
concept ArgPrependState
  @intention: "Head argument AST + the parsed rest of the argument list"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:15
  fields:
    head_node : Ast
    rest : ParsedArgs


-- A call-build state: the callee span (start, len) plus the parsed argument
-- list (as a ParsedArgs). call_build extracts the ArgList + its end index and
-- builds the AstCall node. In the parser cycle (called only from
-- parse_primary's call branch), so the ParsedArgs group-field input compiles
-- natively.
concept CallState
  @intention: "Callee span + the parsed argument list of a function call"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:15
  fields:
    toks : TokenList
    cstart : number [0, 512]
    clen : number [0, 512]
    pargs : ParsedArgs


-- A field-chain state: the token list, the current index, and the accumulated
-- base AST (the expression whose field is being accessed). field_rest folds
-- successive '.IDENT' steps onto the base, left-deep (a.b.c => AstField(
-- AstField(AstVar(a), b), c)).
concept FieldState
  @intention: "Token list + current index + the accumulated field-access base"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:15
  fields:
    toks : TokenList
    pos : number [0, 512]
    base : Ast


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 6: `if cond then thn else els` as an expression. The single-line form
-- only — there is no INDENT/DEDENT in this tokenizer. parse_primary detects the
-- `if` keyword (kind 201) and threads three sub-parses (cond / thn / els, each a
-- full parse_or) through a chain of continuation rules, because a Verbose rule
-- has ONE input and `let` is EAGER (a let-bound parse_or would fire on every
-- parse_primary call, recursing forever). Each continuation carries the partial
-- state in a single concept and parses its sub-expression LAZILY (only when
-- reached from the if-branch). The chain: parse_primary --(cond Parsed)-->
-- if_then --(thn Parsed)--> if_else --(els Parsed)--> if_build (assembles AstIf).
-- All three continuations live in the parser recursion cycle (they call
-- parse_or), so their Parsed group-field inputs compile natively (group-field
-- ABI, commit 9529277).
-- ============================================================================

-- if_then: given the parsed condition, locate the `then` keyword (kind 207),
-- step over it, and parse the then-branch (a full parse_or). The cond's AST node
-- is carried forward; the thn parse is handed to if_else.
concept IfThenState
  @intention: "Token list + the parsed condition of an if-expression"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:25
  fields:
    toks : TokenList
    cond : Parsed


-- if_else: given the cond node and the parsed then-branch, locate the `else`
-- keyword (kind 208), step over it, and parse the else-branch. The cond and thn
-- nodes are carried forward; the els parse is handed to if_build.
concept IfElseState
  @intention: "Token list + the if-expression condition node + the parsed then-branch"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:25
  fields:
    toks : TokenList
    cond_node : Ast
    thn : Parsed


-- if_build: given the cond and thn nodes and the parsed else-branch, assemble the
-- AstIf node carrying the else-branch's end index.
concept IfBuildState
  @intention: "The if-expression cond + then nodes + the parsed else-branch"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:25
  fields:
    cond_node : Ast
    thn_node : Ast
    els : Parsed


-- Pull the ArgList out of a ParsedArgs result.
rule parsed_args_list
  @intention: "The argument cons-list from a call-argument parse result"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:15
  input:
    p : ParsedArgs
  output:
    out : ArgList
  logic:
    out = match p:
      MkArgs(args, next) => args
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [p]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Pull the end index out of a ParsedArgs result.
rule parsed_args_next
  @intention: "The token index just past a call-argument parse result"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:15
  input:
    p : ParsedArgs
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match p:
      MkArgs(args, next) => next
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [p]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Consume the optional ')' after a '(' add_expr. Reads where the inner
-- expression ended; if the next token is ')' (kind 422) it is consumed
-- (next = inner_end + 1), otherwise the position is left as-is (a missing ')'
-- is tolerated rather than aborting — error recovery is a later brick).
rule paren_close
  @intention: "Consume a closing paren after a parenthesized sub-expression"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:16
  input:
    ps : ParenState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let inner_next = parsed_next(ps.inner)
    let inner_node = parsed_node(ps.inner)
    let after_op = peek_op_code(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: inner_next })
    let close_pos = if after_op == 22 then inner_next + 1 else inner_next
    out = Parsed::Mk { node: inner_node, next: close_pos }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [ps.toks, ps.inner]
      calls : [parsed_next, parsed_node, peek_op_code]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 5: identifiers, function calls, field access. Mirrors src/parser.rs's
-- parse_primary ident path:
--   primary = '(' parse_or ')' | NUMBER | IDENT trailer
--   trailer = '(' arglist ')'   -- function call
--           | ('.' IDENT)*      -- field access chain (left-deep)
--           | (nothing)         -- a bare variable reference
--   arglist = (parse_or (',' parse_or)*)?   -- zero or more comma-separated exprs
-- An IDENT here is a Token::Ident (kind 100); the logical keywords and/or/not
-- lex as Keyword (kind 200+kw) so they never reach this path.
-- ============================================================================

-- arglist parsing — itself a recursive cons-list builder (like tokenize builds
-- TokenList). parse_args is entered at the token index of the FIRST argument
-- (just past the '('). Zero-arg case: if the very next token is ')' (op 22) the
-- list is empty and we consume the ')'. Otherwise parse one argument (parse_or,
-- LAZILY in the else branch so a non-call ident never descends here) and hand
-- it to args_cons, which decides comma-continue vs ')'-stop.
rule parse_args
  @intention: "Parse a (possibly empty) comma-separated call-argument list, consuming the ')'"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:16
  input:
    st : ParseState
  output:
    out : ParsedArgs
  logic:
    let opc = peek_op_code(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos })
    let isclose = if opc == 22 then 1 else 0
    out = if isclose == 1 then ParsedArgs::MkArgs { args: ArgList::ArgNil, next: st.pos + 1 } else args_cons(ArgConsState { toks: st.toks, first: parse_or(st) })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st.toks, st.pos, st]
      calls : [peek_op_code, parse_or, args_cons]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- args_cons: given a freshly-parsed argument (Parsed), fold it into the arg
-- cons-list. Extract the arg node + its end index, peek the next token: a ','
-- (op 11) continues — parse the REST of the list (LAZILY, in the then branch)
-- from just past the comma and prepend this arg; a ')' (op 22) stops, consuming
-- it (next = arg_end + 1); anything else stops too (missing ')' tolerated, like
-- paren_close — error recovery is a later brick), leaving next = arg_end.
rule args_cons
  @intention: "Fold one parsed argument into the cons-list, continuing on ',' or stopping on ')'"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:16
  input:
    cs : ArgConsState
  output:
    out : ParsedArgs
  logic:
    let arg_node = parsed_node(cs.first)
    let arg_next = parsed_next(cs.first)
    let opc = peek_op_code(Nth { lst: cs.toks, n: arg_next })
    let iscomma = if opc == 11 then 1 else 0
    let close_next = if opc == 22 then arg_next + 1 else arg_next
    out = if iscomma == 1 then args_prepend(ArgPrependState { head_node: arg_node, rest: parse_args(ParseState { toks: cs.toks, pos: arg_next + 1 }) }) else ParsedArgs::MkArgs { args: ArgList::ArgCons { head: arg_node, tail: ArgList::ArgNil }, next: close_next }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [cs.toks, cs.first]
      calls : [parsed_node, parsed_next, peek_op_code, args_prepend, parse_args]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- args_prepend: cons the head argument onto the front of the already-parsed
-- REST of the argument list, carrying the rest's end index through. Splitting
-- this out of args_cons keeps the recursive parse_args call lazily inside the
-- comma branch (a let would force it eagerly). Reached only from args_cons in
-- the parser cycle, so the ParsedArgs group-field input compiles natively.
rule args_prepend
  @intention: "Cons the head argument onto the front of the parsed rest of the list"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:16
  input:
    aps : ArgPrependState
  output:
    out : ParsedArgs
  logic:
    let rest_list = parsed_args_list(aps.rest)
    let rest_next = parsed_args_next(aps.rest)
    out = ParsedArgs::MkArgs { args: ArgList::ArgCons { head: aps.head_node, tail: rest_list }, next: rest_next }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [aps.head_node, aps.rest]
      calls : [parsed_args_list, parsed_args_next]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- call_build: given the callee span and the parsed argument list, build the
-- AstCall node carrying the arg cons-list and the index just past the ')'.
-- In the parser cycle (called only from parse_primary's call branch).
rule call_build
  @intention: "Build an AstCall node from the callee span and the parsed argument list"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:16
  input:
    cs : CallState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let arglist = parsed_args_list(cs.pargs)
    let argnext = parsed_args_next(cs.pargs)
    out = Parsed::Mk { node: Ast::AstCall { callee_start: cs.cstart, callee_len: cs.clen, args: arglist }, next: argnext }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [cs.cstart, cs.clen, cs.pargs]
      calls : [parsed_args_list, parsed_args_next]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- field_rest: fold a chain of '.IDENT' field accesses onto a base AST, left-deep
-- (a.b.c => AstField(AstField(AstVar(a), b), c)). Peeks the op at fs.pos: a '.'
-- (op 12) followed by an IDENT consumes both, wraps the base in AstField with
-- the field's span, and recurses with the new base at pos+2. Anything else
-- stops, returning the base unchanged at the current position. The recursion is
-- in the then branch (LAZY); each step consumes at least two tokens so pos
-- strictly grows toward Eof.
rule field_rest
  @intention: "Fold a chain of '.field' accesses onto a base, left-deep"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:16
  input:
    fs : FieldState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let opc = peek_op_code(Nth { lst: fs.toks, n: fs.pos })
    let isdot = if opc == 12 then 1 else 0
    let fstart = peek_start(Nth { lst: fs.toks, n: fs.pos + 1 })
    let flen = peek_len(Nth { lst: fs.toks, n: fs.pos + 1 })
    let isident = peek_is_ident(Nth { lst: fs.toks, n: fs.pos + 1 })
    let isfield = if isdot == 1 and isident == 1 then 1 else 0
    out = if isfield == 1 then field_rest(FieldState { toks: fs.toks, pos: fs.pos + 2, base: Ast::AstField { base: fs.base, fstart: fstart, flen: flen } }) else Parsed::Mk { node: fs.base, next: fs.pos }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [fs.toks, fs.pos, fs.base]
      calls : [peek_op_code, peek_start, peek_len, peek_is_ident, field_rest]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- if_then: the parsed condition arrives as cs.cond. Extract its node + end
-- index. The `then` keyword (kind 207) should sit at cond_next; if it does, step
-- over it (then_pos = cond_next + 1), otherwise tolerate its absence (then_pos =
-- cond_next) — error recovery is a later brick, like paren_close's missing ')'.
-- Parse the then-branch (a full parse_or) from then_pos and hand it, with the
-- cond node, to if_else. The parse_or is unconditional (a then-branch is always
-- required once we are in an if-expression) and strictly advances position.
rule if_then
  @intention: "Consume 'then' after the condition, parse the then-branch, continue to if_else"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:25
  input:
    cs : IfThenState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let cond_node = parsed_node(cs.cond)
    let cond_next = parsed_next(cs.cond)
    let knd = peek_kind(Nth { lst: cs.toks, n: cond_next })
    let then_pos = if knd == 207 then cond_next + 1 else cond_next
    out = if_else(IfElseState { toks: cs.toks, cond_node: cond_node, thn: parse_or(ParseState { toks: cs.toks, pos: then_pos }) })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [cs.toks, cs.cond]
      calls : [parsed_node, parsed_next, peek_kind, if_else, parse_or]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- if_else: the parsed then-branch arrives as cs.thn (cond node carried in
-- cs.cond_node). Extract the thn node + end index. The `else` keyword (kind 208)
-- should sit at thn_next; step over it if present (else_pos = thn_next + 1),
-- tolerate its absence otherwise. Parse the else-branch from else_pos and hand
-- it, with the cond + thn nodes, to if_build.
rule if_else
  @intention: "Consume 'else' after the then-branch, parse the else-branch, continue to if_build"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:25
  input:
    cs : IfElseState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let thn_node = parsed_node(cs.thn)
    let thn_next = parsed_next(cs.thn)
    let knd = peek_kind(Nth { lst: cs.toks, n: thn_next })
    let else_pos = if knd == 208 then thn_next + 1 else thn_next
    out = if_build(IfBuildState { cond_node: cs.cond_node, thn_node: thn_node, els: parse_or(ParseState { toks: cs.toks, pos: else_pos }) })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [cs.toks, cs.cond_node, cs.thn]
      calls : [parsed_node, parsed_next, peek_kind, if_build, parse_or]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- if_build: the parsed else-branch arrives as cs.els (cond + thn nodes carried).
-- Extract the els node + end index and assemble the AstIf node, carrying the
-- else-branch's end index as the conditional's `next`.
rule if_build
  @intention: "Assemble the AstIf node from the cond, then, and else sub-expressions"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:25
  input:
    cs : IfBuildState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let els_node = parsed_node(cs.els)
    let els_next = parsed_next(cs.els)
    out = Parsed::Mk { node: Ast::AstIf { cond: cs.cond_node, thn: cs.thn_node, els: els_node }, next: els_next }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [cs.cond_node, cs.thn_node, cs.els]
      calls : [parsed_node, parsed_next]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- primary = 'if' parse_or 'then' parse_or 'else' parse_or
--         | '(' parse_or ')' | NUMBER | IDENT trailer | <error leaf>
-- Peeks the token at pos. A '(' (op code 21 => kind 421) opens a sub-expr:
-- parse_or inside (LAZILY, only in this branch), then paren_close consumes the
-- ')'. A Num (kind 300+value) becomes an AstNum leaf consuming one token. An
-- IDENT (kind 100) takes the brick-5 trailer path: look at the NEXT token —
-- '(' (op 21) => a function call (parse_args from pos+2, build AstCall); '.'
-- (op 12) => a field-access chain (AstVar base folded by field_rest from pos+1);
-- anything else => a bare AstVar consuming one token. Any other lead token is an
-- AstErr leaf that consumes nothing (position does not advance => higher levels
-- read it as "stop").
--
-- All recursive descents (parse_or for parens, parse_args for a call) live
-- INSIDE their guarded branch so eager let evaluation never descends on the
-- wrong lead token (the loop trap). The trailer dispatch is on op codes of the
-- token at pos+1, computed up front in lets (those peeks are pure/total — they
-- only READ the token list, never recurse), but each descent stays lazy.
rule parse_primary
  @intention: "Parse a primary: parenthesized expr, number, or identifier (var / call / field)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:16
  input:
    st : ParseState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let lead_kind = peek_kind(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos })
    let isif = if lead_kind == 201 then 1 else 0
    let istrue = if lead_kind == 209 then 1 else 0
    let isfalse = if lead_kind == 210 then 1 else 0
    let isnum = peek_is_num(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos })
    let isstr = peek_is_str(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos })
    let opc = peek_op_code(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos })
    let isparen = if opc == 21 then 1 else 0
    let isident = peek_is_ident(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos })
    let numval = peek_value(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos })
    let sstart = peek_str_start(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos })
    let slen = peek_str_len(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos })
    let idstart = peek_start(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos })
    let idlen = peek_len(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos })
    let next_opc = peek_op_code(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos + 1 })
    let iscall = if next_opc == 21 then 1 else 0
    out = if isif == 1 then if_then(IfThenState { toks: st.toks, cond: parse_or(ParseState { toks: st.toks, pos: st.pos + 1 }) }) else if istrue == 1 then Parsed::Mk { node: Ast::AstBool { value: 1 }, next: st.pos + 1 } else if isfalse == 1 then Parsed::Mk { node: Ast::AstBool { value: 0 }, next: st.pos + 1 } else if isnum == 1 then Parsed::Mk { node: Ast::AstNum { value: numval }, next: st.pos + 1 } else if isstr == 1 then Parsed::Mk { node: Ast::AstStr { start: sstart, len: slen }, next: st.pos + 1 } else if isparen == 1 then paren_close(ParenState { toks: st.toks, inner: parse_or(ParseState { toks: st.toks, pos: st.pos + 1 }) }) else if isident == 1 then (if iscall == 1 then call_build(CallState { toks: st.toks, cstart: idstart, clen: idlen, pargs: parse_args(ParseState { toks: st.toks, pos: st.pos + 2 }) }) else field_rest(FieldState { toks: st.toks, pos: st.pos + 1, base: Ast::AstVar { start: idstart, len: idlen } })) else Parsed::Mk { node: Ast::AstErr, next: st.pos }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st.toks, st.pos]
      calls : [peek_kind, peek_is_num, peek_is_str, peek_op_code, peek_is_ident, peek_value, peek_str_start, peek_str_len, peek_start, peek_len, if_then, paren_close, parse_or, call_build, parse_args, field_rest]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- unary = ('not' | '-') unary | primary
-- A prefix-unary level sitting between mul and primary. Peeks the token at pos:
-- a 'not' keyword (kind 206) wraps the rest in AstNot; a '-' operator (op 14,
-- kind 414) in OPERAND position wraps it in AstNeg; otherwise it is a primary.
-- Right-recursive (not not 0, - -3 both parse): the inner parse_unary call lives
-- INSIDE the matched branch (LAZY), so on a non-prefix token no descent fires.
-- A unary node consumes the prefix token (pos + 1) then whatever its operand
-- consumed; the Parsed.next from the inner operand is the node's next.
rule parse_unary
  @intention: "Parse a prefix-unary expression: not / negation, else a primary"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:18
  input:
    st : ParseState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let knd = peek_kind(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos })
    let opc = peek_op_code(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos })
    let isnot = if knd == 206 then 1 else 0
    let isneg = if opc == 14 then 1 else 0
    out = if isnot == 1 then unary_wrap(WrapState { toks: st.toks, isnot: 1, inner: parse_unary(ParseState { toks: st.toks, pos: st.pos + 1 }) }) else if isneg == 1 then unary_wrap(WrapState { toks: st.toks, isnot: 0, inner: parse_unary(ParseState { toks: st.toks, pos: st.pos + 1 }) }) else parse_primary(st)
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st.toks, st.pos, st]
      calls : [peek_kind, peek_op_code, unary_wrap, parse_unary, parse_primary]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- unary_wrap: given a parsed inner operand and which prefix it was, build the
-- AstNot or AstNeg node carrying the operand's `next` index unchanged (the
-- prefix token was already stepped over by parse_unary at pos + 1). Lives in the
-- parser cycle (called only from parse_unary), so the Parsed group-field input
-- compiles natively.
rule unary_wrap
  @intention: "Wrap a parsed operand in AstNot or AstNeg, keeping its end index"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:18
  input:
    ws : WrapState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let inner_node = parsed_node(ws.inner)
    let inner_next = parsed_next(ws.inner)
    out = if ws.isnot == 1 then Parsed::Mk { node: Ast::AstNot { inner: inner_node }, next: inner_next } else Parsed::Mk { node: Ast::AstNeg { inner: inner_node }, next: inner_next }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [ws.isnot, ws.inner]
      calls : [parsed_node, parsed_next]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- mul_join: fold one * or / step. Given the parsed right primary, build
-- AstBin(op, acc, rhs) — acc on the LEFT for left-associativity — and continue
-- folding from just past the right operand via mul_rest.
rule mul_join
  @intention: "Fold one multiplicative step then continue the fold"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:17
  input:
    js : JoinState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let rhs_node = parsed_node(js.rhs)
    let rhs_next = parsed_next(js.rhs)
    out = mul_rest(FoldState { toks: js.toks, pos: rhs_next, acc: Ast::AstBin { op: js.opcode, lhs: js.acc, rhs: rhs_node } })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [js.toks, js.acc, js.opcode, js.rhs]
      calls : [parsed_node, parsed_next, mul_rest]
    termination:
      bound : 512
-- (mul_join now folds onto a unary operand; see parse_mul / mul_rest below.)


-- mul_rest: left-associative fold of ('*' | '/' | '%') unary onto an accumulator.
-- Peeks the op at fs.pos. If it is '*' (15), '/' (16), or '%' (17), parse the
-- next unary operand (LAZILY, in the then-branch) and hand it to mul_join.
-- Otherwise return the accumulator unchanged at the current position.
rule mul_rest
  @intention: "Fold *, /, and % onto the accumulator, left-associatively"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:17
  input:
    fs : FoldState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let opcode = peek_op_code(Nth { lst: fs.toks, n: fs.pos })
    let ismul = if opcode == 15 or (opcode == 16 or opcode == 17) then 1 else 0
    out = if ismul == 1 then mul_join(JoinState { toks: fs.toks, acc: fs.acc, opcode: opcode, rhs: parse_unary(ParseState { toks: fs.toks, pos: fs.pos + 1 }) }) else Parsed::Mk { node: fs.acc, next: fs.pos }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [fs.toks, fs.pos, fs.acc]
      calls : [peek_op_code, mul_join, parse_unary]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- mul_expr = unary (('*' | '/' | '%') unary)*
-- Parse the first unary operand, then fold the rest via mul_rest with that
-- operand as the initial accumulator. The first descent is unconditional (an
-- operand is always required) and bounded.
rule parse_mul
  @intention: "Parse a multiplicative expression (*, /, %, left-associative)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:18
  input:
    st : ParseState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let first = parse_unary(st)
    let first_node = parsed_node(first)
    let first_next = parsed_next(first)
    out = mul_rest(FoldState { toks: st.toks, pos: first_next, acc: first_node })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st, st.toks]
      calls : [parse_unary, mul_rest, parsed_node, parsed_next]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- add_join: fold one + or - step. Given the parsed right mul_expr, build
-- AstBin(op, acc, rhs) — acc on the LEFT — and continue folding via add_rest.
rule add_join
  @intention: "Fold one additive step then continue the fold"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:19
  input:
    js : JoinState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let rhs_node = parsed_node(js.rhs)
    let rhs_next = parsed_next(js.rhs)
    out = add_rest(FoldState { toks: js.toks, pos: rhs_next, acc: Ast::AstBin { op: js.opcode, lhs: js.acc, rhs: rhs_node } })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [js.toks, js.acc, js.opcode, js.rhs]
      calls : [parsed_node, parsed_next, add_rest]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- add_rest: left-associative fold of ('+' | '-') mul_expr onto an accumulator.
-- Symmetric to mul_rest but for '+' (kind 413) and '-' (kind 414); the next
-- operand is a full mul_expr (so * / bind tighter). The descent is LAZY (in the
-- then-branch) and handed to add_join.
rule add_rest
  @intention: "Fold + and - onto the accumulator, left-associatively"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:19
  input:
    fs : FoldState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let opcode = peek_op_code(Nth { lst: fs.toks, n: fs.pos })
    let isadd = if opcode == 13 or opcode == 14 then 1 else 0
    out = if isadd == 1 then add_join(JoinState { toks: fs.toks, acc: fs.acc, opcode: opcode, rhs: parse_mul(ParseState { toks: fs.toks, pos: fs.pos + 1 }) }) else Parsed::Mk { node: fs.acc, next: fs.pos }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [fs.toks, fs.pos, fs.acc]
      calls : [peek_op_code, add_join, parse_mul]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- add_expr = mul_expr (('+' | '-') mul_expr)*
-- The top of the precedence ladder. Parse the first mul_expr, then fold the
-- rest via add_rest.
rule parse_add
  @intention: "Parse an additive expression (+ and -, left-associative)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:20
  input:
    st : ParseState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let first = parse_mul(st)
    let first_node = parsed_node(first)
    let first_next = parsed_next(first)
    out = add_rest(FoldState { toks: st.toks, pos: first_next, acc: first_node })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st, st.toks]
      calls : [parse_mul, add_rest, parsed_node, parsed_next]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- ============================================================================
-- cmp_expr = add_expr (('==' | '!=' | '<' | '>' | '<=' | '>=') add_expr)?
-- A comparison binds looser than +/- and is NON-associative: at most ONE
-- comparison operator (so `1 < 2 < 3` does not chain — the trailing `< 3` is
-- left for a higher level to reject/stop on, matching most languages and
-- src/parser.rs's single-comparison rule). The AST op-code IS the tokenizer
-- op_code (== =1, >= =4, <= =5, != =6, < =19, > =20), all disjoint from the
-- arithmetic and logical bands.
--
-- cmp_join folds the single comparison: build AstBin(op, lhs, rhs) and STOP
-- (return at the rhs end index — no further comparison consumed). The rhs
-- descent is LAZY (inside the matched branch) and handed to cmp_join, keeping it
-- in the recursion cycle so the Parsed group-field input compiles natively.
rule cmp_join
  @intention: "Fold the single comparison step (non-associative, stops after one)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:19
  input:
    js : JoinState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let rhs_node = parsed_node(js.rhs)
    let rhs_next = parsed_next(js.rhs)
    out = Parsed::Mk { node: Ast::AstBin { op: js.opcode, lhs: js.acc, rhs: rhs_node }, next: rhs_next }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [js.acc, js.opcode, js.rhs]
      calls : [parsed_node, parsed_next]
    termination:
      bound : 512


rule parse_cmp
  @intention: "Parse a comparison: an additive expr, optionally one compare op + additive expr"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:19
  input:
    st : ParseState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let lhs = parse_add(st)
    let lhs_node = parsed_node(lhs)
    let lhs_next = parsed_next(lhs)
    let opcode = peek_op_code(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: lhs_next })
    let iscmp = if opcode == 1 or (opcode == 4 or (opcode == 5 or (opcode == 6 or (opcode == 19 or opcode == 20)))) then 1 else 0
    out = if iscmp == 1 then cmp_join(JoinState { toks: st.toks, acc: lhs_node, opcode: opcode, rhs: parse_add(ParseState { toks: st.toks, pos: lhs_next + 1 }) }) else Parsed::Mk { node: lhs_node, next: lhs_next }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st, st.toks]
      calls : [parse_add, parsed_node, parsed_next, peek_op_code, cmp_join]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- ============================================================================
-- and_expr = cmp_expr ('and' cmp_expr)*    left-associative, keyword 'and'.
-- The `and` keyword lexes as Token::Keyword(kw=5) -> kind 205. and_rest peeks
-- the kind (NOT an op code) at fs.pos; on 205 it parses the next cmp_expr
-- (LAZILY, in the then-branch) and folds AstBin(30, acc, rhs) left-associatively
-- via and_join. AST op-code 30 is dedicated to `and` (disjoint from all others).
-- ============================================================================
rule and_join
  @intention: "Fold one 'and' step then continue the fold"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:20
  input:
    js : JoinState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let rhs_node = parsed_node(js.rhs)
    let rhs_next = parsed_next(js.rhs)
    out = and_rest(FoldState { toks: js.toks, pos: rhs_next, acc: Ast::AstBin { op: 30, lhs: js.acc, rhs: rhs_node } })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [js.toks, js.acc, js.rhs]
      calls : [parsed_node, parsed_next, and_rest]
    termination:
      bound : 512


rule and_rest
  @intention: "Fold 'and' onto the accumulator, left-associatively"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:20
  input:
    fs : FoldState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let knd = peek_kind(Nth { lst: fs.toks, n: fs.pos })
    let isand = if knd == 205 then 1 else 0
    out = if isand == 1 then and_join(JoinState { toks: fs.toks, acc: fs.acc, opcode: 30, rhs: parse_cmp(ParseState { toks: fs.toks, pos: fs.pos + 1 }) }) else Parsed::Mk { node: fs.acc, next: fs.pos }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [fs.toks, fs.pos, fs.acc]
      calls : [peek_kind, and_join, parse_cmp]
    termination:
      bound : 512


rule parse_and
  @intention: "Parse an 'and' expression: a comparison followed by any number of 'and's"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:20
  input:
    st : ParseState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let first = parse_cmp(st)
    let first_node = parsed_node(first)
    let first_next = parsed_next(first)
    out = and_rest(FoldState { toks: st.toks, pos: first_next, acc: first_node })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st, st.toks]
      calls : [parse_cmp, and_rest, parsed_node, parsed_next]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- ============================================================================
-- or_expr = and_expr ('or' and_expr)*    left-associative, keyword 'or'.
-- The `or` keyword lexes as Token::Keyword(kw=2) -> kind 202. or_rest peeks the
-- kind at fs.pos; on 202 it parses the next and_expr (LAZILY) and folds
-- AstBin(31, acc, rhs) via or_join. AST op-code 31 is dedicated to `or`.
-- parse_or is the TOP of the ladder (the entry point for any sub-expression,
-- including the one inside parentheses).
-- ============================================================================
rule or_join
  @intention: "Fold one 'or' step then continue the fold"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:21
  input:
    js : JoinState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let rhs_node = parsed_node(js.rhs)
    let rhs_next = parsed_next(js.rhs)
    out = or_rest(FoldState { toks: js.toks, pos: rhs_next, acc: Ast::AstBin { op: 31, lhs: js.acc, rhs: rhs_node } })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [js.toks, js.acc, js.rhs]
      calls : [parsed_node, parsed_next, or_rest]
    termination:
      bound : 512


rule or_rest
  @intention: "Fold 'or' onto the accumulator, left-associatively"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:21
  input:
    fs : FoldState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let knd = peek_kind(Nth { lst: fs.toks, n: fs.pos })
    let isor = if knd == 202 then 1 else 0
    out = if isor == 1 then or_join(JoinState { toks: fs.toks, acc: fs.acc, opcode: 31, rhs: parse_and(ParseState { toks: fs.toks, pos: fs.pos + 1 }) }) else Parsed::Mk { node: fs.acc, next: fs.pos }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [fs.toks, fs.pos, fs.acc]
      calls : [peek_kind, or_join, parse_and]
    termination:
      bound : 512


rule parse_or
  @intention: "Parse the full expression: an 'and' expr followed by any number of 'or's"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:21
  input:
    st : ParseState
  output:
    out : Parsed
  logic:
    let first = parse_and(st)
    let first_node = parsed_node(first)
    let first_next = parsed_next(first)
    out = or_rest(FoldState { toks: st.toks, pos: first_next, acc: first_node })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st, st.toks]
      calls : [parse_and, or_rest, parsed_node, parsed_next]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- ============================================================================
-- EVALUATOR. Recursive walk over the Ast group, computing the number.
-- AstBin dispatches on the operator code (13=+, 14=-, 15=*, 16=/). Verbose
-- itself has NO operator precedence, so every non-leftmost product in this
-- body is parenthesized — note: that is the LANGUAGE's left-to-right rule, a
-- different level entirely from the precedence this program PARSES.
-- ============================================================================
rule eval_ast
  @intention: "Evaluate an arithmetic AST to a number"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:21
  input:
    e : Ast
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match e:
      AstNum(value) => value
      AstBin(op, lhs, rhs) => if op == 13 then eval_ast(lhs) + eval_ast(rhs) else if op == 14 then eval_ast(lhs) - eval_ast(rhs) else if op == 15 then eval_ast(lhs) * eval_ast(rhs) else if op == 16 then eval_ast(lhs) / eval_ast(rhs) else if op == 17 then eval_ast(lhs) % eval_ast(rhs) else if op == 1 then (if eval_ast(lhs) == eval_ast(rhs) then 1 else 0) else if op == 6 then (if eval_ast(lhs) != eval_ast(rhs) then 1 else 0) else if op == 19 then (if eval_ast(lhs) < eval_ast(rhs) then 1 else 0) else if op == 20 then (if eval_ast(lhs) > eval_ast(rhs) then 1 else 0) else if op == 5 then (if eval_ast(lhs) <= eval_ast(rhs) then 1 else 0) else if op == 4 then (if eval_ast(lhs) >= eval_ast(rhs) then 1 else 0) else if op == 30 then (if eval_ast(lhs) != 0 and eval_ast(rhs) != 0 then 1 else 0) else if op == 31 then (if eval_ast(lhs) != 0 or eval_ast(rhs) != 0 then 1 else 0) else 0
      AstNeg(inner) => 0 - eval_ast(inner)
      AstNot(inner) => if eval_ast(inner) == 0 then 1 else 0
      -- Brick 5's variable / field / call nodes have NO numeric value without an
      -- environment to resolve names; they are out of the arithmetic evaluator's
      -- scope and evaluate to 0. (Brick 5's correctness is proven by `shape`, the
      -- STRUCTURAL signature walk below — not by eval_ast.) eval_ast stays the
      -- brick-3/4 evaluator for variable-free expressions: 2+3*4 = 14 still.
      AstVar(start, len) => 0
      AstField(base, fstart, flen) => 0
      AstCall(callee_start, callee_len, args) => 0
      -- The language's lazy if: cond is evaluated, then ONLY the selected
      -- branch's eval_ast runs — the dead branch is never walked. Truthiness is
      -- "non-zero is true" (matching AstNot / and / or above).
      AstIf(cond, thn, els) => if eval_ast(cond) != 0 then eval_ast(thn) else eval_ast(els)
      -- A boolean literal carries its arithmetic value directly (true -> 1,
      -- false -> 0), so it participates in and / or / not / comparisons as a 1/0
      -- number would. (Brick 7.)
      AstBool(value) => value
      -- A string literal has no arithmetic value without an environment to decode
      -- its bytes; like AstVar / AstCall / AstField it is out of the arithmetic
      -- evaluator's scope and evaluates to 0. Its correctness is proven
      -- STRUCTURALLY by shape_ast. (Brick 7.)
      AstStr(start, len) => 0
      AstErr => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [e]
      calls : [eval_ast]
    termination:
      bound : 4000
      structural : e


-- ============================================================================
-- STRUCTURAL SIGNATURE (the brick-5 oracle). Unlike bricks 3/4, a variable /
-- call / field node has no numeric value (no environment), so brick 5's parser
-- is validated by the SHAPE of the AST it builds, not by an evaluated number.
--
-- shape_ast walks the tree and returns a signature that counts node kinds:
--
--   10000000 * (#AstStr) + 1000000 * (#AstBool) + 100000 * (#AstIf)
--     + 10000 * (#AstCall) + 1000 * (#AstField) + 100 * (#AstVar)
--     + 10 * (#AstBin) + (#AstNot + #AstNeg)
--
-- The count bands are spaced by powers of ten wide enough that no test input
-- overflows a lower band into a higher one (the deepest test has at most a
-- handful of each kind). AstNum and AstErr contribute 0 — they are not part of
-- the brick-5/7 surface being proven by shape. Each test input's signature is
-- hand-derivable and distinct, so a single number certifies the exact shape.
-- Brick 7 added the two top bands: AstBool (1000000) and AstStr (10000000).
--
-- shape_ast and shape_args are mutually recursive (a call's signature includes
-- its arguments' signatures). Both walk a strictly-shrinking group value at
-- every recursive step (a sub-Ast or the tail ArgList), so they declare the
-- structural termination proof — same posture as eval_ast.
-- ============================================================================
rule shape_args
  @intention: "Sum the structural signatures of every argument in a call-argument list"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:23
  input:
    a : ArgList
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match a:
      ArgCons(head, tail) => shape_ast(head) + shape_args(tail)
      ArgNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a]
      calls : [shape_ast, shape_args]
    termination:
      bound : 4000
      structural : a


rule shape_ast
  @intention: "Structural signature of an AST: a kind-count fingerprint of its shape"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:23
  input:
    e : Ast
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match e:
      AstNum(value) => 0
      AstBin(op, lhs, rhs) => 10 + shape_ast(lhs) + shape_ast(rhs)
      AstNeg(inner) => 1 + shape_ast(inner)
      AstNot(inner) => 1 + shape_ast(inner)
      AstVar(start, len) => 100
      AstField(base, fstart, flen) => 1000 + shape_ast(base)
      AstCall(callee_start, callee_len, args) => 10000 + shape_args(args)
      -- An AstIf contributes a dedicated top band (100000) plus the signatures of
      -- its three sub-expressions, so a conditional's shape is hand-derivable and
      -- distinct from every other kind. (Brick 6.)
      AstIf(cond, thn, els) => 100000 + shape_ast(cond) + shape_ast(thn) + shape_ast(els)
      -- Brick 7's literals each get a dedicated band ABOVE AstIf's 100000, so a
      -- bool or string node is countable and distinct from every other kind:
      -- AstBool adds 1000000, AstStr adds 10000000. (A bool/string leaf has no
      -- sub-expressions, so neither recurses.)
      AstBool(value) => 1000000
      AstStr(start, len) => 10000000
      AstErr => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [e]
      calls : [shape_ast, shape_args]
    termination:
      bound : 4000
      structural : e


-- shape: the brick-5 driver. Tokenize the source, parse the full expression
-- from index 0, and return the STRUCTURAL signature of the resulting AST. This
-- is the observable that proves f(x, y) builds an AstCall with a 2-element
-- ArgList and a.b.c builds nested AstField — by a number we can predict by hand.
rule shape
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, and return the AST's structural signature"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:23
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let parsed = parse_or(ParseState { toks: toks, pos: 0 })
    let root = parsed_node(parsed)
    out = shape_ast(root)
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [tokenize, parse_or, shape_ast, parsed_node]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- DRIVER (observable, end-to-end): text -> tokens -> AST -> value.
-- Tokenize the source, parse an add_expr from index 0, evaluate the AST.
-- This is the money shot: eval_expr("2+3*4") must be 14 (precedence!), NOT 20.
-- Entry rule takes a TEXT input (ScanState), so argv can supply it — the
-- group-field parse rules are reached internally, never as _start's input.
-- ============================================================================
rule eval_expr
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse with precedence, and evaluate an arithmetic expression"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:22
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let parsed = parse_or(ParseState { toks: toks, pos: 0 })
    let root = parsed_node(parsed)
    out = eval_ast(root)
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [tokenize, parse_or, eval_ast, parsed_node]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 8a VALIDATION DRIVERS (structural — multi-line eval is not meaningful
-- yet, so these certify the token STREAM shape, like brick 7's shape_ast).
--
-- count_cells walks the materialized TokenList and counts every cons cell —
-- including the Newline cells brick 8a now emits and the trailing Eof cell. The
-- count is a single number predictable by hand for each multi-line source, so
-- it certifies "the tokenizer traversed every line and emitted a Newline at each
-- line boundary" without needing to evaluate anything.
--
-- Trailing-Eof convention (stated): tokenize always appends ONE Cons{Eof, Nil}
-- at end of source (brick 2's convention, unchanged). So an N-real-token source
-- with K newlines produces N + K + 1 cells: N lexeme cells + K Newline cells +
-- 1 trailing Eof cell. Blank lines contribute an extra Newline cell each (8a
-- emits newlines faithfully; collapsing blanks is brick 8b).
-- ============================================================================

-- 1 iff the token IS a Newline, structurally (brick 8a). Mirrors tok_is_str /
-- tok_is_num: a magnitude test on tok_kind (== 600) would misread a Num literal
-- whose value is 300 (kind 600), so the position check uses this structural test.
rule tok_is_newline
  @intention: "1 if the token is a line-boundary Newline, 0 otherwise (value-independent)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:26
  input:
    t : Token
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match t:
      Ident(start, len) => 0
      Keyword(start, len, kw) => 0
      Num(value, len) => 0
      Op(code, len) => 0
      Str(start, len) => 0
      Newline(pos) => 1
      Indent => 0
      Dedent => 0
      IndentErr(pos) => 0
      Eof => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [t]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Count every cons cell of a token list (lexeme cells + Newline cells + the
-- trailing Eof cell). Walks a strictly-shrinking group value (the tail) at each
-- step, so it declares the structural termination proof — same posture as
-- shape_ast / eval_ast.
rule count_cells
  @intention: "Number of cons cells in a token list (every token incl. Newline and trailing Eof)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:26
  input:
    lst : TokenList
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match lst:
      Cons(head, tail) => 1 + count_cells(tail)
      Nil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [lst]
      calls : [count_cells]
    termination:
      bound : 4000
      structural : lst


-- An entry concept carrying a source text plus a token index, so a single-input
-- entry rule can tokenize then peek the kind of the token at that index.
concept KindAtState
  @intention: "Source text plus a token index to peek the kind of"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:26
  fields:
    source : text [..256]
    idx : number [0, 512]


-- Entry driver: tokenize the source (from argv) and return the KIND code of the
-- token at index `arg.idx` (Eof=0, Ident=100, Keyword=200+kw, Num=300+value,
-- Op=400+code, Str=500, Newline=600). Confirms the Newline appears at the right
-- position in the stream: kind_at("a\nb", 1) = 600. Native-only for newline
-- sources (same JSON \n limit as count_cells_src).
rule kind_at
  @intention: "Tokenize a source and return the kind code of the token at the given index"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:26
  input:
    arg : KindAtState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = tokenize(ScanState { source: arg.source, pos: 0 })
    out = peek_kind(Nth { lst: toks, n: arg.idx })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [arg.source, arg.idx]
      calls : [tokenize, peek_kind]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 8b: INDENT / DEDENT via a column stack (design (a), docs/indent-dedent-
-- design.md). Turns the flat-plus-Newline stream of brick 8a into a block-
-- structured stream by weaving Indent / Dedent tokens at line starts, driven by
-- a column stack (ColStack) threaded alongside the output token list through a
-- line-by-line driver recursion. Mirrors src/lexer.rs::handle_line_start +
-- tokenize one-to-one. The two errors the reference returns as a LexError
-- (tab-in-indent, inconsistent indentation) become Token::IndentErr in the
-- stream, because a Verbose rule is TOTAL (cannot abort mid-evaluation).
--
-- Faithful simplifications vs the reference (documented, not silent):
--  * BLANK lines (whitespace only, to the newline or EOF) are SKIPPED entirely
--    — no Indent/Dedent and no Newline. They carry no block structure; the
--    reference's main loop would emit a Newline for them but suppresses it after
--    a prior Newline. Skipping keeps the observable hand-derivable (test 7).
--  * The TAB sentinel (line_width returns 99999 on a tab in leading whitespace)
--    is well above any real width (source is <= 256 bytes), so it never aliases
--    a genuine indentation level.
-- ============================================================================

-- line_width: from a line-start position `pos`, count consecutive leading
-- spaces (byte 32). If a TAB (byte 9) appears in the leading whitespace, return
-- the sentinel 99999 (> any real width, since source <= 256) so the driver can
-- turn it into a Token::IndentErr — the faithful translation of src/lexer.rs's
-- tab rejection (:193-199). byte_at is fail-closed OOB, so at end-of-source the
-- count so far is returned. Termination: pos strictly increases toward len.
rule line_width
  @intention: "Count leading spaces at a line start; 99999 sentinel if a tab is seen"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let len = length(s.source)
    out = if s.pos >= len then 0 else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 9 then 99999 else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 32 then 1 + line_width(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: s.pos + 1 }) else 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : [line_width]
    termination:
      bound : 256
      increasing : pos


-- next_line_start: from anywhere on a line, scan forward to the byte AFTER the
-- next newline (byte 10), or to length(source) at end-of-source. This is how the
-- driver steps from one line to the next — it replaces the brick-2 scanner's
-- "a newline stops tokenize" behaviour. Termination: pos strictly increases.
rule next_line_start
  @intention: "Index just past the next newline, or end-of-source"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let len = length(s.source)
    out = if s.pos >= len then len else if byte_at(s.source, s.pos) == 10 then s.pos + 1 else next_line_start(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: s.pos + 1 })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : [next_line_start]
    termination:
      bound : 256
      increasing : pos


-- top_width: the head width of the column stack (0 for Empty, the column-0
-- sentinel). Trivial match — no recursion.
rule top_width
  @intention: "Head width of the column stack (0 for the Empty sentinel)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    cs : ColStack
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match cs:
      Push(width, rest) => width
      Empty => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [cs]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- A multi-DEDENT pop argument: the column stack and the target width.
concept PopArg
  @intention: "Column stack + the line's width to pop down to"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  fields:
    stk : ColStack
    width : number [0, 100000]


-- dedents_to: the multi-DEDENT recursion (src/lexer.rs:223-236). Pop every level
-- whose width is STRICTLY GREATER than the target `width`, counting one Dedent
-- per pop. Stops when the top width is <= the target (or the stack is the Empty
-- sentinel). Returns the popped stack, the pop count, AND an inconsistency flag:
-- err = 1 iff after popping the new top width does NOT exactly equal the target
-- (the line's width matches no enclosing block). The sentinel Empty has width 0,
-- so a target of 0 pops everything and lands exactly (err = 0). Termination: the
-- ColStack strictly shrinks (one Push removed per recursive step), so it is a
-- structural recursion on `stk`.
rule dedents_to
  @intention: "Pop the column stack down to a width, returning new stack + dedent count + inconsistency flag"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    pa : PopArg
  output:
    out : DedentResult
  logic:
    out = match pa.stk:
      Push(width, rest) => if width > pa.width then dedent_bump(dedents_to(PopArg { stk: rest, width: pa.width })) else (if width == pa.width then DedentResult::MkDed { popped: pa.stk, count: 0, err: 0 } else DedentResult::MkDed { popped: pa.stk, count: 0, err: 1 })
      Empty => if pa.width == 0 then DedentResult::MkDed { popped: ColStack::Empty, count: 0, err: 0 } else DedentResult::MkDed { popped: ColStack::Empty, count: 0, err: 1 }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [pa.stk, pa.width]
      calls : [dedents_to, dedent_bump]
    termination:
      bound : 4096


-- dedent_bump: add one to the pop count of a DedentResult, carrying the popped
-- stack and the err flag through unchanged. Used by dedents_to to fold "+1
-- Dedent" onto the result of the deeper pop. A trivial wrapper so dedents_to's
-- recursive arm stays a single constructor expression.
rule dedent_bump
  @intention: "Increment a DedentResult's pop count by one (stack + err unchanged)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    dr : DedentResult
  output:
    out : DedentResult
  logic:
    out = match dr:
      MkDed(popped, count, err) => DedentResult::MkDed { popped: popped, count: count + 1, err: err }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [dr]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Accessors for a DedentResult. A block-form `match` is only legal in the FINAL
-- `out = match ...` position (not as a `let` RHS, and a sum-typed value cannot be
-- field-accessed with `.field`), so destructuring a DedentResult is factored into
-- these three tiny rules — exactly the parsed_node / parsed_next pattern.
rule dr_popped
  @intention: "The popped column stack from a DedentResult"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    dr : DedentResult
  output:
    out : ColStack
  logic:
    out = match dr:
      MkDed(popped, count, err) => popped
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [dr]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


rule dr_count
  @intention: "The dedent count from a DedentResult"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    dr : DedentResult
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match dr:
      MkDed(popped, count, err) => count
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [dr]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


rule dr_err
  @intention: "The inconsistency flag from a DedentResult"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    dr : DedentResult
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match dr:
      MkDed(popped, count, err) => err
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [dr]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- A cons-dedents argument: how many Dedent tokens to prepend, and the tail list
-- they prepend onto (the already-built continuation).
concept ConsDedArg
  @intention: "A dedent count plus the tail list to prepend the Dedent tokens onto"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  fields:
    count : number [0, 4096]
    tail : TokenList


-- cons_dedents: prepend `count` Token::Dedent cells onto the front of `tail`.
-- The tail is the already-computed continuation (the rest of the stream); each
-- recursive step conses ONE Dedent and decrements the count, so the result is
-- count Dedents followed by tail. Termination: count strictly decreases.
rule cons_dedents
  @intention: "Prepend `count` Dedent tokens onto a tail token list"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    cda : ConsDedArg
  output:
    out : TokenList
  logic:
    out = if cda.count <= 0 then cda.tail else TokenList::Cons { head: Token::Dedent, tail: cons_dedents(ConsDedArg { count: cda.count - 1, tail: cda.tail }) }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [cda.count, cda.tail]
      calls : [cons_dedents]
    termination:
      bound : 4096
      decreasing : count


-- tokenize_line: tokenize ONE line's lexemes, starting at `pos`, stopping at (and
-- NOT consuming) the line's newline (byte 10) or end-of-source. Returns a
-- Nil-terminated list of the line's lexeme tokens — no Newline, no Eof. This is
-- brick 2's `tokenize` bounded to a single line: it conses next_token / advances
-- by token_end exactly as `tokenize` does, but the stop condition is "reached a
-- newline or end-of-source" instead of "reached end-of-source". A Newline token
-- is never produced here (the driver conses the line's Newline itself); if the
-- next lexeme would be a Newline we stop. Termination: pos strictly advances by
-- at least one byte each step (endp > p), bounded by source length.
rule tokenize_line
  @intention: "Tokenize one line's lexemes up to (not including) its newline; Nil-terminated"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : TokenList
  logic:
    let len = length(s.source)
    let p = skip_spaces(s)
    let endp = token_end(s)
    let atnl = if p >= len then 1 else if byte_at(s.source, p) == 10 then 1 else 0
    out = if atnl == 1 then TokenList::Nil else if endp <= p then TokenList::Nil else TokenList::Cons { head: next_token(s), tail: tokenize_line(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: endp }) }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s]
      calls : [skip_spaces, token_end, next_token, tokenize_line]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- An append argument: a front list and a back list to append onto it.
concept AppendArg
  @intention: "A front token list and a back token list to append onto its end"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  fields:
    front : TokenList
    back : TokenList


-- append_toks: append `back` onto the end of `front`, returning front ++ back.
-- Walks `front` to its Nil and splices `back` there. Used by the driver to put a
-- line's lexeme list (front) in front of the continuation (back = Newline + the
-- rest of the stream). Termination: structural recursion on `front`.
rule append_toks
  @intention: "Append the back token list onto the end of the front token list"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    aa : AppendArg
  output:
    out : TokenList
  logic:
    out = match aa.front:
      Cons(head, tail) => TokenList::Cons { head: head, tail: append_toks(AppendArg { front: tail, back: aa.back }) }
      Nil => aa.back
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [aa.front, aa.back]
      calls : [append_toks]
    termination:
      bound : 65535


-- The line-driver state: the source text, the column stack, and the current
-- byte position (always a LINE START by invariant). Two group-concept fields
-- (ColStack, and the output is built as the return value so it is NOT a field —
-- the driver returns a TokenList and threads the stack forward). Note: unlike
-- the design note's first sketch, the output list is the RETURN value (built
-- front-to-back, like brick 2's tokenize), so the state carries only ONE group
-- field (the stack) plus the text and position. This still exercises the
-- text + group-field recursive ABI (text input in a recursive callable, PR #52,
-- composed with a group-concept field).
concept LineState
  @intention: "Line driver state: source text + column stack + line-start position"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  fields:
    src : text [..256]
    stack : ColStack
    pos : number [0, 256]


-- tokenize_indent: THE line driver. Processes the source line by line from a
-- line-start `pos`, threading the column stack, and returns the full block-
-- structured token stream (Indent/Dedent/Newline woven in, trailing Eof).
--
-- At each line start:
--  * EOF (pos >= len): flush a Dedent per still-open level (dedents_to to width
--    0 pops every Push), then cons the trailing Eof. This is src/lexer.rs's EOF
--    flush (:176-179).
--  * TAB in indent (width == 99999): cons a Token::IndentErr, then skip the rest
--    of this line and continue at the next line with the stack UNCHANGED (the
--    error token is the hard-stop signal for the downstream parser).
--  * BLANK line (content start at newline or EOF): skip entirely — recurse to the
--    next line with no structural token (documented simplification).
--  * width > top: ONE Indent, push width, then the line's lexemes + Newline +
--    recurse with the deeper stack.
--  * width < top: dedents_to pops to width; cons that many Dedents; if the pop
--    landed inconsistently (err == 1) weave a Token::IndentErr; then the line's
--    lexemes + Newline + recurse with the popped stack.
--  * width == top: no structural token; the line's lexemes + Newline + recurse.
--
-- LAZINESS: every recursive call to tokenize_indent sits inside an if-branch (or
-- as a constructor/call arg reached only within a branch), NEVER in a `let`, so
-- the forward recursion fires only along the taken path and pos strictly advances
-- to next_line_start each step (the eager-let trap, vexprparse.verbose:1198-1210).
-- Termination: bound-only + the mandatory recursion breadcrumb (a line scanner
-- has no structural/decreasing field that fits — the backstop is the finite
-- source length: pos advances to next_line_start, strictly greater, each step).
rule tokenize_indent
  @intention: "Line-by-line driver: weave Indent/Dedent/Newline into the token stream"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    ls : LineState
  output:
    out : TokenList
  logic:
    let len = length(ls.src)
    let width = line_width(ScanState { source: ls.src, pos: ls.pos })
    let cstart = ls.pos + width
    let nls = next_line_start(ScanState { source: ls.src, pos: ls.pos })
    let tw = top_width(ls.stack)
    let istab = if width == 99999 then 1 else 0
    let isblank = if istab == 1 then 0 else if cstart >= len then 1 else if byte_at(ls.src, cstart) == 10 then 1 else 0
    let dr = dedents_to(PopArg { stk: ls.stack, width: width })
    let dr_c = dr_count(dr)
    let dr_e = dr_err(dr)
    let dr_p = dr_popped(dr)
    let flush_c = dr_count(dedents_to(PopArg { stk: ls.stack, width: 0 }))
    out = if ls.pos >= len then cons_dedents(ConsDedArg { count: flush_c, tail: TokenList::Cons { head: Token::Eof, tail: TokenList::Nil } }) else if istab == 1 then TokenList::Cons { head: Token::IndentErr { pos: ls.pos }, tail: tokenize_indent(LineState { src: ls.src, stack: ls.stack, pos: nls }) } else if isblank == 1 then tokenize_indent(LineState { src: ls.src, stack: ls.stack, pos: nls }) else if width > tw then TokenList::Cons { head: Token::Indent, tail: append_toks(AppendArg { front: tokenize_line(ScanState { source: ls.src, pos: cstart }), back: TokenList::Cons { head: Token::Newline { pos: nls }, tail: tokenize_indent(LineState { src: ls.src, stack: ColStack::Push { width: width, rest: ls.stack }, pos: nls }) } }) } else if width < tw then cons_dedents(ConsDedArg { count: dr_c, tail: (if dr_e == 1 then TokenList::Cons { head: Token::IndentErr { pos: cstart }, tail: append_toks(AppendArg { front: tokenize_line(ScanState { source: ls.src, pos: cstart }), back: TokenList::Cons { head: Token::Newline { pos: nls }, tail: tokenize_indent(LineState { src: ls.src, stack: dr_p, pos: nls }) } }) } else append_toks(AppendArg { front: tokenize_line(ScanState { source: ls.src, pos: cstart }), back: TokenList::Cons { head: Token::Newline { pos: nls }, tail: tokenize_indent(LineState { src: ls.src, stack: dr_p, pos: nls }) } })) }) else append_toks(AppendArg { front: tokenize_line(ScanState { source: ls.src, pos: cstart }), back: TokenList::Cons { head: Token::Newline { pos: nls }, tail: tokenize_indent(LineState { src: ls.src, stack: ls.stack, pos: nls }) } })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [ls.src, ls.stack, ls.pos]
      calls : [line_width, next_line_start, top_width, dedents_to, dr_count, dr_err, dr_popped, cons_dedents, tokenize_line, append_toks, tokenize_indent]
    termination:
      bound : 65535


-- shape_toks: the brick-8b structural observable. Walks a block-structured token
-- list and returns a kind-count fingerprint with a dedicated band per structural
-- token kind, so each test input's signature is a single number predictable by
-- hand (the shape_ast technique, brick 7):
--
--   1000000 * (#IndentErr) + 10000 * (#Newline) + 100 * (#Dedent) + (#Indent)
--
-- The bands are spaced wide enough that no test input overflows a lower band
-- (the deepest test has a handful of each). Lexeme tokens (Ident/Keyword/Num/
-- Op/Str) and Eof contribute 0 — they are brick 2/8a's surface, not 8b's.
-- Structural recursion on the tail.
rule shape_toks
  @intention: "Structural signature of a token list: a kind-count fingerprint of its block tokens"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    lst : TokenList
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match lst:
      Cons(head, tail) => tok_band(head) + shape_toks(tail)
      Nil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [lst]
      calls : [tok_band, shape_toks]
    termination:
      bound : 65535
      structural : lst


-- tok_band: the per-token contribution to shape_toks. Indent=1, Dedent=100,
-- Newline=10000, IndentErr=1000000; every other token (lexemes + Eof) = 0.
rule tok_band
  @intention: "shape_toks band contribution of one token (block tokens only)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    t : Token
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match t:
      Ident(start, len) => 0
      Keyword(start, len, kw) => 0
      Num(value, len) => 0
      Op(code, len) => 0
      Str(start, len) => 0
      Newline(pos) => 10000
      Indent => 1
      Dedent => 100
      IndentErr(pos) => 1000000
      Eof => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [t]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- begin_tokenize: a thin entry into the line driver that builds the initial
-- empty column stack INSIDE a callable body (the final-position call), so the
-- ColStack::Empty VariantConstruct sees the arena context. (A group-variant
-- construction in a `let` RHS at an entry rule's frame has no arena context in
-- the native emitter — the let-eval path runs without it — so the construction
-- is pushed down into this callable, whose body emit does thread the arena. The
-- entry drivers below therefore call begin_tokenize instead of constructing
-- ColStack::Empty themselves.) Returns the full block-structured token stream.
rule begin_tokenize
  @intention: "Start the line driver from an empty column stack at line 0"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : TokenList
  logic:
    out = tokenize_indent(LineState { src: s.source, stack: ColStack::Empty, pos: 0 })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [tokenize_indent]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- An entry concept for the brick-8b drivers: a source text (argv) to tokenize
-- with indentation. (pos always starts at 0 — the file's first line start.)
concept IndentSrc
  @intention: "Source text for the block-structured (INDENT/DEDENT) tokenizer"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  fields:
    source : text [..256]


-- shape_indent_src: the brick-8b money-shot observable. Tokenize the source with
-- indentation (tokenize_indent from line start 0, empty column stack) and return
-- the structural signature of the resulting block-structured stream. A single
-- number, hand-derivable per input, certifies the exact Indent/Dedent/Newline/
-- IndentErr shape. NATIVE-ONLY for newline-bearing sources (the interpreter's
-- JSON reader does not decode \n into a real byte 10 — see count_cells_src).
rule shape_indent_src
  @intention: "Tokenize a source with INDENT/DEDENT and return its block-structure signature"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    a : IndentSrc
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: a.source, pos: 0 })
    out = shape_toks(toks)
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, shape_toks]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- kind_at_indent: like kind_at (brick 8a) but over the block-structured stream.
-- Tokenize with indentation and return the KIND code of the token at index
-- `arg.idx` (… Newline=600, Indent=700, Dedent=800, IndentErr=900). Confirms a
-- structural token appears at the expected position. Native-only for newline
-- sources. Reuses KindAtState (source + idx).
rule kind_at_indent
  @intention: "Tokenize a source with INDENT/DEDENT and return the kind of the token at an index"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    arg : KindAtState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: arg.source, pos: 0 })
    out = peek_kind(Nth { lst: toks, n: arg.idx })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [arg.source, arg.idx]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, peek_kind]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- count_cells_indent: count every cons cell of the block-structured stream
-- (lexemes + Indent + Dedent + Newline + IndentErr + trailing Eof). A coarser
-- companion to shape_indent_src. Native-only for newline sources.
rule count_cells_indent
  @intention: "Tokenize a source with INDENT/DEDENT and count its token cons cells"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:27
  input:
    a : IndentSrc
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: a.source, pos: 0 })
    out = count_cells(toks)
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, count_cells]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 9: parse a statement BLOCK (let-bindings + a final out value). The first
-- PROGRAM-grammar parse that consumes the block-structured tokens (Indent /
-- Dedent / Newline) brick 8b weaves in. The grammar mirrors src/parser.rs's
-- logic-block shape:
--
--   <block>  = Indent stmt_seq Dedent
--   stmt_seq = (let_stmt Newline)* out_stmt Newline?
--   let_stmt = 'let' IDENT '=' expr
--   out_stmt = IDENT '=' expr          (conventionally `out = expr`)
--
-- BLOCK FRAMING (documented invariant). The brick-9 test sources are the block
-- BODY lines, written at COLUMN 0 (no leading indentation). begin_tokenize then
-- produces a stream of the shape `[lexemes Newline]* Eof` with NO Indent/Dedent
-- (every line sits at width 0 == the column-0 sentinel top, so the line driver
-- weaves neither). parse_stmts is nonetheless written to be framing-AGNOSTIC: at
-- each step it first SKIPS any leading Newline / Indent tokens (skip_seps), so a
-- genuinely-indented block (a leading Indent, statements separated by Newline,
-- closed by a Dedent) parses identically — the leading Indent is skipped, each
-- statement's trailing Newline is skipped before the next, and a Dedent or Eof
-- ends the binding scan exactly like the column-0 Eof does. The parser STOPS the
-- binding sweep at a Dedent (800) or Eof (0): in the column-0 framing the final
-- out-statement is followed by Newline then Eof, so after the out value parse the
-- block is complete.
--
-- The let-vs-out distinction is purely the leading token of the (sep-skipped)
-- line: kind 204 (the `let` keyword, kw=4) => a let_stmt; otherwise a bare IDENT
-- (kind 100) followed by `=` (op 18) => the out_stmt. Each statement's `=` is the
-- op-code-18 token; each RHS is a full parse_or expression. parse_or already
-- stops at a Newline (kind 600 is not an operator at any precedence level), so an
-- expression never bleeds across a line boundary.
--
-- RECURSION / LAZINESS. parse_stmts is self-recursive THROUGH a continuation
-- (stmt_let_join), exactly like the expression fold rules (add_rest <-> add_join).
-- The eager-let trap (vexprparse.verbose: the parse-fold comment) applies: the
-- recursive descent into the next statement must be GUARDED, so it sits inside the
-- let-branch's continuation, never in a bare `let`. parse_stmts only ever parses
-- the CURRENT statement eagerly; the tail recursion is reached only along the
-- let-branch, via stmt_let_join, after the value's `next` index is known. Both
-- live in the brick-9 parse cycle, so their TokenList / Parsed group-field inputs
-- compile natively (the group-field recursive ABI).
-- ============================================================================

-- Accessors for a Block (a match-block is only legal in final position, so
-- destructuring is factored into tiny rules, like parsed_node / parsed_next).
rule block_binds
  @intention: "The binding list of a parsed block"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:28
  input:
    b : Block
  output:
    out : Binding
  logic:
    out = match b:
      MkBlock(binds, result) => binds
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [b]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


rule block_result
  @intention: "The final out-expression of a parsed block"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:28
  input:
    b : Block
  output:
    out : Ast
  logic:
    out = match b:
      MkBlock(binds, result) => result
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [b]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Accessors for a ParsedBlock parse result.
rule pb_block
  @intention: "The Block from a block parse result"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:28
  input:
    p : ParsedBlock
  output:
    out : Block
  logic:
    out = match p:
      MkPB(block, next) => block
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [p]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


rule pb_next
  @intention: "The token index just past a block parse result"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:28
  input:
    p : ParsedBlock
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match p:
      MkPB(block, next) => next
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [p]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- skip_seps: advance past any leading separator tokens (Newline kind 600 OR
-- Indent kind 700) starting at `st.pos`, returning the index of the first
-- non-separator token. Stops at a Dedent (800), Eof (0), or any lexeme. Used at
-- the head of each statement so parse_stmts dispatches on the real leading token
-- regardless of the framing (column-0: skip the inter-statement Newline; indented
-- block: skip the leading Indent too). Recursion advances `pos` strictly toward
-- the finite end of the token list; no structural/decreasing FIELD fits a forward
-- index scan, so it carries the bound + the mandatory recursion breadcrumb (the
-- backstop is the finite token-list length, bounded by max_nodes).
rule skip_seps
  @intention: "Index of the first non-separator token at/after pos (skips Newline/Indent)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:28
  input:
    st : ParseState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let knd = peek_kind(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos })
    let issep = if knd == 600 then 1 else if knd == 700 then 1 else 0
    out = if issep == 1 then skip_seps(ParseState { toks: st.toks, pos: st.pos + 1 }) else st.pos
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st.toks, st.pos]
      calls : [peek_kind, skip_seps]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- stmt_let_join: the continuation that threads a parsed let-value's `next` index
-- into the recursive scan of the REST of the block, then conses the binding onto
-- the front of the rest's binding list. Called ONLY from parse_stmts's let-branch
-- (so the recursion stays guarded, never eager). It:
--   * extracts the value node + next index from the already-parsed RHS (jl.value),
--   * recurses parse_stmts at that next index (which re-skips the trailing
--     Newline before the next statement),
--   * conses BCons(name span, value, rest.binds) and keeps rest.result + rest.next.
-- In the brick-9 parse cycle, so its Parsed / TokenList group-field inputs compile
-- natively.
rule stmt_let_join
  @intention: "Cons a parsed let-binding onto the recursively-parsed rest of the block"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:28
  input:
    jl : LetJoinState
  output:
    out : ParsedBlock
  logic:
    let vnode = parsed_node(jl.value)
    let vnext = parsed_next(jl.value)
    let rest = parse_stmts(ParseState { toks: jl.toks, pos: vnext })
    let rblock = pb_block(rest)
    let rbinds = block_binds(rblock)
    let rresult = block_result(rblock)
    let rnext = pb_next(rest)
    out = ParsedBlock::MkPB { block: Block::MkBlock { binds: Binding::BCons { name_start: jl.name_start, name_len: jl.name_len, value: vnode, rest: rbinds }, result: rresult }, next: rnext }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [jl.toks, jl.name_start, jl.name_len, jl.value]
      calls : [parsed_node, parsed_next, parse_stmts, pb_block, block_binds, block_result, pb_next]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- parse_stmts: parse a statement sequence starting at st.pos. Skips leading
-- separators, then:
--   * if the leading token is `let` (kind 204): it is a let_stmt. The bound name
--     is the IDENT at headp+1 (its span via peek_start / peek_len); the `=` is at
--     headp+2 (op 18, not re-checked here — the grammar is fixed); the RHS is a
--     full parse_or from headp+3. The RHS parse is handed to stmt_let_join, which
--     recurses on the rest and conses this binding. The recursion is reached ONLY
--     on this branch, keeping it guarded (the eager-let discipline).
--   * otherwise (a bare IDENT `=` expr, the out_stmt): the RHS is a full parse_or
--     from headp+2 (IDENT at headp, `=` at headp+1). The block terminates here:
--     return MkBlock(BNil, value) with next = the value's end index. A Dedent or
--     Eof leading token would also land here (peek_kind != 204) and produce an
--     empty-result block — but in the brick-9 column-0 framing the out_stmt always
--     precedes the Eof, so this is the normal terminator.
-- Self-recursive THROUGH stmt_let_join; both in the parse cycle. Bound + recursion
-- breadcrumb (the backstop: each step's RHS parse consumes >=1 token, and the
-- finite token list is bounded by max_nodes).
rule parse_stmts
  @intention: "Parse a (let_stmt Newline)* out_stmt sequence into a Block + end index"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:28
  input:
    st : ParseState
  output:
    out : ParsedBlock
  logic:
    let headp = skip_seps(ParseState { toks: st.toks, pos: st.pos })
    let knd = peek_kind(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: headp })
    let islet = if knd == 204 then 1 else 0
    let name_start = if islet == 1 then peek_start(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: headp + 1 }) else peek_start(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: headp })
    let name_len = if islet == 1 then peek_len(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: headp + 1 }) else peek_len(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: headp })
    out = if islet == 1 then stmt_let_join(LetJoinState { toks: st.toks, name_start: name_start, name_len: name_len, value: parse_or(ParseState { toks: st.toks, pos: headp + 3 }) }) else ParsedBlock::MkPB { block: Block::MkBlock { binds: Binding::BNil, result: parsed_node(parse_or(ParseState { toks: st.toks, pos: headp + 2 })) }, next: parsed_next(parse_or(ParseState { toks: st.toks, pos: headp + 2 })) }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st.toks, st.pos]
      calls : [skip_seps, peek_kind, peek_start, peek_len, stmt_let_join, parse_or, parsed_node, parsed_next]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- parse_block: the brick-9 block entry. The documented framing makes the source
-- the block BODY (column-0 lines); parse_stmts is framing-agnostic, so this is a
-- thin wrapper that starts the sweep at index 0. (A future brick that nests a
-- block under a header would start parse_stmts after the header's Newline+Indent;
-- the skip_seps head makes that a position change only.)
rule parse_block
  @intention: "Parse a statement block from token index 0 into a Block + end index"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:28
  input:
    st : ParseState
  output:
    out : ParsedBlock
  logic:
    out = parse_stmts(st)
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st]
      calls : [parse_stmts]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 9 STRUCTURAL ORACLE. A block with name-bearing bindings has no numeric
-- value without an environment (the bonus eval below adds one), so the parser is
-- validated by the SHAPE of the Block it builds, like brick 5/7's shape_ast. The
-- signature is hand-derivable per input:
--
--   block_shape = 1000000 * (#bindings) + shape_binds(binds) + shape_ast(result)
--
-- where shape_binds sums shape_ast over every binding's RHS expression. The
-- 1000000 band counts bindings (each test has <100); shape_binds + shape_ast(result)
-- both stay well under 1000000 for every test input, so a single number certifies
-- the exact (#bindings, per-binding RHS shapes, result shape) triple.
-- ============================================================================

-- count_binds: number of bindings in a Binding cons-list. Structural recursion.
rule count_binds
  @intention: "Number of let-bindings in a binding cons-list"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:28
  input:
    b : Binding
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match b:
      BCons(name_start, name_len, value, rest) => 1 + count_binds(rest)
      BNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [b]
      calls : [count_binds]
    termination:
      bound : 4000
      structural : b


-- shape_binds: sum of shape_ast over every binding's RHS expression. Structural
-- recursion on the binding tail; shape_ast (the brick-5/7 oracle) supplies each
-- value's structural signature.
rule shape_binds
  @intention: "Sum of the structural signatures of every binding's RHS expression"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:28
  input:
    b : Binding
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match b:
      BCons(name_start, name_len, value, rest) => shape_ast(value) + shape_binds(rest)
      BNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [b]
      calls : [shape_ast, shape_binds]
    termination:
      bound : 4000
      structural : b


-- block_shape: tokenize a block-body source (column-0 lines) with indentation,
-- parse a statement block from index 0, and return its structural signature.
-- The brick-9 money-shot observable. NATIVE-ONLY for newline-bearing sources
-- (the interpreter's JSON reader does not decode \n into a real byte 10 — see
-- count_cells_src). Reuses IndentSrc (source text).
rule block_shape
  @intention: "Parse a statement block and return 1000000*#binds + binding-shapes + result-shape"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:28
  input:
    a : IndentSrc
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: a.source, pos: 0 })
    let pb = parse_block(ParseState { toks: toks, pos: 0 })
    let blk = pb_block(pb)
    let binds = block_binds(blk)
    let result = block_result(blk)
    out = 1000000 * count_binds(binds) + (shape_binds(binds) + shape_ast(result))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_block, pb_block, block_binds, block_result, count_binds, shape_binds, shape_ast]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 10: EVALUATING A LET-BLOCK WITH AN ENVIRONMENT (name resolution).
--
-- Brick 9 PARSED a let-block into a Block { binds, result } and proved the parse
-- structurally (block_shape). Brick 10 RUNS it to a number, resolving variable
-- references by BYTES against the source text. The pieces:
--
--   * name_eq      — are two source spans byte-for-byte equal? (recursion over a
--                    byte range, bounded by the span length).
--   * env_lookup   — find a name in the Env by byte-comparing its span against
--                    each entry's span; return the bound value (recursion over
--                    the Env list, innermost-first so the latest binding wins).
--   * eval_ast_env — eval_ast EXTENDED with an Env + src: AstVar(start, len) now
--                    resolves to env_lookup(...) instead of 0. This rule carries
--                    BOTH a group field (node : Ast) AND a text field (src) and
--                    recurses with sibling calls (AstBin lhs/rhs) — the shape the
--                    2b052a7 compiler fix unblocked (cf. recursive_text_eval).
--   * build_env    — walk the binding list IN ORDER, evaluating each binding's
--                    RHS against the env built SO FAR (so `let y = x + 1` sees an
--                    earlier `let x = 1`), consing (name span, value) on the front.
--   * eval_block   — the entry: tokenize -> parse_block -> build_env -> eval the
--                    result against the populated env. The money shot.
--
-- NAME RESOLUTION BY BYTES. A variable's identity is its bytes in the source, not
-- a symbol-table index: two `x` at different spans ARE the same variable. So both
-- the binding name (recorded as a span by parse_stmts) and the AstVar reference
-- (recorded as a span by parse_primary) are resolved by comparing the actual
-- source bytes. eval_ast_env and build_env therefore both carry the source text
-- alongside the AST/Env — exactly the "group field + text field, recursive" shape.
--
-- OUT OF SCOPE FOR THIS BRICK (documented, evaluate to 0 like brick 7's eval_ast):
-- AstField / AstCall / AstStr — they need a richer environment (records, function
-- values, decoded string bytes). The point of brick 10 is VARIABLE resolution in
-- arithmetic/logic let-blocks; those three stay 0 and are proven by shape_ast.
--
-- TERMINATION. name_eq recurses over a byte range with `increasing : off` bounded
-- by the span length (a Number field of its packed input — same shape as the
-- tokenizer's scanners, so the proof verifies mechanically). env_lookup,
-- build_env, and eval_ast_env recurse over a strictly-shrinking cons-list tail /
-- Ast sub-node, but that shrinking value is a FIELD of a packed input concept,
-- not the input itself; the `structural` proof requires the input to BE a group
-- concept, so it does not fit. Like the parser's packed-state rules (parse_add,
-- stmt_let_join, ...) these carry bound-only termination and ACCEPT the mandatory
-- native recursion breadcrumb. Backstops: the Env / binding lists are finite
-- (built by a finite binding sweep) and the AST is finite (bounded by max_nodes),
-- so every recursion strictly shrinks toward a leaf / Nil. byte_at is fail-closed
-- OOB (returns 0), so an out-of-range span never reads past the buffer.
-- ============================================================================

-- A name-equality probe: the source text, the two span starts, the common length
-- to compare, and the current byte offset within the spans. name_eq compares
-- src[a_start+off] vs src[b_start+off] for off in [0, len).
concept NameEqState
  @intention: "Source text + two span starts + length + current offset, for byte-comparing two names"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:29
  fields:
    src : text [..256]
    a_start : number [0, 256]
    b_start : number [0, 256]
    len : number [0, 256]
    off : number [0, 256]


-- name_eq: 1 iff the byte ranges src[a_start..a_start+len] and
-- src[b_start..b_start+len] are equal. Compares byte by byte from `off` up to
-- `len`; equal when off reaches len. The caller checks the two LENGTHS are equal
-- BEFORE calling (env_lookup does this), so this rule assumes a common len and
-- only walks the bytes. Recursion advances `off` toward `len`; bounded by 256.
rule name_eq
  @intention: "1 if two source spans of equal length are byte-for-byte identical, 0 otherwise"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:29
  input:
    st : NameEqState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = if st.off >= st.len then 1 else if byte_at(st.src, st.a_start + st.off) == byte_at(st.src, st.b_start + st.off) then name_eq(NameEqState { src: st.src, a_start: st.a_start, b_start: st.b_start, len: st.len, off: st.off + 1 }) else 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st.src, st.a_start, st.b_start, st.len, st.off]
      calls : [name_eq]
    termination:
      bound : 256
      increasing : off


-- The environment-lookup probe: the Env to search, the source text (for byte
-- comparison), and the query name's span (q_start, q_len).
concept EnvLookState
  @intention: "An Env to search + the source text + the query name's span"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:29
  fields:
    env : Env
    src : text [..256]
    q_start : number [0, 256]
    q_len : number [0, 256]


-- env_lookup: find the query name in the Env and return its bound value, or 0 if
-- the name is unbound (an unbound variable evaluates to 0 — the same default as a
-- brick-7 AstVar, just now reachable through the environment). Walks the Env
-- innermost-first: at each ECons it checks the entry's LENGTH equals the query
-- length AND the bytes match (name_eq); on a match it returns the entry's `val`,
-- otherwise it recurses into `rest`. Because build_env conses the newest binding
-- on the front, the FIRST match is the most recent binding — shadowing wins.
-- Bound-only termination + the native recursion breadcrumb (packed input concept;
-- the shrinking Env tail is a field, not the input — see the header).
rule env_lookup
  @intention: "Value bound to a name in the environment (0 if unbound); innermost binding wins"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:29
  input:
    st : EnvLookState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match st.env:
      ECons(name_start, name_len, val, rest) => if name_len == st.q_len and name_eq(NameEqState { src: st.src, a_start: name_start, b_start: st.q_start, len: name_len, off: 0 }) == 1 then val else env_lookup(EnvLookState { env: rest, src: st.src, q_start: st.q_start, q_len: st.q_len })
      ENil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st.env, st.src, st.q_start, st.q_len]
      calls : [name_eq, env_lookup]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- eval_ast_env's input: the AST node to evaluate, the environment to resolve
-- variable references against, and the source text the spans index into. Carries
-- a group field (node : Ast) AND a text field (src) — the 2b052a7 shape.
concept EvalEnvArg
  @intention: "An Ast node + the environment + the source text + the program, for evaluating with name resolution and calls"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:36
  fields:
    node : Ast
    env : Env
    src : text [..256]
    prog : RuleList


-- eval_ast_env: eval_ast EXTENDED with an environment. Identical to eval_ast for
-- every variable-free node (the same arithmetic / comparison / logical / unary /
-- if / bool dispatch), but AstVar(start, len) now RESOLVES the name: it looks the
-- span up in the env by byte comparison and returns the bound value. Every
-- recursive call threads the SAME env and src down, so a nested sub-expression
-- sees the same bindings. AstBin makes TWO sibling recursive calls (lhs and rhs)
-- while carrying the text field src — exactly the shape the 2b052a7 fix unblocked.
-- AstField / AstCall / AstStr stay 0 (out of scope for this brick — see header).
-- Bound-only termination + the native recursion breadcrumb: each recursive call
-- walks a strict sub-node of ea.node, but ea.node is a FIELD of the packed input
-- (not the input), so the `structural` proof does not fit — see the header.
rule eval_ast_env
  @intention: "Evaluate an AST to a number, resolving variable references against an environment"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:29
  input:
    ea : EvalEnvArg
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match ea.node:
      AstNum(value) => value
      AstBin(op, lhs, rhs) => if op == 13 then eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: lhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) + eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: rhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) else if op == 14 then eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: lhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) - eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: rhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) else if op == 15 then eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: lhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) * eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: rhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) else if op == 16 then eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: lhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) / eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: rhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) else if op == 17 then eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: lhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) % eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: rhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) else if op == 1 then (if eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: lhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) == eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: rhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) then 1 else 0) else if op == 6 then (if eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: lhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) != eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: rhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) then 1 else 0) else if op == 19 then (if eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: lhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) < eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: rhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) then 1 else 0) else if op == 20 then (if eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: lhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) > eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: rhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) then 1 else 0) else if op == 5 then (if eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: lhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) <= eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: rhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) then 1 else 0) else if op == 4 then (if eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: lhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) >= eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: rhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) then 1 else 0) else if op == 30 then (if eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: lhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) != 0 and eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: rhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) != 0 then 1 else 0) else if op == 31 then (if eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: lhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) != 0 or eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: rhs, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) != 0 then 1 else 0) else 0
      AstNeg(inner) => 0 - eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: inner, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog })
      AstNot(inner) => if eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: inner, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) == 0 then 1 else 0
      AstVar(start, len) => env_lookup(EnvLookState { env: ea.env, src: ea.src, q_start: start, q_len: len })
      AstField(base, fstart, flen) => 0
      AstCall(callee_start, callee_len, args) => eval_call(EvalCallState { callee_start: callee_start, callee_len: callee_len, args: args, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog })
      AstIf(cond, thn, els) => if eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: cond, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) != 0 then eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: thn, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog }) else eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: els, env: ea.env, src: ea.src, prog: ea.prog })
      AstBool(value) => value
      AstStr(start, len) => 0
      AstErr => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [ea.node, ea.env, ea.src, ea.prog]
      calls : [eval_ast_env, env_lookup, eval_call]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- build_env's input: the remaining binding list, the env built so far, and the
-- source text (each binding's RHS is evaluated against env_so_far, and AstVar
-- references in it resolve via src).
concept BuildEnvArg
  @intention: "Remaining bindings + the env built so far + the source text + the program (for calls in RHSes)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:36
  fields:
    binds : Binding
    env : Env
    src : text [..256]
    prog : RuleList


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 18: call/apply in the evaluator. The evaluator resolved VARIABLES
-- (brick 10) but returned 0 for CALLS. Brick 18 makes AstCall actually EXECUTE
-- a rule: find the called rule by NAME in the program, evaluate the argument
-- expressions against the CALLER's env, bind them to the callee's params in a
-- FRESH env (lexical scoping — the callee does NOT see the caller's locals),
-- build the callee's let-env on top of that, then evaluate the callee's result.
-- Calls recurse naturally: a `fact` that calls itself just works if it
-- terminates. This closes the loop from source text to a real computed call
-- result — the file is now a (toy) INTERPRETER, not just a parser + var-resolver.
--
-- THE SCC. eval_ast_env, eval_call, bind_params, and build_env now form one
-- mutual-recursion cluster (eval_ast_env -> eval_call -> bind_params/build_env ->
-- eval_ast_env). Like the brick-10 evaluator rules they carry bound-only
-- termination and ACCEPT the mandatory native recursion breadcrumb: each
-- recursive call walks a strict sub-node / shorter tail, but that shrinking
-- value is a FIELD of a packed input concept (not the input itself), so the
-- `structural` proof does not fit. The backstops are the same as brick 10 (finite
-- Env / binding / arg / param lists and a finite AST bounded by max_nodes) PLUS:
-- a call chain is bounded only by the source program's own termination — an
-- infinite Verbose program (no base case) would not terminate here either, which
-- is the honest interpreter semantics, not a soundness gap in this brick.
-- ============================================================================

-- The call-evaluation probe: the callee's name span (callee_start, callee_len),
-- the call's argument AST list, the CALLER's environment (arg expressions are
-- evaluated against it), the source text (for name byte-comparison), and the
-- whole program (the scope the callee name is resolved against, and threaded so
-- the callee body can itself call other rules).
concept EvalCallState
  @intention: "A callee name span + the call's args + the caller env + the source text + the program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:36
  fields:
    callee_start : number [0, 256]
    callee_len : number [0, 256]
    args : ArgList
    env : Env
    src : text [..256]
    prog : RuleList


-- The parameter-binding probe: the callee's remaining formal parameter list, the
-- remaining call-argument AST list (positional, in lock-step with params), the
-- CALLER's environment (each arg expression is evaluated against it), the source
-- text, and the program (threaded because an argument can itself be a call).
concept BindParamsState
  @intention: "Callee params + call args + the caller env + the source text + the program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:36
  fields:
    params : ParamList
    args : ArgList
    env : Env
    src : text [..256]
    prog : RuleList


-- The rule-lookup probe: the program's rule list to search, the source text (for
-- byte-comparison), and the query name's span (q_start, q_len). Same shape as the
-- arity pass's RuleNamedState, but returns the matched RuleDecl rather than 0/1.
concept FindRuleState
  @intention: "A program rule list to search + the source text + the query name's span"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:36
  fields:
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]
    q_start : number [0, 256]
    q_len : number [0, 256]


-- A one-field probe to read the HEAD of an argument list (block-form match is only
-- legal in final position, so destructuring an ArgList is factored into a tiny
-- rule — same idiom as parsed_args_* / pp_params).
concept AHeadState
  @intention: "A call-argument list, for reading its head node"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:36
  fields:
    args : ArgList


-- A one-field probe to read the TAIL of an argument list (mirror of AHeadState).
concept ATailState
  @intention: "A call-argument list, for reading its tail"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:36
  fields:
    args : ArgList


-- build_env: fold the binding list (in source order) into an Env. For each
-- BCons, evaluate the binding's RHS Ast against the env built SO FAR (so a later
-- binding can reference an earlier one — `let x = 1` then `let y = x + 1` makes y
-- see x = 1), then cons (name span, computed value) onto the FRONT of the env and
-- recurse on the rest with the extended env. BNil returns the accumulated env
-- unchanged. Consing on the front means env_lookup finds the most-recent binding
-- first, which gives last-binding-wins shadowing. Bound-only termination + the
-- native recursion breadcrumb (packed input; the shrinking binding tail is a
-- field, not the input — see the header).
rule build_env
  @intention: "Fold a binding list into an environment, evaluating each RHS against the env so far"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:29
  input:
    ba : BuildEnvArg
  output:
    out : Env
  logic:
    out = match ba.binds:
      BCons(name_start, name_len, value, rest) => build_env(BuildEnvArg { binds: rest, env: Env::ECons { name_start: name_start, name_len: name_len, val: eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: value, env: ba.env, src: ba.src, prog: ba.prog }), rest: ba.env }, src: ba.src, prog: ba.prog })
      BNil => ba.env
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [ba.binds, ba.env, ba.src, ba.prog]
      calls : [build_env, eval_ast_env]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- arg_head: the HEAD argument AST of a call's ArgList (an AstNum(0) placeholder
-- when the list is empty). bind_params reads one argument per parameter via this;
-- a call with fewer args than params binds the surplus params to 0 (the same
-- "missing -> 0" default the rest of the evaluator uses, e.g. an unbound variable
-- or an out-of-scope callee). Factored into a tiny rule because block-form match
-- is only legal in final position (same idiom as parsed_args_head / pp_params).
rule arg_head
  @intention: "The head argument AST of a call's argument list (AstNum 0 if empty)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:36
  input:
    a : AHeadState
  output:
    out : Ast
  logic:
    out = match a.args:
      ArgCons(head, tail) => head
      ArgNil => Ast::AstNum { value: 0 }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.args]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- arg_tail: the TAIL of a call's ArgList (ArgNil when already empty). bind_params
-- consumes one argument per parameter and recurses on this tail in lock-step with
-- the parameter list's tail. Mirror of arg_head.
rule arg_tail
  @intention: "The tail of a call's argument list (ArgNil if empty)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:36
  input:
    a : ATailState
  output:
    out : ArgList
  logic:
    out = match a.args:
      ArgCons(head, tail) => tail
      ArgNil => ArgList::ArgNil
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.args]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- find_rule: locate the rule whose NAME span byte-equals the query span and return
-- its RuleDecl, walking the program rule list front-to-back. Same name-matching
-- idiom as the arity pass's rule_named (length equality first, then name_eq on the
-- bytes), but returns the matched RuleDecl instead of 0/1. On no match it returns
-- a SENTINEL MkRule(0, 0, PNil, MkBlock(BNil, AstErr)) — an empty-param rule whose
-- body is AstErr, so eval_call on a nonexistent callee evaluates to 0, preserving
-- the pre-brick-18 "AstCall => 0" behavior (the undefined-callee lint pass flags
-- the missing rule separately). Bound-only termination + the native recursion
-- breadcrumb (the shrinking rule-list tail is a field of the packed input).
rule find_rule
  @intention: "The RuleDecl whose name matches the query span (sentinel empty rule if none)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:36
  input:
    st : FindRuleState
  output:
    out : RuleDecl
  logic:
    out = match st.rules:
      RCons(head, tail) => if rd_name_len(head) == st.q_len and name_eq(NameEqState { src: st.src, a_start: rd_name_start(head), b_start: st.q_start, len: st.q_len, off: 0 }) == 1 then head else find_rule(FindRuleState { rules: tail, src: st.src, q_start: st.q_start, q_len: st.q_len })
      RNil => RuleDecl::MkRule { name_start: 0, name_len: 0, params: ParamList::PNil, body: Block::MkBlock { binds: Binding::BNil, result: Ast::AstErr } }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st.rules, st.src, st.q_start, st.q_len]
      calls : [rd_name_len, rd_name_start, name_eq, find_rule]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- bind_params: build the callee's PARAMETER environment by walking the callee's
-- formal parameter list and the call's argument list in lock-step. For each
-- PCons(name span, rest), evaluate the corresponding argument AST (arg_head) against
-- the CALLER's environment bp.env (threading bp.prog, since an argument can itself
-- be a call), cons (param name span, computed value) onto a FRESH env, and recurse
-- on the param tail with the argument tail (arg_tail). PNil returns ENil — the
-- accumulation base is the EMPTY environment, NOT the caller env, which is exactly
-- lexical scoping: the callee body sees only its parameters (and its own lets,
-- added later by build_env on top of this), never the caller's locals. Bound-only
-- termination + the native recursion breadcrumb (the shrinking param/arg tails are
-- fields of the packed input).
rule bind_params
  @intention: "Bind a callee's params to its call's args (each evaluated in the caller env) onto a fresh env"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:36
  input:
    bp : BindParamsState
  output:
    out : Env
  logic:
    out = match bp.params:
      PCons(name_start, name_len, ty, rest) => Env::ECons { name_start: name_start, name_len: name_len, val: eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: arg_head(AHeadState { args: bp.args }), env: bp.env, src: bp.src, prog: bp.prog }), rest: bind_params(BindParamsState { params: rest, args: arg_tail(ATailState { args: bp.args }), env: bp.env, src: bp.src, prog: bp.prog }) }
      PNil => Env::ENil
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [bp.params, bp.args, bp.env, bp.src, bp.prog]
      calls : [eval_ast_env, arg_head, arg_tail, bind_params]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- eval_call: APPLY a rule. (1) find_rule resolves the callee name span against the
-- program; (2) bind_params evaluates each argument in the CALLER env and binds it
-- to the callee's parameters in a FRESH env (penv) — lexical scoping, no leak of
-- caller locals; (3) build_env folds the callee's own let-bindings on TOP of penv
-- (so a let RHS sees both the parameters and earlier lets) into cenv; (4)
-- eval_ast_env evaluates the callee's result expression against cenv. Plain rule
-- (not a match arm) so it can use `let` bindings. Recurses through eval_ast_env ->
-- AstCall -> eval_call for nested / self / mutual calls; a Verbose `fact` that
-- calls itself terminates iff the source program terminates (honest interpreter
-- semantics). Bound-only termination + the native recursion breadcrumb: this rule
-- is in the eval SCC, and a call chain's length is the source program's own depth,
-- not a structurally-shrinking field of this input.
rule eval_call
  @intention: "Evaluate a function call: find the rule, bind params in a fresh env, build its lets, evaluate its body"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:36
  input:
    ec : EvalCallState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let callee = find_rule(FindRuleState { rules: ec.prog, src: ec.src, q_start: ec.callee_start, q_len: ec.callee_len })
    let penv = bind_params(BindParamsState { params: rd_params(callee), args: ec.args, env: ec.env, src: ec.src, prog: ec.prog })
    let cbody = rd_body(callee)
    let cbinds = block_binds(cbody)
    let cresult = block_result(cbody)
    let cenv = build_env(BuildEnvArg { binds: cbinds, env: penv, src: ec.src, prog: ec.prog })
    out = eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: cresult, env: cenv, src: ec.src, prog: ec.prog })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [ec.callee_start, ec.callee_len, ec.args, ec.env, ec.src, ec.prog]
      calls : [find_rule, bind_params, rd_params, rd_body, block_binds, block_result, build_env, eval_ast_env]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- eval_block: the brick-10 money-shot driver. Tokenize the block-body source
-- (column-0 lines) with indentation, parse a statement block from index 0, build
-- the environment from its bindings (in order, each RHS resolved against the env
-- so far), then evaluate the block's final out-expression against that env. The
-- result is a real NUMBER — a let-block interpreter written in Verbose.
--
--   eval_block("let x = 1\nlet y = x + 1\nout = y") = 2
--
-- NATIVE-ONLY for newline-bearing sources (the interpreter's JSON reader does not
-- decode \n into a real byte 10 — see count_cells_src). Single-line, zero-binding
-- sources (e.g. "out = 2 + 3 * 4" — but a bare expression like "2 + 3 * 4" also
-- works: parse_stmts treats the leading non-`let` token as the out_stmt's IDENT
-- and parses the value from headp+2, so a single expression with no `name =`
-- prefix lands as the result with an empty binding list) cross-check native vs
-- interpreter. eval_block takes a ScanState (source + pos) like eval_expr, so the
-- source is argv arg 1 and pos is argv arg 2 (always 0).
rule eval_block
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, build the environment, and evaluate a let-block to a number"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:29
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let pb = parse_block(ParseState { toks: toks, pos: 0 })
    let blk = pb_block(pb)
    let binds = block_binds(blk)
    let result = block_result(blk)
    let env = build_env(BuildEnvArg { binds: binds, env: Env::ENil, src: s.source, prog: RuleList::RNil })
    out = eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: result, env: env, src: s.source, prog: RuleList::RNil })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_block, pb_block, block_binds, block_result, build_env, eval_ast_env]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 11: parse a top-level `rule` declaration with a `logic:` block. This
-- lifts the parser from a bare statement-block (brick 9/10) to a real top-level
-- PROGRAM item: a named rule whose body is a logic block. The grammar mirrors
-- src/parser.rs's parse_rule, restricted to the tractable subset:
--
--   rule_decl = 'rule' IDENT Newline Indent
--                 'logic' ':' Newline Indent
--                   <stmt_seq>          -- the brick-9 (let ...)* out = ... body
--                 Dedent Dedent
--
-- WHAT IS PARSED (the subset). Only the `rule` keyword, the rule NAME, and the
-- `logic:` section. No @intention / @source / input: / output: / proofs: — those
-- are later bricks. The point of brick 11 is the HEADER (the `rule NAME` line and
-- the nested `logic:` indent framing) plus delegating the body to the brick-9
-- block parser.
--
-- `rule` AND `logic` ARE PLAIN IDENTS (no keyword code). The tokenizer's
-- keyword_code only classifies if/or/of/let/and/not/then/else/true/false; `rule`
-- and `logic` lex as ordinary Ident tokens (kind 100). So the parser recognizes
-- them by BYTE COMPARISON of the Ident's source span against the literal bytes
-- "rule" (r=114 u=117 l=108 e=101) and "logic" (l=108 o=111 g=103 i=105 c=99).
-- This is why the rule-parsing rules carry `src` (the source text) ALONGSIDE the
-- token list: the byte comparison reads the actual source bytes the Ident's span
-- points at. span_is_rule / span_is_logic are flat fixed-width byte checks (like
-- the tokenizer's kw4 / kw5), not recursions.
--
-- THE NESTED INDENT/DEDENT. The token stream for `rule f\n  logic:\n    out=...`
-- is (verified via kind_at_indent):
--   0 Ident"rule"  1 Ident"f"  2 Newline  3 Indent      <- enter rule body
--   4 Ident"logic" 5 Op`:`(10) 6 Newline  7 Indent      <- enter logic body
--   8 <first stmt token> ...  Newline  Dedent Dedent Eof
-- parse_rule_decl consumes the two nested INDENTs by SKIPPING separators
-- (skip_seps skips Newline 600 AND Indent 700): after the name at index 1 it
-- skip_seps from 2 to land on `logic` (index 4); after the `:` at index 5 it
-- skip_seps from 6 to land on the first statement (index 8). The trailing two
-- DEDENTs need no explicit consumption — parse_stmts already STOPS its binding
-- sweep at a Dedent (800) or Eof (0), so the block body ends exactly there. This
-- reuses the framing-agnostic block parser unchanged (brick 9's design payoff).
--
-- HOW src IS THREADED. The brick-9 block parser threads only the TokenList. The
-- rule-header recognition needs the source text too, so parse_rule_decl takes a
-- RuleParseState { toks : TokenList, src : text } — a group field (the token
-- list) ALONGSIDE a text field (the source) — exactly the multi-field recursive
-- shape the 2b052a7 / 9529277 compiler fixes support. parse_rule_decl itself is
-- NOT recursive (it is a one-shot fixed-grammar parse delegating the body to the
-- self-recursive parse_stmts), so it carries bound-only termination with no
-- recursion breadcrumb.
--
-- VALIDATION. A RuleDecl carries a Block, so it is BOTH evaluable (brick 10) and
-- structurally checkable (brick 9):
--   * eval_rule_decl(source) parses the rule decl, extracts its body Block,
--     build_env's the bindings, and evaluates the result — proving the HEADER
--     parsed AND the body still evaluates correctly (the rule's `out` value).
--   * rule_shape(source) = 1000 * name_len + block_shape(body), proving the name
--     span length AND the body's structural signature (brick 9's block_shape).
-- Both are NATIVE-ONLY (the source is multi-line — the interpreter's JSON reader
-- does not decode \n into a real byte 10; see count_cells_src). Multi-line argv
-- via $'rule f\n  logic:\n    out = 2 + 3'.
--
-- Oracle: src/parser.rs's parse_rule (the `rule NAME` + `logic:` block shape).
-- ============================================================================

-- The rule-parse entry state: the whole token list plus the source text. The
-- token list drives the structural parse; the source text backs the byte
-- comparison that recognizes the `rule` / `logic` idents (which have no keyword
-- code). A group field (toks) + a text field (src) — the supported multi-field
-- shape.
concept RuleParseState
  @intention: "The token list plus the source text, for parsing a rule declaration"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:30
  fields:
    toks : TokenList
    src : text [..256]


-- Brick 16: the parameter-list parse cursor — the token list plus the index at
-- which the parameter list (or its absence) begins. Same shape as ParseState; a
-- distinct name keeps parse_params's input self-documenting. parse_params reads
-- the token at `pos`: a '(' opens a comma-separated IDENT list; anything else
-- means "no parameters".
-- Brick 20: ParamParseState also carries the SOURCE TEXT so params_scan can read a
-- type-name Ident span (after a `:`) and map it to a type code via type_code_of_span.
concept ParamParseState
  @intention: "The token list, the source text, plus the index where a parameter list may begin"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:34
  fields:
    toks : TokenList
    src : text [..256]
    pos : number [0, 512]


-- A fixed-width span byte-check probe: the source text plus an Ident token's
-- span (start, len). span_is_rule / span_is_logic compare the span against a
-- fixed literal word, length first then each byte.
concept SpanCheck
  @intention: "Source text + an Ident span, for byte-comparing it to a fixed keyword"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:30
  fields:
    src : text [..256]
    start : number [0, 256]
    len : number [0, 256]


-- span_is_rule: 1 iff the span src[start..start+len] is exactly the 4 bytes
-- "rule" (r=114 u=117 l=108 e=101). Flat fixed-width check (like the tokenizer's
-- kw4), length-guarded first so a shorter/longer ident never reads past its span.
rule span_is_rule
  @intention: "1 if an Ident span spells exactly \"rule\", 0 otherwise"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:30
  input:
    sc : SpanCheck
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = if sc.len == 4 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start) == 114 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 1) == 117 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 2) == 108 and byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 3) == 101))) then 1 else 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [sc.src, sc.start, sc.len]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 64


-- span_is_logic: 1 iff the span src[start..start+len] is exactly the 5 bytes
-- "logic" (l=108 o=111 g=103 i=105 c=99). Flat fixed-width check (like kw5).
rule span_is_logic
  @intention: "1 if an Ident span spells exactly \"logic\", 0 otherwise"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:30
  input:
    sc : SpanCheck
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = if sc.len == 5 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start) == 108 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 1) == 111 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 2) == 103 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 3) == 105 and byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 4) == 99)))) then 1 else 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [sc.src, sc.start, sc.len]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 64


-- type_code_of_span (Brick 20): map a TYPE-NAME Ident span to its type code, using
-- the SAME codes brick 19 assigns (0=number, 1=bool, 2=text). The param parser
-- reads the typename token after a `:` and calls this to record the param's
-- declared type. Three flat fixed-width byte checks (mirroring span_is_rule /
-- span_is_logic), length-guarded first so a wrong-length ident never reads past its
-- span: "number" = n,u,m,b,e,r (110,117,109,98,101,114) len 6; "bool" = b,o,o,l
-- (98,111,111,108) len 4; "text" = t,e,x,t (116,101,120,116) len 4. Anything else
-- (including the `len 4` non-bool/non-text case and any other length) falls through
-- to 0 — the same DEFAULT an untyped param gets, so an unrecognized type name is
-- treated as `number`, never an error (parser stays fail-graceful like the rest of
-- the header parse).
rule type_code_of_span
  @intention: "Map a type-name Ident span to its type code (0=number, 1=bool, 2=text, else 0)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:38
  input:
    sc : SpanCheck
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = if sc.len == 6 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start) == 110 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 1) == 117 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 2) == 109 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 3) == 98 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 4) == 101 and byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 5) == 114))))) then 0 else (if sc.len == 4 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start) == 98 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 1) == 111 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 2) == 111 and byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 3) == 108))) then 1 else (if sc.len == 4 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start) == 116 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 1) == 101 and (byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 2) == 120 and byte_at(sc.src, sc.start + 3) == 116))) then 2 else 0))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [sc.src, sc.start, sc.len]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 64


-- Accessors for a RuleDecl (a block-form match is only legal in final position,
-- so destructuring is factored into tiny rules — like block_binds / pb_block).
rule rd_name_start
  @intention: "The name-span start offset of a parsed rule declaration"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:30
  input:
    r : RuleDecl
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match r:
      MkRule(name_start, name_len, params, body) => name_start
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [r]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


rule rd_name_len
  @intention: "The name-span length of a parsed rule declaration"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:30
  input:
    r : RuleDecl
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match r:
      MkRule(name_start, name_len, params, body) => name_len
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [r]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


rule rd_body
  @intention: "The logic block of a parsed rule declaration"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:30
  input:
    r : RuleDecl
  output:
    out : Block
  logic:
    out = match r:
      MkRule(name_start, name_len, params, body) => body
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [r]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


rule rd_params
  @intention: "The formal parameter list of a parsed rule declaration"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:34
  input:
    r : RuleDecl
  output:
    out : ParamList
  logic:
    out = match r:
      MkRule(name_start, name_len, params, body) => params
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [r]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- Accessors for a ParsedParams result (block-form match only legal in final
-- position, so destructuring is factored into tiny rules — like parsed_args_*).
rule pp_params
  @intention: "The ParamList from a parameter-list parse result"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:34
  input:
    p : ParsedParams
  output:
    out : ParamList
  logic:
    out = match p:
      MkPP(params, next) => params
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [p]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


rule pp_next
  @intention: "The token index just past a parameter-list parse result"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:34
  input:
    p : ParsedParams
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match p:
      MkPP(params, next) => next
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [p]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- params_prepend: cons the head parameter span onto the front of the already-
-- parsed REST of the parameter list, carrying the rest's end index through.
-- Splitting this out keeps the recursive params_scan call lazily inside the comma
-- branch (a let would force it eagerly) — the same shape as args_prepend.
-- Brick 20: ParamPrependState also carries head_ty — the head parameter's declared
-- type code — so params_prepend can cons it into the PCons it builds.
concept ParamPrependState
  @intention: "A head parameter span + its type code, plus the parsed rest of the parameter list"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:34
  fields:
    head_start : number
    head_len : number
    head_ty : number
    rest : ParsedParams


rule params_prepend
  @intention: "Cons a parameter span (with its type code) onto the front of the parsed rest of the list"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:34
  input:
    pps : ParamPrependState
  output:
    out : ParsedParams
  logic:
    let rest_list = pp_params(pps.rest)
    let rest_next = pp_next(pps.rest)
    out = ParsedParams::MkPP { params: ParamList::PCons { name_start: pps.head_start, name_len: pps.head_len, ty: pps.head_ty, rest: rest_list }, next: rest_next }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [pps.head_start, pps.head_len, pps.head_ty, pps.rest]
      calls : [pp_params, pp_next]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- params_scan: parse a NON-EMPTY comma-separated parameter list starting at the
-- FIRST parameter's token index `ps.pos`. Brick 20 makes each parameter OPTIONALLY
-- TYPED: `IDENT` (untyped) OR `IDENT : TYPENAME` (typed). In the token stream a
-- typed param is THREE tokens (name, `:` op-10, typename-IDENT) before the
-- separator; an untyped param is ONE token before it.
--
-- Read the name IDENT span at ps.pos. Peek ps.pos+1: if it is `:` (op 10) the param
-- is typed — read the TYPENAME span at ps.pos+2 and map it to a code via
-- type_code_of_span (reading ps.src); the separator is at ps.pos+3. Otherwise the
-- param is untyped (ty defaults to 0 = number) and the separator is at ps.pos+1.
-- Then the brick-16 separator dispatch on that separator position: a ',' (op 11)
-- continues — parse the REST (LAZILY, in the then branch) from just past the comma
-- and prepend this param; a ')' (op 22) stops, consuming it (next = sep_pos + 1);
-- anything else stops too (missing ')' tolerated, like args_cons), leaving
-- next = sep_pos. When UNTYPED, sep_pos = ps.pos + 1 and this reduces EXACTLY to the
-- brick-16 behavior (close_next = pos+2 on ')', else pos+1; comma-continue from
-- pos+2), so untyped lists parse byte-identically to before. Recurses over a forward
-- token scan (no structural FIELD fits), so bound + the mandatory recursion
-- breadcrumb (the backstop is the finite token list, bounded by max_nodes). Every
-- peek is OOB-guarded by the token-list accessors (Eof past the end).
rule params_scan
  @intention: "Parse a non-empty comma-separated list of optionally-typed params, consuming the ')'"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:38
  input:
    ps : ParamParseState
  output:
    out : ParsedParams
  logic:
    let name_start = peek_start(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: ps.pos })
    let name_len = peek_len(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: ps.pos })
    let colon_opc = peek_op_code(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: ps.pos + 1 })
    let typed = if colon_opc == 10 then 1 else 0
    let ty_start = peek_start(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: ps.pos + 2 })
    let ty_len = peek_len(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: ps.pos + 2 })
    let ty = if typed == 1 then type_code_of_span(SpanCheck { src: ps.src, start: ty_start, len: ty_len }) else 0
    let sep_pos = if typed == 1 then ps.pos + 3 else ps.pos + 1
    let sep_opc = peek_op_code(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: sep_pos })
    let iscomma = if sep_opc == 11 then 1 else 0
    let close_next = if sep_opc == 22 then sep_pos + 1 else sep_pos
    out = if iscomma == 1 then params_prepend(ParamPrependState { head_start: name_start, head_len: name_len, head_ty: ty, rest: params_scan(ParamParseState { toks: ps.toks, src: ps.src, pos: sep_pos + 1 }) }) else ParsedParams::MkPP { params: ParamList::PCons { name_start: name_start, name_len: name_len, ty: ty, rest: ParamList::PNil }, next: close_next }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [ps.toks, ps.src, ps.pos]
      calls : [peek_start, peek_len, peek_op_code, type_code_of_span, params_prepend, params_scan]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- parse_params: parse an OPTIONAL parameter list starting at ps.pos (the token
-- right AFTER a rule's name). Three cases, in order:
--   * token at pos is NOT '(' (op 21): no parens at all -> PNil, next = pos
--     unchanged (the caller continues to `logic:` from there).
--   * token at pos IS '(' and the next token is ')' (op 22): empty param list
--     `()` -> PNil, next = pos + 2 (past both parens).
--   * otherwise: a non-empty list -> params_scan from pos + 1 (the first IDENT).
-- Mirrors parse_args's '(' / ')' / first-arg dispatch, but builds a ParamList of
-- bare name spans instead of an ArgList of AST nodes. One-shot dispatch (the
-- recursion lives in params_scan); bound-only termination.
rule parse_params
  @intention: "Parse an optional '(' name, name, ... ')' parameter list into a ParamList + end index"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:34
  input:
    ps : ParamParseState
  output:
    out : ParsedParams
  logic:
    let opc = peek_op_code(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: ps.pos })
    let isopen = if opc == 21 then 1 else 0
    let next_opc = peek_op_code(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: ps.pos + 1 })
    let isempty = if next_opc == 22 then 1 else 0
    out = if isopen == 0 then ParsedParams::MkPP { params: ParamList::PNil, next: ps.pos } else (if isempty == 1 then ParsedParams::MkPP { params: ParamList::PNil, next: ps.pos + 2 } else params_scan(ParamParseState { toks: ps.toks, src: ps.src, pos: ps.pos + 1 }))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [ps.toks, ps.src, ps.pos]
      calls : [peek_op_code, params_scan]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- parse_rule_decl: parse ONE top-level rule declaration into a RuleDecl. The
-- grammar is fixed, so positions are computed by skipping separators rather than
-- re-validated token by token:
--   * index 0 is the `rule` Ident, RECOGNIZED by byte-comparing its span against
--     "rule" (span_is_rule, reading rp.src). The keyword `rule` has no keyword
--     code, so this byte check is how the header is recognized at all.
--   * the NAME is the Ident at index 1; its span is (peek_start 1, peek_len 1).
--   * skip_seps from index 2 skips Newline + the rule-body Indent, landing on the
--     `logic` Ident (index 4 in the canonical stream), RECOGNIZED by byte-
--     comparing its span against "logic" (span_is_logic, also via rp.src).
--   * the `:` is at logic_idx + 1; skip_seps from logic_idx + 2 skips Newline +
--     the logic-body Indent, landing on the first statement token (index 8).
--   * parse_stmts parses the body block from there; it stops at the trailing
--     Dedent/Eof, so the two closing DEDENTs need no explicit consumption.
-- FAIL-GRACEFUL: a Verbose rule is total, so a malformed header cannot abort.
-- When BOTH byte checks pass (`hdr_ok == 1`) the body is the parsed block;
-- otherwise the body is an empty block (BNil result AstErr) — eval_rule_decl
-- then yields 0 and rule_shape yields name-band-only, a distinguishable signal
-- rather than a crash. One-shot (not self-recursive); delegates the body to the
-- self-recursive parse_stmts. Bound-only termination, no recursion breadcrumb.
rule parse_rule_decl
  @intention: "Parse a `rule NAME` + `logic:` block into a RuleDecl (byte-recognizing the rule/logic idents)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:30
  input:
    rp : RuleParseState
  output:
    out : RuleDecl
  logic:
    let name_start = peek_start(Nth { lst: rp.toks, n: 1 })
    let name_len = peek_len(Nth { lst: rp.toks, n: 1 })
    let kw_start = peek_start(Nth { lst: rp.toks, n: 0 })
    let kw_len = peek_len(Nth { lst: rp.toks, n: 0 })
    let is_rule = span_is_rule(SpanCheck { src: rp.src, start: kw_start, len: kw_len })
    let pp = parse_params(ParamParseState { toks: rp.toks, src: rp.src, pos: 2 })
    let params = pp_params(pp)
    let after_params = pp_next(pp)
    let logic_idx = skip_seps(ParseState { toks: rp.toks, pos: after_params })
    let logic_start = peek_start(Nth { lst: rp.toks, n: logic_idx })
    let logic_len = peek_len(Nth { lst: rp.toks, n: logic_idx })
    let is_logic = span_is_logic(SpanCheck { src: rp.src, start: logic_start, len: logic_len })
    let hdr_ok = if is_rule == 1 and is_logic == 1 then 1 else 0
    let body_idx = skip_seps(ParseState { toks: rp.toks, pos: logic_idx + 2 })
    let pb = parse_stmts(ParseState { toks: rp.toks, pos: body_idx })
    let goodblk = pb_block(pb)
    out = RuleDecl::MkRule { name_start: name_start, name_len: name_len, params: params, body: if hdr_ok == 1 then goodblk else Block::MkBlock { binds: Binding::BNil, result: Ast::AstErr } }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [rp.toks, rp.src]
      calls : [peek_start, peek_len, span_is_rule, parse_params, pp_params, pp_next, span_is_logic, skip_seps, parse_stmts, pb_block]
    termination:
      bound : 64


-- eval_rule_decl: the brick-11 money-shot driver. Tokenize the rule-declaration
-- source (with indentation), parse the rule decl, extract its body Block, build
-- the environment from the body's bindings (in order, each RHS against the env so
-- far), and evaluate the body's final out-expression against that env. The result
-- is the rule's `out` value — proving the HEADER parsed AND the body evaluates.
--
--   eval_rule_decl("rule add\n  logic:\n    let x = 5\n    out = x + 1") = 6
--
-- NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source — the interpreter's JSON reader does not decode
-- \n; see count_cells_src). Takes a ScanState (source + pos) like eval_block, so
-- the source is argv arg 1 and pos is argv arg 2 (always 0).
rule eval_rule_decl
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse a rule decl, build the environment, and evaluate its body to a number"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:30
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let rd = parse_rule_decl(RuleParseState { toks: toks, src: s.source })
    let blk = rd_body(rd)
    let binds = block_binds(blk)
    let result = block_result(blk)
    let env = build_env(BuildEnvArg { binds: binds, env: Env::ENil, src: s.source, prog: RuleList::RNil })
    out = eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: result, env: env, src: s.source, prog: RuleList::RNil })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_rule_decl, rd_body, block_binds, block_result, build_env, eval_ast_env]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- rule_shape: the brick-11 STRUCTURAL oracle. Tokenize, parse the rule decl, and
-- return 1000 * name_len + block_shape(body). The 1000 band carries the rule
-- NAME's span length (every test name is < 1000 chars and block_shape's smallest
-- nonzero contribution is shape_ast >= 0, with the binding-count band at 1000000
-- well clear), so a single number certifies the name length AND the full body
-- structure (binding count, per-binding RHS shapes, result shape). NATIVE-ONLY.
rule rule_shape
  @intention: "Parse a rule decl and return 1000*name_len + block_shape(body)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:30
  input:
    a : IndentSrc
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: a.source, pos: 0 })
    let rd = parse_rule_decl(RuleParseState { toks: toks, src: a.source })
    let nlen = rd_name_len(rd)
    let blk = rd_body(rd)
    let binds = block_binds(blk)
    let result = block_result(blk)
    out = 1000 * nlen + (1000000 * count_binds(binds) + (shape_binds(binds) + shape_ast(result)))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_rule_decl, rd_name_len, rd_body, block_binds, block_result, count_binds, shape_binds, shape_ast]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 12: parse a PROGRAM = a SEQUENCE of top-level rule declarations.
--
-- This lifts the parser from ONE rule decl (brick 11) to a whole (rule-only)
-- program. The grammar:
--
--   program   = rule_decl*
--   rule_decl = 'rule' IDENT Newline Indent 'logic' ':' Newline Indent <stmts> Dedent Dedent
--
-- TOKEN STREAM at a rule boundary (hand-traced for two rules whose bodies are at
-- column 4, logic: at column 2, rule at column 0):
--
--   rule f          rule(0) f(1) Nl(2)
--     logic:        Indent(3) logic(4) :(5) Nl(6)
--       out = 2+3   Indent(7) out(8) =(9) 2(10) +(11) 3(12) Nl(13)
--   rule g          Dedent(14) Dedent(15) rule(16) g(17) Nl(18)
--     logic:        Indent(19) logic(20) :(21) Nl(22)
--       ...         Indent(23) ... Nl  ...  Dedent Dedent Eof
--
-- So rule f's body parse (parse_stmts from idx 8) parses `out = 2 + 3` and STOPS
-- at the Dedent(14) — its pb_next is 13 (just past the `3` at idx 12, before the
-- Newline). Between that end position and the next `rule` keyword (idx 16) sit:
-- Newline(13) Dedent(14) Dedent(15). The program loop must skip ALL of these
-- (Newline + Indent + Dedent) to reach the next `rule`. skip_seps (brick 9) stops
-- at a Dedent (it only skips Newline 600 / Indent 700), so brick 12 adds
-- skip_seps_dedent, which ALSO skips Dedent 800 — landing on the next lexeme
-- (`rule`) or the trailing Eof.
--
-- POSITION THREADING (option a). parse_rule_decl (brick 11) returns a RuleDecl
-- but NOT where it stopped; to parse a sequence we need both. Brick 12 adds
-- parse_rule_decl_pos, which takes a ProgramState (toks + src + a START position
-- p) and returns a ParsedRule = MkPR(rule, next). It generalizes the brick-11
-- offsets — which assumed the `rule` keyword sits at index 0 — to start at p:
-- keyword at p, name at p+1, skip_seps from p+2 to `logic`, `:` at logic_idx+1,
-- skip_seps from logic_idx+2 to the first body token, parse_stmts from there.
-- `next` is the body block's pb_next. Brick 11's parse_rule_decl stays untouched
-- (the p=0 special case) so its drivers (eval_rule_decl / rule_shape) do not
-- regress.
--
-- VALIDATION DRIVERS:
--   * count_rules(source)         = length of the parsed RuleList (the program
--                                   split into the right number of rule decls).
--   * eval_nth_rule(source, n)    = evaluate the body of the n-th rule decl
--                                   (build_env + eval its Block result), proving
--                                   each rule parsed AND its body is intact.
-- Both NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source — the interpreter's JSON reader does not
-- decode \n; see count_cells_src).
--
-- Oracle: src/parser.rs's top-level item loop (parse a `rule`, push, repeat).
-- ============================================================================

-- The program-parse entry/cursor state: the whole token list, the source text
-- (backs the byte recognition of the `rule` keyword), and the current scan index.
-- A group field (toks) + a text field (src) + a number (pos) — the supported
-- multi-field shape (same as RuleParseState plus a cursor).
concept ProgramState
  @intention: "The token list, source text, and current index, for parsing a program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:31
  fields:
    toks : TokenList
    src : text [..256]
    pos : number [0, 512]


-- The eval-nth-rule driver state: a multi-line source plus the rule index n.
concept EvalNthState
  @intention: "A program source plus the index of the rule decl to evaluate"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:31
  fields:
    source : text [..256]
    n : number [0, 512]


-- skip_seps_dedent: advance past any leading SEPARATOR token — Newline (600),
-- Indent (700), OR Dedent (800) — starting at st.pos, returning the index of the
-- first non-separator token (a lexeme such as `rule`, or the trailing Eof 0).
-- Brick 9's skip_seps stops at a Dedent because INSIDE a block the Dedent is the
-- block terminator; at the PROGRAM level the Dedents that close one rule's body
-- are just noise between two sibling rule decls, so the program loop skips them
-- too. Same forward-index recursion as skip_seps (strictly advancing toward the
-- finite end of the token list); bound + the mandatory recursion breadcrumb (the
-- backstop is the finite token-list length, bounded by max_nodes).
rule skip_seps_dedent
  @intention: "Index of the first non-separator token at/after pos (skips Newline/Indent/Dedent)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:31
  input:
    st : ParseState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let knd = peek_kind(Nth { lst: st.toks, n: st.pos })
    let issep = if knd == 600 then 1 else if knd == 700 then 1 else if knd == 800 then 1 else 0
    out = if issep == 1 then skip_seps_dedent(ParseState { toks: st.toks, pos: st.pos + 1 }) else st.pos
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st.toks, st.pos]
      calls : [peek_kind, skip_seps_dedent]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- Accessors for a ParsedRule (a block-form match is only legal in final position,
-- so destructuring is factored into tiny rules — like pb_block / pb_next).
rule pr_rule
  @intention: "The RuleDecl from a rule-decl parse result"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:31
  input:
    p : ParsedRule
  output:
    out : RuleDecl
  logic:
    out = match p:
      MkPR(rule, next) => rule
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [p]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


rule pr_next
  @intention: "The token index just past a rule-decl parse result"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:31
  input:
    p : ParsedRule
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match p:
      MkPR(rule, next) => next
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [p]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- parse_rule_decl_pos: parse ONE top-level rule declaration STARTING at ps.pos,
-- returning a ParsedRule (the RuleDecl + the end index). The position-aware
-- generalization of brick 11's parse_rule_decl: every fixed offset (0, 1, 2)
-- becomes relative to the start position p = ps.pos.
--   * the `rule` keyword is at index p, recognized by byte-comparing its span to
--     "rule" (span_is_rule, reading ps.src).
--   * the NAME is the Ident at p+1; its span is (peek_start p+1, peek_len p+1).
--   * skip_seps from p+2 skips the Newline + the rule-body Indent, landing on the
--     `logic` Ident, recognized by byte-comparing its span to "logic".
--   * the `:` is at logic_idx+1; skip_seps from logic_idx+2 skips the Newline +
--     the logic-body Indent, landing on the first body statement token.
--   * parse_stmts parses the body block from there; it stops at the trailing
--     Dedent/Eof, and pb_next is the index just past the body's final expression.
-- FAIL-GRACEFUL like brick 11: when both byte checks pass the body is the parsed
-- block, else an empty block (BNil result AstErr). `next` is always the body's
-- pb_next, so the program loop advances even on a malformed header. One-shot
-- (delegates body recursion to parse_stmts); bound-only termination.
rule parse_rule_decl_pos
  @intention: "Parse a `rule NAME` + `logic:` block starting at ps.pos into a RuleDecl + end index"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:31
  input:
    ps : ProgramState
  output:
    out : ParsedRule
  logic:
    let kw_start = peek_start(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: ps.pos })
    let kw_len = peek_len(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: ps.pos })
    let is_rule = span_is_rule(SpanCheck { src: ps.src, start: kw_start, len: kw_len })
    let name_start = peek_start(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: ps.pos + 1 })
    let name_len = peek_len(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: ps.pos + 1 })
    let pp = parse_params(ParamParseState { toks: ps.toks, src: ps.src, pos: ps.pos + 2 })
    let params = pp_params(pp)
    let after_params = pp_next(pp)
    let logic_idx = skip_seps(ParseState { toks: ps.toks, pos: after_params })
    let logic_start = peek_start(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: logic_idx })
    let logic_len = peek_len(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: logic_idx })
    let is_logic = span_is_logic(SpanCheck { src: ps.src, start: logic_start, len: logic_len })
    let hdr_ok = if is_rule == 1 and is_logic == 1 then 1 else 0
    let body_idx = skip_seps(ParseState { toks: ps.toks, pos: logic_idx + 2 })
    let pb = parse_stmts(ParseState { toks: ps.toks, pos: body_idx })
    let goodblk = pb_block(pb)
    let endp = pb_next(pb)
    out = ParsedRule::MkPR { rule: RuleDecl::MkRule { name_start: name_start, name_len: name_len, params: params, body: if hdr_ok == 1 then goodblk else Block::MkBlock { binds: Binding::BNil, result: Ast::AstErr } }, next: endp }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [ps.toks, ps.src, ps.pos]
      calls : [peek_start, peek_len, span_is_rule, parse_params, pp_params, pp_next, span_is_logic, skip_seps, parse_stmts, pb_block, pb_next]
    termination:
      bound : 64


-- parse_program: parse a SEQUENCE of rule declarations starting at ps.pos into a
-- RuleList. The loop:
--   * skip_seps_dedent from ps.pos to the first significant token (a lexeme or
--     Eof), past any leftover Newline / Indent / Dedent that closes a prior rule.
--   * if that token's span spells `rule` (span_is_rule), parse one rule decl there
--     via parse_rule_decl_pos, then RCons it onto the recursive parse of the rest
--     starting at the rule decl's `next` index — which the next iteration's
--     skip_seps_dedent will advance past the body's closing Dedents to the next
--     `rule` (or Eof).
--   * else (Eof, or any non-`rule` token) the program ends: RNil.
-- TERMINATION: each iteration that conses a rule advances the cursor by at least
-- the rule decl's whole body (parse_rule_decl_pos's `next` is strictly past the
-- starting `rule` token), so pos grows strictly toward the finite end of the
-- token list. No structural/decreasing FIELD fits a forward token-index scan, so
-- this carries the bound + the mandatory recursion breadcrumb (the backstop is
-- the finite token list, bounded by max_nodes).
rule parse_program
  @intention: "Parse a sequence of top-level rule declarations into a RuleList"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:31
  input:
    ps : ProgramState
  output:
    out : RuleList
  logic:
    let hp = skip_seps_dedent(ParseState { toks: ps.toks, pos: ps.pos })
    let kw_start = peek_start(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: hp })
    let kw_len = peek_len(Nth { lst: ps.toks, n: hp })
    let is_rule = span_is_rule(SpanCheck { src: ps.src, start: kw_start, len: kw_len })
    let pr = parse_rule_decl_pos(ProgramState { toks: ps.toks, src: ps.src, pos: hp })
    let rd = pr_rule(pr)
    let endp = pr_next(pr)
    out = if is_rule == 1 then RuleList::RCons { head: rd, tail: parse_program(ProgramState { toks: ps.toks, src: ps.src, pos: endp }) } else RuleList::RNil
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [ps.toks, ps.src, ps.pos]
      calls : [skip_seps_dedent, peek_start, peek_len, span_is_rule, parse_rule_decl_pos, pr_rule, pr_next, parse_program]
    termination:
      bound : 512


-- rule_list_len: the number of rule declarations in a parsed program. Structural
-- recursion on the RuleList tail (Phase C), like count_binds on a Binding list.
rule rule_list_len
  @intention: "Number of rule declarations in a parsed program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:31
  input:
    rl : RuleList
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match rl:
      RCons(head, tail) => 1 + rule_list_len(tail)
      RNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [rl]
      calls : [rule_list_len]
    termination:
      bound : 4000
      structural : rl


-- param_list_len: the number of formal parameters in a rule's ParamList.
-- Structural recursion on the PCons tail (Phase C), like count_binds / rule_list_len.
rule param_list_len
  @intention: "Number of formal parameters in a rule's parameter list"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:34
  input:
    pl : ParamList
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match pl:
      PCons(name_start, name_len, ty, rest) => 1 + param_list_len(rest)
      PNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [pl]
      calls : [param_list_len]
    termination:
      bound : 512
      structural : pl


-- drop_rules: the RuleList with its first dr.n rule cells removed — the cons-list
-- analogue of drop_cells on a TokenList. A decreasing number field (dr.n) drives
-- termination: each step recurses on the tail with n - 1. RNil (or n == 0)
-- returns the list as-is. Used by eval_nth_rule to land on the n-th rule.
concept DropRules
  @intention: "A rule list plus a count of leading rule cells to remove"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:31
  fields:
    rl : RuleList
    n : number [0, 512]


rule drop_rules
  @intention: "The rule list with its first dr.n rule cells removed"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:31
  input:
    dr : DropRules
  output:
    out : RuleList
  logic:
    out = match dr.rl:
      RCons(head, tail) => if dr.n == 0 then dr.rl else drop_rules(DropRules { rl: tail, n: dr.n - 1 })
      RNil => RuleList::RNil
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [dr.rl, dr.n]
      calls : [drop_rules]
    termination:
      bound : 512
      decreasing : n


-- rl_head_body: the body Block of the HEAD rule of a rule list (an empty block —
-- BNil result AstErr — for an empty list, so eval yields 0 rather than crashing).
rule rl_head_body
  @intention: "The logic block of the head rule of a rule list (empty block if none)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:31
  input:
    rl : RuleList
  output:
    out : Block
  logic:
    out = match rl:
      RCons(head, tail) => rd_body(head)
      RNil => Block::MkBlock { binds: Binding::BNil, result: Ast::AstErr }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [rl]
      calls : [rd_body]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- rl_head_params: the parameter list of the head rule of a rule list (empty list
-- if none). Mirror of rl_head_body for brick 16's parameters.
rule rl_head_params
  @intention: "The formal parameter list of the head rule of a rule list (PNil if none)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:34
  input:
    rl : RuleList
  output:
    out : ParamList
  logic:
    out = match rl:
      RCons(head, tail) => rd_params(head)
      RNil => ParamList::PNil
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [rl]
      calls : [rd_params]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- count_rules: the brick-12 STRUCTURAL driver. Tokenize the program source (with
-- indentation), parse the whole sequence of rule decls from index 0, and return
-- the RuleList length. Proves the program splits into the right number of rule
-- declarations.
--
--   count_rules("rule f\n  logic:\n    out = 7")                                   = 1
--   count_rules("rule f\n  logic:\n    out = 2 + 3\nrule g\n  logic:\n    ...")     = 2
--
-- NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source). Takes a ScanState (source + pos) so the source
-- is argv arg 1 and pos is argv arg 2 (always 0).
rule count_rules
  @intention: "Tokenize a program, parse the rule-decl sequence, and count the rules"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:31
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    out = rule_list_len(prog)
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, rule_list_len]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- rule_param_count: the brick-16 PARSE money-shot driver. Tokenize the program
-- source, parse the whole rule-decl sequence, and return the number of formal
-- parameters of the FIRST rule.
--
--   rule_param_count("rule add(x, y)\n  logic:\n    out = x + y") = 2
--   rule_param_count("rule f()\n  logic:\n    out = 1")          = 0   (empty parens)
--   rule_param_count("rule g\n  logic:\n    out = 1")            = 0   (no parens)
--
-- NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source). Takes a ScanState: source is argv arg 1, pos
-- is argv arg 2 (always 0).
rule rule_param_count
  @intention: "Parse a program and return the number of parameters of its first rule"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:34
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let params = rl_head_params(prog)
    out = param_list_len(params)
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, rl_head_params, param_list_len]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ParamNthState (Brick 20): a ParamList plus a 0-based index n, the input to
-- param_nth_type. The decreasing `n` field drives termination as the list is walked.
concept ParamNthState
  @intention: "A parameter list plus a 0-based index, for reading the n-th param's type code"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:38
  fields:
    params : ParamList
    n : number [0, 512]


-- param_nth_type (Brick 20): the declared type code of the n-th parameter (0-based)
-- of a ParamList. Walk the PCons tail n times, then return that cell's `ty`. A
-- sentinel of 9 is returned when n runs past the end (PNil) — distinguishable from
-- every real type code (0/1/2). Recursion is driven by the decreasing Number field
-- `n` (each step recurses on the tail with n - 1), which mechanically proves
-- termination (Phase C decreasing proof), exactly like drop_rules over a RuleList.
rule param_nth_type
  @intention: "The declared type code of the n-th parameter (0-based), sentinel 9 if out of range"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:38
  input:
    q : ParamNthState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match q.params:
      PCons(name_start, name_len, ty, rest) => if q.n == 0 then ty else param_nth_type(ParamNthState { params: rest, n: q.n - 1 })
      PNil => 9
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [q.params, q.n]
      calls : [param_nth_type]
    termination:
      bound : 512
      decreasing : n


-- nth_param_type (Brick 20): the BRICK-20 money-shot driver. Tokenize the program
-- source, parse the whole rule-decl sequence, take the FIRST rule's parameter list,
-- and return the type code of its s.pos-th parameter (0-based — s.pos doubles as the
-- index n). This proves the type ANNOTATION on each parameter parsed correctly:
--
--   nth_param_type("rule add(x : number, y : bool)\n  logic:\n    out = x + 1", 0) = 0  (number)
--   nth_param_type("rule add(x : number, y : bool)\n  logic:\n    out = x + 1", 1) = 1  (bool)
--   nth_param_type("rule f(a : text, b : number, c : bool)\n  logic:\n    out = b + 1", 0) = 2  (text)
--   nth_param_type("rule g(x)\n  logic:\n    out = x + 1", 0)                       = 0  (untyped -> number)
--   nth_param_type("rule h()\n  logic:\n    out = 1", 0)                            = 9  (no params -> sentinel)
--
-- NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source). Takes a ScanState: source is argv arg 1, the
-- index n is argv arg 2 (carried in s.pos).
rule nth_param_type
  @intention: "Parse a program and return the declared type code of the n-th param of its first rule"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:38
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let params = rl_head_params(prog)
    out = param_nth_type(ParamNthState { params: params, n: s.pos })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, rl_head_params, param_nth_type]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- eval_nth_rule: the brick-12 money-shot driver. Tokenize the program source,
-- parse the whole rule-decl sequence, DROP the first n rule cells to land on the
-- n-th rule (0-based), take its body Block, build the environment from the body's
-- bindings (each RHS against the env so far), and evaluate the body's final
-- out-expression. The result is the n-th rule's `out` value — proving the rule
-- parsed AND its body is intact and evaluable.
--
--   eval_nth_rule("rule f\n  logic:\n    out = 2+3\nrule g\n  logic:\n    let x=4\n    out = x*2", 0) = 5
--   eval_nth_rule(same, 1) = 8
--
-- NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source). Takes an EvalNthState (source + n): source is
-- argv arg 1 and n is argv arg 2.
rule eval_nth_rule
  @intention: "Parse a program, select the n-th rule, build its env, and evaluate its body to a number"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:31
  input:
    e : EvalNthState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: e.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: e.source, pos: 0 })
    let nth = drop_rules(DropRules { rl: prog, n: e.n })
    let blk = rl_head_body(nth)
    let binds = block_binds(blk)
    let result = block_result(blk)
    let env = build_env(BuildEnvArg { binds: binds, env: Env::ENil, src: e.source, prog: prog })
    out = eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: result, env: env, src: e.source, prog: prog })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [e.source, e.n]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, drop_rules, rl_head_body, block_binds, block_result, build_env, eval_ast_env]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 18 driver: eval_main — run a whole PROGRAM. Tokenize, parse the entire
-- rule sequence, then evaluate the FIRST rule's body with the program threaded so
-- its calls resolve against the other rules. This is the brick-18 money-shot: a
-- multi-rule Verbose program whose entry rule CALLS the others, evaluated to a
-- real number by an interpreter that is itself written in Verbose.
--
-- Convention: the FIRST rule in the source is the entry point (like `main`), and
-- the rest are its (possibly recursive) callees. The entry's `out =` result is
-- evaluated; calls in it dispatch through eval_ast_env -> eval_call -> find_rule.
--
-- Worked examples (all NATIVE-ONLY — multi-line sources; the interpreter's JSON
-- reader does not decode \n into a real byte 10):
--
--   rule main
--     logic:
--       out = double(21)
--   rule double(x)
--     logic:
--       out = x * 2                                   = 42
--
--   rule main
--     logic:
--       out = add(20, 22)
--   rule add(x, y)
--     logic:
--       out = x + y                                   = 42   (two params)
--
--   rule main
--     logic:
--       out = f(10)
--   rule f(n)
--     logic:
--       let d = n * 2
--       out = d + 1                                   = 21   (callee has a let)
--
--   rule main
--     logic:
--       out = double(inc(20))
--   rule double(x)
--     logic:
--       out = x * 2
--   rule inc(n)
--     logic:
--       out = n + 1                                   = 42   (nested call as arg)
--
--   rule main
--     logic:
--       out = fact(5)
--   rule fact(n)
--     logic:
--       out = if n == 0 then 1 else n * fact(n - 1)   = 120  (RECURSIVE)
--
-- eval_main takes a ScanState (source + pos) like eval_block, so the source is
-- argv arg 1 and pos is argv arg 2 (always 0).
rule eval_main
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse a program, and evaluate the FIRST rule's body with calls resolving against the program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:36
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let body = rl_head_body(prog)
    let binds = block_binds(body)
    let result = block_result(body)
    let env = build_env(BuildEnvArg { binds: binds, env: Env::ENil, src: s.source, prog: prog })
    out = eval_ast_env(EvalEnvArg { node: result, env: env, src: s.source, prog: prog })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, rl_head_body, block_binds, block_result, build_env, eval_ast_env]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 13: a LINTER in Verbose — detect undefined-variable references. This is
-- the FIRST static analysis written in Verbose that consumes a parsed Verbose
-- program (brick 12's RuleList) and reports a diagnostic count. It turns the
-- parser front end into a TOOL: lint_program(source) = the total number of
-- undefined-variable references across every rule in the program. 0 = clean.
--
-- THE LINT. For each rule, every variable referenced in the rule's body (the
-- `out =` result expression AND every let-binding's RHS) must be bound by a
-- `let` in that same rule. A reference is an AstVar(start, len); it is DEFINED
-- iff its source span byte-equals SOME binding name in the rule's `binds` list.
-- An AstVar whose name matches no binding name is a LINT ERROR.
--
-- SCOPING RULE CHOSEN (the SIMPLE, whole-rule rule). A variable is defined iff
-- it appears as ANY binding name in the rule's `binds` list — the WHOLE rule's
-- bindings are treated as mutually in scope. So in
--     let x = 1
--     out = x + y
-- x is defined, y is undefined -> 1 error. This deliberately ignores let-order
-- (it does not flag use-before-def within a let RHS): it is a SOUND
-- over-approximation of "defined somewhere in the rule". Order-sensitivity
-- (a let RHS sees only EARLIER lets) is a later refinement, not built here.
-- Documented trade-off: the simple rule never reports a false UNDEF (every
-- name that IS a binding is accepted), but it does not catch forward references.
--
-- WHAT COUNTS AS A VARIABLE REFERENCE (and what does NOT):
--   * AstVar(start, len) is the only variable reference. It is checked.
--   * AstCall callee names are RULE names, not variables — IGNORED. Only the
--     call's ARGUMENT expressions (its ArgList) are walked for AstVar refs.
--   * AstField field names (the .b in a.b) are RECORD field names, not
--     variables — IGNORED. Only the field-access BASE expression is walked
--     (so the `a` in a.b IS checked as an AstVar, the `.b` is not).
--   * AstStr / AstBool / AstNum / AstErr carry no variable reference -> 0.
--
-- NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line program source, as in bricks 10/12): the interpreter's
-- JSON reader does not decode \n into a real byte 10. The lint drivers take a
-- ScanState (source + pos) so the source is argv arg 1 and pos is argv arg 2
-- (always 0). The supporting structural rules (name_bound,
-- count_undef_binds_ordered, the program fold) ARE cross-checkable on hand-built
-- inputs, but the headline
-- driver runs on multi-line source and is native-only.
--
-- RECURSION SHAPES.
-- ALL FIVE recursive lint rules pack the cons-list (Binding / ArgList / RuleList)
-- as a FIELD of their input concept (so they can carry the scope + src alongside),
-- so they recurse over a field, NOT over the input itself. Phase C's structural
-- proof requires the input to BE the group cons-list (structural_param ==
-- input_name); a field-borne list does not fit. They therefore use bound + the
-- mandatory native recursion breadcrumb — exactly like env_lookup / build_env /
-- eval_ast_env, which recurse over a field-borne Env / Binding / Ast for the same
-- reason. The shrinking is real (each step recurses on the list tail), just not
-- expressible as a structural FIELD proof.
--   * name_bound      — walks the Binding cons-list, returns 1/0 membership.
--                       Mirrors env_lookup's byte compare (length-guard then
--                       name_eq) but yields presence, not value.
--   * count_undef_ast — walks an Ast (a FIELD of the packed input, like
--                       eval_ast_env). Mutually recursive with count_undef_args
--                       (over ArgList).
--   * count_undef_binds_ordered — walks the Binding cons-list (the bindings being
--                       iterated), checking each binding's RHS against the PREFIX
--                       of earlier bindings only (proper let-ordering — catches
--                       use-before-def and self-reference).
--   * lint_list       — walks the RuleList tail (like rule_list_len, but over a
--                       field, so bound + breadcrumb not structural).
-- ============================================================================

-- name_bound's probe: the Binding list to search + the source text + the query
-- name's span (q_start, q_len). The membership analogue of EnvLookState.
concept NameBoundState
  @intention: "A binding list to search + the source text + the query name's span"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:32
  fields:
    binds : Binding
    src : text [..256]
    q_start : number [0, 256]
    q_len : number [0, 256]


-- name_bound: 1 iff the query span byte-equals some binding NAME in the list, 0
-- otherwise. Walks the Binding cons-list; at each BCons it checks the binding
-- name's LENGTH equals the query length AND the bytes match (name_eq); on a match
-- it returns 1, otherwise it recurses into `rest`. BNil (end of list) returns 0
-- (not found). Mirrors env_lookup's structure but returns presence (1/0) — the
-- distinct found/not-found a lint needs, where env_lookup's 0 is ambiguous (an
-- unbound var and a var bound to 0 both look like 0). Recurses over the binding
-- tail, which is a FIELD of the input (not the input), so bound + breadcrumb,
-- like env_lookup (the structural proof needs the input to BE the cons-list).
rule name_bound
  @intention: "1 if a name span matches some binding name in the list, 0 otherwise"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:32
  input:
    st : NameBoundState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match st.binds:
      BCons(name_start, name_len, value, rest) => if name_len == st.q_len and name_eq(NameEqState { src: st.src, a_start: name_start, b_start: st.q_start, len: name_len, off: 0 }) == 1 then 1 else name_bound(NameBoundState { binds: rest, src: st.src, q_start: st.q_start, q_len: st.q_len })
      BNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st.binds, st.src, st.q_start, st.q_len]
      calls : [name_eq, name_bound]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- count_undef_args's input: the argument list to walk + the rule's binding list
-- (the SCOPE every AstVar is checked against) + the source text.
concept UndefArgsState
  @intention: "A call-argument list + the rule's bindings (scope) + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:32
  fields:
    args : ArgList
    binds : Binding
    src : text [..256]


-- The Ast-walking input: the AST node + the rule's binding list (scope) + src.
-- Carries a group field (node : Ast) AND a text field (src) — the 2b052a7 shape,
-- same as EvalEnvArg. The node is a FIELD of the packed input (not the input
-- itself), so the recursion uses bound + breadcrumb, not a structural FIELD proof.
concept UndefAstState
  @intention: "An Ast node + the rule's bindings (scope) + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:32
  fields:
    node : Ast
    binds : Binding
    src : text [..256]


-- count_undef_args: sum count_undef_ast over every argument of a call's ArgList.
-- Mutually recursive with count_undef_ast (a call's arguments are themselves Asts
-- that may contain variable references). Recurses over the ArgList tail (a field
-- of the input), so bound + breadcrumb. Threads the same binds (scope) + src down.
rule count_undef_args
  @intention: "Total undefined-variable references across every argument of a call"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:32
  input:
    a : UndefArgsState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match a.args:
      ArgCons(head, tail) => count_undef_ast(UndefAstState { node: head, binds: a.binds, src: a.src }) + count_undef_args(UndefArgsState { args: tail, binds: a.binds, src: a.src })
      ArgNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.args, a.binds, a.src]
      calls : [count_undef_ast, count_undef_args]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- count_undef_ast: walk an Ast and count the AstVar references whose name is NOT
-- name_bound in the rule's scope. Mirrors shape_ast's structural walk, but each
-- node contributes its UNDEFINED-variable count instead of a shape signature:
--   * AstVar(start, len) => 1 if name_bound == 0 (undefined), else 0.
--   * AstBin sums lhs + rhs; AstNeg / AstNot descend into the single child;
--     AstIf sums cond + thn + els.
--   * AstCall walks its ARGUMENT list (count_undef_args). The callee name is a
--     RULE name, not a variable — it is NOT checked (see the brick header).
--   * AstField walks its BASE expression. The field name (.b) is a record field
--     name, not a variable — it is NOT checked (only the `a` in a.b counts).
--   * AstNum / AstStr / AstBool / AstErr carry no reference -> 0.
-- Every recursive call threads the same binds (scope) + src. Like eval_ast_env,
-- the recursion walks a strict sub-node of a.node, but a.node is a FIELD of the
-- packed input (not the input), so the structural proof does not fit — this
-- carries the bound + the mandatory native recursion breadcrumb.
rule count_undef_ast
  @intention: "Total undefined-variable references in an AST, given the rule's binding scope"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:32
  input:
    a : UndefAstState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match a.node:
      AstNum(value) => 0
      AstBin(op, lhs, rhs) => count_undef_ast(UndefAstState { node: lhs, binds: a.binds, src: a.src }) + count_undef_ast(UndefAstState { node: rhs, binds: a.binds, src: a.src })
      AstNeg(inner) => count_undef_ast(UndefAstState { node: inner, binds: a.binds, src: a.src })
      AstNot(inner) => count_undef_ast(UndefAstState { node: inner, binds: a.binds, src: a.src })
      AstVar(start, len) => if name_bound(NameBoundState { binds: a.binds, src: a.src, q_start: start, q_len: len }) == 0 then 1 else 0
      AstField(base, fstart, flen) => count_undef_ast(UndefAstState { node: base, binds: a.binds, src: a.src })
      AstCall(callee_start, callee_len, args) => count_undef_args(UndefArgsState { args: args, binds: a.binds, src: a.src })
      AstIf(cond, thn, els) => count_undef_ast(UndefAstState { node: cond, binds: a.binds, src: a.src }) + count_undef_ast(UndefAstState { node: thn, binds: a.binds, src: a.src }) + count_undef_ast(UndefAstState { node: els, binds: a.binds, src: a.src })
      AstBool(value) => 0
      AstStr(start, len) => 0
      AstErr => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.node, a.binds, a.src]
      calls : [count_undef_ast, count_undef_args, name_bound]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- count_undef_binds_ordered's input: the binding list being ITERATED (each
-- binding's RHS is lint-checked) + the PREFIX of bindings already seen earlier in
-- source order (the only scope a RHS may legitimately reference) + the source
-- text. `iter` shrinks each step; `prefix` GROWS each step (front-consed). This is
-- the brick-14 refinement of brick-13's UndefBindsState: brick-13 checked every
-- RHS against the WHOLE binding list (`scope`), which silently accepted
-- use-before-def. Here each RHS is checked against `prefix` (earlier lets only).
concept UndefBindsOrderedState
  @intention: "The bindings being iterated + the prefix of earlier bindings + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:32
  fields:
    iter : Binding
    prefix : Binding
    src : text [..256]


-- count_undef_binds_ordered: for each binding in `iter`, count_undef_ast on its
-- RHS `value` against `prefix` ONLY (the bindings that appear EARLIER in the
-- list), then recurse on `rest` with `prefix` EXTENDED by THIS binding. Because
-- name_bound checks membership (order-agnostic), the prefix can be built by
-- front-consing the current binding onto `prefix` — that yields exactly the SET of
-- earlier bindings, which is all name_bound needs. lint_rule seeds the walk with
-- `prefix = BNil`.
--
-- This catches USE-BEFORE-DEF that brick-13 missed: `let a = b + 1\nlet b = 2`
-- now flags `b` in a's RHS because `b` is NOT yet in the prefix when a is checked
-- (b is only consed onto the prefix when descending into `rest`, AFTER a's RHS is
-- checked). A SELF-REFERENCE `let x = x + 1` is also flagged: `x` is added to the
-- prefix only on the recursion into `rest`, so x's OWN RHS is checked against a
-- prefix that does NOT contain x -> x is unbound -> counted. A legitimate
-- later-let reference (`let y = x + 1` with x earlier) stays 0 because x is in the
-- prefix by the time y is checked. The final `result` expression still sees ALL
-- bindings (lint_rule passes the full list there, unchanged).
--
-- Recurses over the iterated binding tail (a field of the input), so bound +
-- breadcrumb; `prefix` is rebuilt and `src` threaded unchanged.
rule count_undef_binds_ordered
  @intention: "Undefined-OR-use-before-def references across every binding's RHS (earlier-only scope)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:32
  input:
    b : UndefBindsOrderedState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match b.iter:
      BCons(name_start, name_len, value, rest) => count_undef_ast(UndefAstState { node: value, binds: b.prefix, src: b.src }) + count_undef_binds_ordered(UndefBindsOrderedState { iter: rest, prefix: Binding::BCons { name_start: name_start, name_len: name_len, value: value, rest: b.prefix }, src: b.src })
      BNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [b.iter, b.prefix, b.src]
      calls : [count_undef_ast, count_undef_binds_ordered]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- Brick 16: convert a rule's ParamList into a Binding list so the existing scope
-- machinery (name_bound, count_undef_*) treats every parameter as already-bound.
-- A parameter has no RHS expression, but name_bound only ever reads a binding's
-- NAME span (name_start, name_len) — never its `value` — so each param is consed
-- as a BCons carrying a DUMMY value (AstNum 0). The resulting list is the rule's
-- INITIAL scope: a param `x` is in scope for every let RHS and for the result,
-- exactly like a let that is always already-defined. Structural recursion on the
-- ParamList tail (Phase C), like count_binds on a Binding list.
rule param_to_binding
  @intention: "Convert a parameter list into a Binding list (params as already-bound names)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:34
  input:
    pl : ParamList
  output:
    out : Binding
  logic:
    out = match pl:
      PCons(name_start, name_len, ty, rest) => Binding::BCons { name_start: name_start, name_len: name_len, value: Ast::AstNum { value: 0 }, rest: param_to_binding(rest) }
      PNil => Binding::BNil
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [pl]
      calls : [param_to_binding]
    termination:
      bound : 512
      structural : pl


-- Brick 16: append_bindings's input — the binding list `a` to prepend onto `b`.
concept BindAppendState
  @intention: "Two binding lists: `a` to be prepended onto `b`"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:34
  fields:
    a : Binding
    b : Binding


-- append_bindings: the binding list with every cell of `a` consed (in order) onto
-- the front of `b`. Used to combine the params-as-bindings with a rule's own let
-- bindings into one scope for the result expression. Because name_bound checks
-- membership (order-agnostic), the relative order of the two lists is irrelevant —
-- the only requirement is that every name from BOTH lists is present. Recurses on
-- the tail of `a` (a FIELD of the packed input, not the input itself), so the
-- structural proof does not fit — this carries the bound + the mandatory native
-- recursion breadcrumb, like count_undef_binds_ordered. The backstop is the finite
-- binding list (bounded by max_nodes).
rule append_bindings
  @intention: "Prepend every binding of `a` onto the front of `b`"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:34
  input:
    ba : BindAppendState
  output:
    out : Binding
  logic:
    out = match ba.a:
      BCons(name_start, name_len, value, rest) => Binding::BCons { name_start: name_start, name_len: name_len, value: value, rest: append_bindings(BindAppendState { a: rest, b: ba.b }) }
      BNil => ba.b
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [ba.a, ba.b]
      calls : [append_bindings]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- lint_rule's input: one rule declaration + the program source text (the spans
-- index into it). RuleDecl carries no src of its own, so the program source is
-- threaded alongside.
concept LintRuleState
  @intention: "A rule declaration + the program source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:32
  fields:
    rd : RuleDecl
    src : text [..256]


-- lint_rule: the undefined-OR-use-before-def count for ONE rule. Take the rule's
-- body Block, split it into its binding list and result expression, then sum:
--   * count_undef_binds_ordered over the bindings, seeded with prefix = BNil so
--     each let's RHS is scoped to the lets that appear EARLIER (proper
--     let-ordering: a forward or self reference in a let RHS is flagged), PLUS
--   * count_undef_ast over the result expression, scoped to the FULL binding list
--     (the result legitimately sees every let in the rule).
-- 0 = the rule is clean (every variable it references is bound by an earlier let,
-- or by any let for the result). Per-rule scope: a rule's bindings are NOT visible
-- to any other rule — block_binds(body) is this rule's binding list and nothing
-- else. Brick-14 refinement of brick-13: the bindings part now threads a growing
-- prefix instead of the whole list, so use-before-def is caught.
--
-- Brick 16 — PARAMETERS as the INITIAL scope. The rule's formal parameters
-- (rd_params) are converted to Bindings (param_to_binding) and used as the BASE
-- scope: a param is in scope for EVERY let RHS (so count_undef_binds_ordered is
-- seeded with prefix = the params, not BNil) AND for the result (so the result's
-- scope is the params APPENDED to the full binding list). A param `x` is therefore
-- treated as already-defined everywhere in the body — like a let that is always
-- already-bound. Note: params are added as the use-before-def prefix BASE, so a
-- later let cannot "use-before-def" a parameter (a param precedes all lets).
rule lint_rule
  @intention: "Number of undefined-OR-use-before-def references in one rule (params in scope; 0 if clean)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:32
  input:
    lr : LintRuleState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let body = rd_body(lr.rd)
    let binds = block_binds(body)
    let result = block_result(body)
    let pbinds = param_to_binding(rd_params(lr.rd))
    let scope = append_bindings(BindAppendState { a: pbinds, b: binds })
    let undef_in_binds = count_undef_binds_ordered(UndefBindsOrderedState { iter: binds, prefix: pbinds, src: lr.src })
    out = undef_in_binds + count_undef_ast(UndefAstState { node: result, binds: scope, src: lr.src })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [lr.rd, lr.src]
      calls : [rd_body, block_binds, block_result, rd_params, param_to_binding, append_bindings, count_undef_binds_ordered, count_undef_ast]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- lint_list's input: the rule list being folded + the program source text.
concept LintListState
  @intention: "A rule list + the program source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:32
  fields:
    rl : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- lint_list: sum lint_rule over every rule in the program. Recurses over the
-- RuleList tail (a field of the input), so bound + breadcrumb; the program source is
-- threaded unchanged so every rule's spans resolve against the same buffer. This
-- is the per-rule scoping check made whole: each rule contributes only its OWN
-- undefined references, because lint_rule reads only that rule's own bindings.
rule lint_list
  @intention: "Total undefined-variable references across every rule in a program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:32
  input:
    ll : LintListState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match ll.rl:
      RCons(head, tail) => lint_rule(LintRuleState { rd: head, src: ll.src }) + lint_list(LintListState { rl: tail, src: ll.src })
      RNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [ll.rl, ll.src]
      calls : [lint_rule, lint_list]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- lint_program: the brick-13 money-shot driver. Tokenize the program source (with
-- indentation), parse the whole rule-decl sequence, and fold lint_rule over it,
-- returning the TOTAL number of undefined-variable references in the program.
-- 0 = the whole program is clean — a real static check written in Verbose, run
-- as native machine code over a parsed Verbose program.
--
--   lint_program("rule f\n  logic:\n    let x = 5\n    out = x + 1") = 0   (x defined)
--   lint_program("rule f\n  logic:\n    let x = 5\n    out = x + y") = 1   (y undefined)
--   lint_program("rule f\n  logic:\n    let x = 1\n    out = x\nrule g\n  logic:\n    out = w") = 1
--                                                  (only g's w; f is clean — per-rule scope)
--
-- NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source). Takes a ScanState (source + pos) so the source
-- is argv arg 1 and pos is argv arg 2 (always 0).
rule lint_program
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, and count all undefined-variable references in a program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:32
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    out = lint_list(LintListState { rl: prog, src: s.source })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, lint_list]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 15 — linter pass #2: undefined-CALLEE detection (INTER-rule).
--
-- The variable lint (lint_program, brick 13/14) is INTRA-rule: a variable
-- reference resolves against the current rule's own bindings, so each rule is
-- linted in isolation. The callee lint is INTER-rule: an AstCall names a RULE,
-- and a rule may be DEFINED anywhere in the program. Resolving a callee therefore
-- needs the WHOLE program's RuleList, not just the current rule's bindings.
--
-- So this is a SEPARATE pass with its own state shapes (it carries the program's
-- RuleList alongside the source text, NOT the current rule's binds). Keeping it
-- separate from the var/use-before-def walk keeps each pass single-purpose and
-- proves their independence: an arg that is an undefined VARIABLE but a valid
-- CALLEE is counted by lint_program and NOT by lint_callees, and vice versa.
--
-- Callee scope is program-wide and ORDER-AGNOSTIC: a rule may call itself
-- (self-reference of a CALLEE is legal — it is existence, not termination, that
-- is checked) and any other rule regardless of source position (forward calls,
-- mutual recursion). So unlike the let-prefix trick in count_undef_binds_ordered,
-- there is no prefix here: every rule sees the FULL program RuleList.
--
-- The rules:
--   * rule_named        — 1 iff some RuleDecl in the list has a name span
--                         byte-equal to the query span. Mirrors name_bound but
--                         over RuleList + rd name spans.
--   * count_badcall_args — sum count_badcall_ast over an ArgList (nested calls).
--   * count_badcall_ast — walk an Ast, count AstCall whose callee is not rule_named.
--   * count_badcall_binds — sum count_badcall_ast over each binding's RHS.
--   * badcall_rule      — one rule's bad-callee count (binds RHSes + result).
--   * lint_callees_list — fold badcall_rule over the program (iter advances, the
--                         full list `all` stays fixed so every rule sees every rule).
--   * lint_callees      — the driver: tokenize -> parse_program -> lint_callees_list.
-- ============================================================================

-- rule_named's probe: the program's RuleList to search + the source text + the
-- query name's span (q_start, q_len). The callee-resolution analogue of
-- NameBoundState (which searches a Binding list); here the search space is the
-- program's rule declarations.
concept RuleNamedState
  @intention: "A rule list to search + the source text + the query callee name's span"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:33
  fields:
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]
    q_start : number [0, 256]
    q_len : number [0, 256]


-- rule_named: 1 iff the query span byte-equals some RuleDecl's NAME span in the
-- list, 0 otherwise. Walks the RuleList cons-list; at each RCons it checks the
-- rule name's LENGTH equals the query length AND the bytes match (name_eq); on a
-- match it returns 1, else recurses into `tail`. RNil (end) returns 0 (no rule of
-- that name). Mirrors name_bound, but reads the rule head's name span via
-- rd_name_start / rd_name_len instead of a binding's name fields. Recurses over
-- the RuleList tail, which is a FIELD of the input (not the input), so bound +
-- breadcrumb, like name_bound / lint_list.
rule rule_named
  @intention: "1 if a callee name span matches some rule's name in the program, 0 otherwise"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:33
  input:
    st : RuleNamedState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match st.rules:
      RCons(head, tail) => if rd_name_len(head) == st.q_len and name_eq(NameEqState { src: st.src, a_start: rd_name_start(head), b_start: st.q_start, len: st.q_len, off: 0 }) == 1 then 1 else rule_named(RuleNamedState { rules: tail, src: st.src, q_start: st.q_start, q_len: st.q_len })
      RNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st.rules, st.src, st.q_start, st.q_len]
      calls : [rd_name_len, rd_name_start, name_eq, rule_named]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- count_badcall_args's input: the argument list to walk + the program's RuleList
-- (the scope every AstCall callee is resolved against) + the source text. Mirrors
-- UndefArgsState but carries `rules` instead of `binds`.
concept BadCallArgsState
  @intention: "A call-argument list + the program rule list (callee scope) + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:33
  fields:
    args : ArgList
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- The Ast-walking input: the AST node + the program's RuleList (callee scope) +
-- src. Same shape as UndefAstState but carries `rules` instead of `binds` — this
-- is the load-bearing difference between the two passes: var-lint carries the
-- rule's bindings, callee-lint carries the whole program's rules.
concept BadCallState
  @intention: "An Ast node + the program rule list (callee scope) + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:33
  fields:
    node : Ast
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- count_badcall_args: sum count_badcall_ast over every argument of a call's
-- ArgList. Mutually recursive with count_badcall_ast (a call's arguments are
-- themselves Asts that may contain more calls — this is how NESTED calls like
-- g(h(1)) get walked: g's existence is checked at the AstCall node, then its
-- argument h(1) is recursed into here). Recurses over the ArgList tail (a field of
-- the input), so bound + breadcrumb. Threads the same rules (scope) + src down.
rule count_badcall_args
  @intention: "Total undefined-callee references across every argument of a call"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:33
  input:
    a : BadCallArgsState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match a.args:
      ArgCons(head, tail) => count_badcall_ast(BadCallState { node: head, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }) + count_badcall_args(BadCallArgsState { args: tail, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      ArgNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.args, a.rules, a.src]
      calls : [count_badcall_ast, count_badcall_args]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- count_badcall_ast: walk an Ast and count the AstCall references whose callee
-- name is NOT rule_named in the program. Mirrors count_undef_ast's structural
-- walk, but the node that contributes is AstCall (not AstVar), checked against the
-- program's rules (not the rule's bindings):
--   * AstCall(callee_start, callee_len, args) => (1 if rule_named == 0, the callee
--     does not exist) PLUS count_badcall_args over the arguments (so a nested call
--     inside an argument — g(h(1)) — is also checked). Parenthesized because there
--     is no operator precedence in Verbose: the `if ... then 1 else 0` is the
--     leftmost summand, the args walk the second.
--   * AstBin sums lhs + rhs; AstNeg / AstNot descend; AstIf sums cond + thn + els;
--     AstField walks its base (the field name is not a callee).
--   * AstVar / AstNum / AstStr / AstBool / AstErr carry no callee -> 0. (An AstVar
--     is a VARIABLE reference; that is the other pass's concern.)
-- Every recursive call threads the same rules (scope) + src. a.node is a FIELD of
-- the packed input (not the input), so bound + mandatory native recursion breadcrumb.
rule count_badcall_ast
  @intention: "Total undefined-callee references in an AST, given the program's rule list"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:33
  input:
    a : BadCallState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match a.node:
      AstNum(value) => 0
      AstBin(op, lhs, rhs) => count_badcall_ast(BadCallState { node: lhs, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }) + count_badcall_ast(BadCallState { node: rhs, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstNeg(inner) => count_badcall_ast(BadCallState { node: inner, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstNot(inner) => count_badcall_ast(BadCallState { node: inner, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstVar(start, len) => 0
      AstField(base, fstart, flen) => count_badcall_ast(BadCallState { node: base, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstCall(callee_start, callee_len, args) => (if rule_named(RuleNamedState { rules: a.rules, src: a.src, q_start: callee_start, q_len: callee_len }) == 0 then 1 else 0) + count_badcall_args(BadCallArgsState { args: args, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstIf(cond, thn, els) => count_badcall_ast(BadCallState { node: cond, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }) + count_badcall_ast(BadCallState { node: thn, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }) + count_badcall_ast(BadCallState { node: els, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstBool(value) => 0
      AstStr(start, len) => 0
      AstErr => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.node, a.rules, a.src]
      calls : [count_badcall_ast, count_badcall_args, rule_named]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- count_badcall_binds's input: the binding list whose RHSes are walked + the
-- program's RuleList (callee scope) + the source text. Unlike the var pass there
-- is no prefix: callee scope is program-wide and order-agnostic, so EVERY RHS sees
-- the FULL program rule list. (A let RHS may legitimately call a rule defined
-- later in the file, or call the rule it lives in.)
concept BadCallBindsState
  @intention: "A binding list + the program rule list (callee scope) + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:33
  fields:
    binds : Binding
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- count_badcall_binds: for each binding in the list, count_badcall_ast on its RHS
-- `value` against the FULL program rule list, then recurse on `rest`. The whole
-- program's rules are visible to every RHS (no prefix trick — callees are not
-- ordered like lets). Recurses over the binding tail (a field of the input), so
-- bound + breadcrumb; rules + src threaded unchanged.
rule count_badcall_binds
  @intention: "Total undefined-callee references across every binding's RHS"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:33
  input:
    b : BadCallBindsState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match b.binds:
      BCons(name_start, name_len, value, rest) => count_badcall_ast(BadCallState { node: value, rules: b.rules, src: b.src }) + count_badcall_binds(BadCallBindsState { binds: rest, rules: b.rules, src: b.src })
      BNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [b.binds, b.rules, b.src]
      calls : [count_badcall_ast, count_badcall_binds]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- badcall_rule's input: ONE rule declaration being checked + the FULL program
-- RuleList (so the checked rule may call itself or any other rule) + the source
-- text. The full list is threaded here, not the iterating tail — every rule
-- resolves its callees against every rule.
concept BadCallRuleState
  @intention: "A rule declaration + the full program rule list + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:33
  fields:
    rd : RuleDecl
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- badcall_rule: the undefined-callee count for ONE rule. Split the body Block into
-- its binding list and result expression, then sum:
--   * count_badcall_binds over the bindings (every let RHS's calls), PLUS
--   * count_badcall_ast over the result expression's calls.
-- Both halves resolve callees against the SAME full program RuleList `br.rules` —
-- callee scope is program-wide, so there is no per-let ordering and no prefix.
-- 0 = the rule calls only rules that exist. A rule calling ITSELF is clean (the
-- rule's own name is in `br.rules`). A rule calling a rule defined later is clean.
rule badcall_rule
  @intention: "Number of undefined-callee references in one rule (0 if all callees exist)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:33
  input:
    br : BadCallRuleState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let body = rd_body(br.rd)
    let binds = block_binds(body)
    let result = block_result(body)
    let bad_in_binds = count_badcall_binds(BadCallBindsState { binds: binds, rules: br.rules, src: br.src })
    out = bad_in_binds + count_badcall_ast(BadCallState { node: result, rules: br.rules, src: br.src })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [br.rd, br.rules, br.src]
      calls : [rd_body, block_binds, block_result, count_badcall_binds, count_badcall_ast]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- lint_callees_list's input: the rule list being ITERATED (`iter` advances each
-- step, one rule checked per step) + the FULL program rule list (`all`, fixed, so
-- every rule resolves callees against every rule) + the source text. The split
-- between `iter` and `all` is what makes callee scope program-wide: badcall_rule
-- always receives `all`, never the shrinking `iter`.
concept LintCalleesState
  @intention: "The rule list being iterated + the full program rule list + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:33
  fields:
    iter : RuleList
    all : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- lint_callees_list: sum badcall_rule over every rule in the program. Recurses
-- over `iter` (a field of the input), so bound + breadcrumb; `all` and `src` are
-- threaded unchanged so every rule sees the same full program rule list and the
-- same source buffer. Total undefined-callee references across the program.
rule lint_callees_list
  @intention: "Total undefined-callee references across every rule in a program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:33
  input:
    lc : LintCalleesState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match lc.iter:
      RCons(head, tail) => badcall_rule(BadCallRuleState { rd: head, rules: lc.all, src: lc.src }) + lint_callees_list(LintCalleesState { iter: tail, all: lc.all, src: lc.src })
      RNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [lc.iter, lc.all, lc.src]
      calls : [badcall_rule, lint_callees_list]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- lint_callees: the brick-15 money-shot driver. Tokenize the program source (with
-- indentation), parse the whole rule-decl sequence into a RuleList, then fold
-- badcall_rule over it with `iter = all = the parsed program` so every rule
-- resolves its callees against the entire program. Returns the TOTAL number of
-- undefined-callee references (calls to rules that do not exist). 0 = every call
-- in the program names a rule that exists.
--
--   lint_callees("rule f\n  logic:\n    out = f(1)") = 0   (f calls itself; f exists)
--   lint_callees("rule f\n  logic:\n    out = h(1)") = 1   (h is not a rule)
--   lint_callees("rule f\n  logic:\n    out = g(h(1))\nrule g\n  logic:\n    out = 2") = 1
--                                          (g exists; h does not — nested-call resolution)
--
-- NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source). Takes a ScanState (source + pos): source is
-- argv arg 1, pos is argv arg 2 (always 0). Independent of lint_program: an arg
-- that is an undefined VAR but a valid callee is 0 here, 1 there.
rule lint_callees
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, and count all undefined-callee references in a program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:33
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    out = lint_callees_list(LintCalleesState { iter: prog, all: prog, src: s.source })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, lint_callees_list]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 17: CALL-ARITY checking — the linter's SECOND inter-rule pass.
--
-- The callee pass (brick 15) asks "does the called rule EXIST?". This pass asks
-- the next question: "does the call pass the RIGHT NUMBER OF ARGUMENTS?". A call
-- `add(1)` to a rule `rule add(x, y)` is well-formed for the callee pass (add
-- exists) but WRONG here (1 argument supplied, 2 parameters declared). The
-- headline driver returns the total number of call sites whose argument count
-- does not match the called rule's parameter count.
--
-- ONLY EXISTING RULES ARE CHECKED. An undefined callee is the callee pass's
-- concern, not this one: if a call names a rule that does not exist, this pass
-- contributes 0 for that call (you cannot compare against an arity that is not
-- there). So the two passes are PROVABLY INDEPENDENT — `g(1, 2)` with g
-- undefined lints 1 under the callee pass and 0 here; `add(1)` with add a real
-- 2-param rule lints 0 under the callee pass and 1 here.
--
-- PROGRAM-WIDE, ORDER-AGNOSTIC SCOPE — identical to the callee pass: a call may
-- target a rule defined anywhere (forward, self, mutual). So the structure
-- mirrors the callee pass exactly: a membership-style probe over the program's
-- RuleList, an Ast/ArgList mutual walk, a per-rule split (binds + result), and
-- an iter/all fold over the program.
--
-- THE SENTINEL. rule_arity returns a NOT-FOUND sentinel of 1000000 (one million)
-- when no rule of the query name exists. A negative sentinel would be wrong: a
-- `number` field defaults to the range [0, i32::MAX], and the optimizer's
-- interval arithmetic could dead-eliminate a branch testing a negative value.
-- 1000000 is safely inside the field range, far above any real parameter count,
-- and the `found == 1000000` test is exact.
--
-- The rules:
--   * arg_list_len      — the number of arguments in a call's ArgList (mirrors
--                         param_list_len over ParamList).
--   * rule_arity        — the parameter count of the FIRST rule whose name span
--                         byte-equals the query span, or the 1000000 sentinel.
--                         Mirrors rule_named's RuleList walk but returns the arity.
--   * arity_mismatch    — 0/1 for ONE call: 0 if the callee is undefined OR the
--                         arg count matches; 1 if the callee exists and the count
--                         differs. A helper so the AstCall arm evaluates rule_arity
--                         exactly once (no inline double-evaluation).
--   * count_badarity_args — sum count_badarity_ast over an ArgList (nested calls).
--   * count_badarity_ast  — walk an Ast; at AstCall add arity_mismatch for THIS
--                           call, then recurse into the arguments.
--   * count_badarity_binds — sum count_badarity_ast over each binding's RHS.
--   * badarity_rule     — one rule's arity-mismatch count (binds RHSes + result).
--   * lint_arity_list   — fold badarity_rule over the program (iter advances,
--                         the full list `all` stays fixed).
--   * lint_arity        — the driver: tokenize -> parse_program -> lint_arity_list.
-- ============================================================================

-- arg_list_len: the number of arguments in a call's ArgList. Structural recursion
-- on the ArgCons tail (Phase C), the exact mirror of param_list_len over ParamList:
-- ArgCons contributes 1 + the tail's length, ArgNil is 0. Takes the bare ArgList
-- as input (no wrapper state) — same shape as param_list_len.
rule arg_list_len
  @intention: "Number of arguments in a call's argument list"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  input:
    al : ArgList
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match al:
      ArgCons(head, tail) => 1 + arg_list_len(tail)
      ArgNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [al]
      calls : [arg_list_len]
    termination:
      bound : 512
      structural : al


-- rule_arity's probe: the program's RuleList to search + the source text + the
-- query callee name's span (q_start, q_len). The arity-resolution analogue of
-- RuleNamedState — same fields, different return (an arity instead of a 0/1
-- membership flag).
concept RuleArityState
  @intention: "A rule list to search + the source text + the query callee name's span"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  fields:
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]
    q_start : number [0, 256]
    q_len : number [0, 256]


-- rule_arity: the parameter count of the FIRST rule whose NAME span byte-equals
-- the query span, or the 1000000 NOT-FOUND sentinel if no rule matches. Walks the
-- RuleList exactly like rule_named (same RCons/RNil cons-walk, same length-then-
-- bytes name_eq guard), but on a match it returns param_list_len(rd_params(head))
-- instead of 1, and on RNil it returns the sentinel instead of 0. The sentinel is
-- 1000000 (NOT -1) so the optimizer's interval arithmetic over the default
-- [0, i32::MAX] field range cannot dead-eliminate a negative-test branch. Recurses
-- over the RuleList tail (a field of the input), so bound + native breadcrumb.
rule rule_arity
  @intention: "Parameter count of the rule matching a callee name span, or 1000000 if none"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  input:
    st : RuleArityState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match st.rules:
      RCons(head, tail) => if rd_name_len(head) == st.q_len and name_eq(NameEqState { src: st.src, a_start: rd_name_start(head), b_start: st.q_start, len: st.q_len, off: 0 }) == 1 then param_list_len(rd_params(head)) else rule_arity(RuleArityState { rules: tail, src: st.src, q_start: st.q_start, q_len: st.q_len })
      RNil => 1000000
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [st.rules, st.src, st.q_start, st.q_len]
      calls : [rd_name_len, rd_name_start, name_eq, param_list_len, rd_params, rule_arity]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- arity_mismatch's input: ONE call's callee name span (callee_start, callee_len)
-- + that call's ArgList + the program's RuleList (the scope the callee is resolved
-- against) + the source text. Packs everything the per-call arity decision needs.
concept MismatchState
  @intention: "A call's callee span + its argument list + the program rule list + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  fields:
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]
    callee_start : number [0, 256]
    callee_len : number [0, 256]
    args : ArgList


-- arity_mismatch: 0/1 for ONE call. Resolve the callee's declared arity via
-- rule_arity (evaluated ONCE here, then bound to `found` — this is why this is a
-- helper rule and not an inline expression in the AstCall arm: an inline form
-- would have to call rule_arity twice). Then:
--   * found == 1000000 (callee does not exist) => 0. An undefined callee is the
--     callee pass's job; arity skips it.
--   * else compare the supplied argument count (arg_list_len) to `found`: equal
--     => 0 (well-formed call), different => 1 (arity mismatch).
-- No recursion of its own; it is a leaf decision summed by count_badarity_ast.
rule arity_mismatch
  @intention: "1 if a call to an existing rule supplies the wrong number of arguments, else 0"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  input:
    m : MismatchState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let found = rule_arity(RuleArityState { rules: m.rules, src: m.src, q_start: m.callee_start, q_len: m.callee_len })
    out = if found == 1000000 then 0 else (if arg_list_len(m.args) == found then 0 else 1)
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [m.rules, m.src, m.callee_start, m.callee_len, m.args]
      calls : [rule_arity, arg_list_len]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- count_badarity_args's input: the argument list to walk + the program's RuleList
-- (callee scope) + the source text. Mirrors BadCallArgsState exactly.
concept BadArityArgsState
  @intention: "A call-argument list + the program rule list (callee scope) + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  fields:
    args : ArgList
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- The Ast-walking input: the AST node + the program's RuleList (callee scope) +
-- src. Mirrors BadCallState exactly.
concept BadArityState
  @intention: "An Ast node + the program rule list (callee scope) + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  fields:
    node : Ast
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- count_badarity_args: sum count_badarity_ast over every argument of a call's
-- ArgList. Mutually recursive with count_badarity_ast — a nested call like h(1)
-- inside g(h(1)) is recursed into here (h's own arity is then checked at its
-- AstCall node). Recurses over the ArgList tail (a field of the input), so bound +
-- breadcrumb; rules (scope) + src threaded unchanged. Mirrors count_badcall_args.
rule count_badarity_args
  @intention: "Total arity-mismatch references across every argument of a call"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  input:
    a : BadArityArgsState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match a.args:
      ArgCons(head, tail) => count_badarity_ast(BadArityState { node: head, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }) + count_badarity_args(BadArityArgsState { args: tail, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      ArgNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.args, a.rules, a.src]
      calls : [count_badarity_ast, count_badarity_args]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- count_badarity_ast: walk an Ast and count the AstCall sites whose argument count
-- does not match the called rule's parameter count. Mirrors count_badcall_ast's
-- structural walk; the ONLY behavioral difference is the AstCall arm:
--   * AstCall(callee_start, callee_len, args) => arity_mismatch for THIS call (0 if
--     the callee is undefined or the count matches, 1 if it exists and differs)
--     PLUS count_badarity_args over the arguments (so a nested call's own arity is
--     also checked). The two summands are the per-call decision and the args walk.
--   * AstBin sums lhs + rhs; AstNeg / AstNot descend; AstIf sums cond + thn + els;
--     AstField walks its base. AstVar / AstNum / AstStr / AstBool / AstErr carry no
--     call -> 0.
-- a.node is a FIELD of the packed input (not the input), so bound + native breadcrumb.
rule count_badarity_ast
  @intention: "Total arity-mismatch references in an AST, given the program's rule list"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  input:
    a : BadArityState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match a.node:
      AstNum(value) => 0
      AstBin(op, lhs, rhs) => count_badarity_ast(BadArityState { node: lhs, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }) + count_badarity_ast(BadArityState { node: rhs, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstNeg(inner) => count_badarity_ast(BadArityState { node: inner, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstNot(inner) => count_badarity_ast(BadArityState { node: inner, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstVar(start, len) => 0
      AstField(base, fstart, flen) => count_badarity_ast(BadArityState { node: base, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstCall(callee_start, callee_len, args) => arity_mismatch(MismatchState { rules: a.rules, src: a.src, callee_start: callee_start, callee_len: callee_len, args: args }) + count_badarity_args(BadArityArgsState { args: args, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstIf(cond, thn, els) => count_badarity_ast(BadArityState { node: cond, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }) + count_badarity_ast(BadArityState { node: thn, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }) + count_badarity_ast(BadArityState { node: els, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstBool(value) => 0
      AstStr(start, len) => 0
      AstErr => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.node, a.rules, a.src]
      calls : [count_badarity_ast, count_badarity_args, arity_mismatch]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- count_badarity_binds's input: the binding list whose RHSes are walked + the
-- program's RuleList (callee scope) + the source text. No prefix — callee scope is
-- program-wide and order-agnostic, so every RHS sees the FULL program rule list.
-- Mirrors BadCallBindsState exactly.
concept BadArityBindsState
  @intention: "A binding list + the program rule list (callee scope) + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  fields:
    binds : Binding
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- count_badarity_binds: for each binding in the list, count_badarity_ast on its
-- RHS `value` against the FULL program rule list, then recurse on `rest`. Recurses
-- over the binding tail (a field of the input), so bound + breadcrumb; rules + src
-- threaded unchanged. Mirrors count_badcall_binds.
rule count_badarity_binds
  @intention: "Total arity-mismatch references across every binding's RHS"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  input:
    b : BadArityBindsState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match b.binds:
      BCons(name_start, name_len, value, rest) => count_badarity_ast(BadArityState { node: value, rules: b.rules, src: b.src }) + count_badarity_binds(BadArityBindsState { binds: rest, rules: b.rules, src: b.src })
      BNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [b.binds, b.rules, b.src]
      calls : [count_badarity_ast, count_badarity_binds]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- badarity_rule's input: ONE rule declaration being checked + the FULL program
-- RuleList (so the checked rule's calls resolve against every rule) + the source
-- text. Mirrors BadCallRuleState exactly.
concept BadArityRuleState
  @intention: "A rule declaration + the full program rule list + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  fields:
    rd : RuleDecl
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- badarity_rule: the arity-mismatch count for ONE rule. Split the body Block into
-- its binding list and result expression, then sum:
--   * count_badarity_binds over the bindings (every let RHS's calls), PLUS
--   * count_badarity_ast over the result expression's calls.
-- Both halves resolve callees against the SAME full program RuleList `br.rules`.
-- 0 = every call in this rule supplies the right number of arguments (or names a
-- rule that does not exist, which arity skips). Mirrors badcall_rule.
rule badarity_rule
  @intention: "Number of arity-mismatch references in one rule (0 if every call's arity is right)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  input:
    br : BadArityRuleState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let body = rd_body(br.rd)
    let binds = block_binds(body)
    let result = block_result(body)
    let bad_in_binds = count_badarity_binds(BadArityBindsState { binds: binds, rules: br.rules, src: br.src })
    out = bad_in_binds + count_badarity_ast(BadArityState { node: result, rules: br.rules, src: br.src })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [br.rd, br.rules, br.src]
      calls : [rd_body, block_binds, block_result, count_badarity_binds, count_badarity_ast]
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- lint_arity_list's input: the rule list being ITERATED (`iter` advances each step,
-- one rule checked per step) + the FULL program rule list (`all`, fixed, so every
-- rule resolves its calls against every rule) + the source text. The iter/all split
-- makes callee scope program-wide, exactly like LintCalleesState.
concept LintArityState
  @intention: "The rule list being iterated + the full program rule list + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  fields:
    iter : RuleList
    all : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- lint_arity_list: sum badarity_rule over every rule in the program. Recurses over
-- `iter` (a field of the input), so bound + breadcrumb; `all` and `src` are threaded
-- unchanged so every rule sees the same full program rule list and the same source
-- buffer. Total arity-mismatch references across the program. Mirrors lint_callees_list.
rule lint_arity_list
  @intention: "Total arity-mismatch references across every rule in a program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  input:
    la : LintArityState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match la.iter:
      RCons(head, tail) => badarity_rule(BadArityRuleState { rd: head, rules: la.all, src: la.src }) + lint_arity_list(LintArityState { iter: tail, all: la.all, src: la.src })
      RNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [la.iter, la.all, la.src]
      calls : [badarity_rule, lint_arity_list]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- lint_arity: the brick-17 money-shot driver. Tokenize the program source (with
-- indentation), parse the whole rule-decl sequence into a RuleList, then fold
-- badarity_rule over it with `iter = all = the parsed program` so every rule
-- resolves its calls' arities against the entire program. Returns the TOTAL number
-- of call sites whose argument count does not match the called rule's parameter
-- count (calls to non-existent rules are skipped — the callee pass's job). 0 =
-- every call to an existing rule supplies the right number of arguments.
--
--   lint_arity("rule add(x, y)\n  logic:\n    out = x + y\nrule f\n  logic:\n    out = add(1, 2)") = 0
--                                          (2 args supplied, 2 params declared)
--   lint_arity("rule add(x, y)\n  logic:\n    out = x + y\nrule f\n  logic:\n    out = add(1)") = 1
--                                          (1 arg supplied, 2 params declared)
--   lint_arity("rule f\n  logic:\n    out = g(1, 2)") = 0
--                                          (g undefined — arity skips it; the callee pass counts it)
--   lint_arity("rule f(n)\n  logic:\n    out = f(n)") = 0   (self-call, correct arity)
--   lint_arity("rule f(n)\n  logic:\n    out = f(n, n)") = 1 (self-call, wrong arity)
--
-- NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source). Takes a ScanState (source + pos): source is
-- argv arg 1, pos is argv arg 2 (always 0). Independent of lint_callees and
-- lint_program: a call to a missing rule is counted there, not here.
rule lint_arity
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, and count all arity-mismatch references in a program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:35
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    out = lint_arity_list(LintArityState { iter: prog, all: prog, src: s.source })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, lint_arity_list]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 19: a TYPE CHECKER in Verbose — the static pendant of brick 18's
-- interpreter. Where eval_ast_env computes a VALUE for an AST, type_of_env
-- computes a TYPE for it: a small type lattice {number, bool, ERROR} encoded as
-- non-negative codes (0 = number, 1 = bool, 3 = ERROR; 2 is reserved for a future
-- `text` brick). The checker MIRRORS the interpreter's recursive shape exactly —
-- same dispatch over the Ast variants, same per-rule fold over the program, same
-- type-environment threading through let-blocks — but propagates type codes
-- instead of numbers. type_check(source) returns the total number of type errors
-- (ill-typed let RHSs + ill-typed rule results) across the whole program.
--
-- WHY NON-NEGATIVE CODES. The optimizer's default field range is [0, i32::MAX],
-- so a -1 sentinel would let interval arithmetic dead-eliminate any `x < 0`
-- branch. Every type code here is >= 0, and the bin/if classifiers compare
-- against the literal codes 0/1/3 directly, never against a negative marker.
--
-- THE TYPE ENVIRONMENT. We REUSE the brick-10 Env concept as the TYPE env: each
-- ECons stores a name span and, in `val`, the bound name's TYPE code (instead of
-- its numeric value). env_lookup works UNCHANGED — it returns the stored `val`
-- (now a type code) on a match, or 0 on an unbound name. 0 = number is exactly
-- the right default: an unannotated PARAMETER is treated as number, matching the
-- interpreter's all-numbers world. build_tenv mirrors build_env: it folds the
-- let-bindings in source order, typing each RHS against the env built so far (so
-- `let b = 1 < 2` then `out = if b ...` sees b : bool), consing (name span, RHS
-- type) onto the front.
--
-- TYPING RULES (v1).
--   AstNum  => number ; AstBool => bool ; AstErr / AstField / AstStr => ERROR.
--   AstVar  => env_lookup (the stored type code; 0 = number for unbound params).
--   AstCall => number (every rule returns number in the interpreter's world).
--   AstNeg(e)  => number if type(e) = number, else ERROR.
--   AstNot(e)  => bool   if type(e) = bool,   else ERROR.
--   AstBin(op, l, r) with lt = type(l), rt = type(r):
--     arithmetic (+ - * / %): number if lt = rt = number, else ERROR.
--     comparison (== != < > <= >=): bool if lt = rt = number, else ERROR.
--        (v1: numbers only; bool comparison is a FUTURE brick.)
--     logic (and / or): bool if lt = rt = bool, else ERROR.
--   AstIf(c, t, e): if type(c) = bool AND type(t) = type(e) AND type(t) != ERROR
--                   then type(t), else ERROR.
--
-- TERMINATION. type_of_env + build_tenv (and the per-rule tcheck_binds) form a
-- recursive group/text SCC exactly like the interpreter's eval_ast_env +
-- build_env: each recursive call walks a strict sub-node / shorter tail, but that
-- shrinking value is a FIELD of a packed input concept (not the input itself), so
-- the `structural` proof does not fit. Like the interpreter rules they carry
-- bound-only termination and ACCEPT the mandatory native recursion breadcrumb.
-- The backstops are identical: finite Env / binding / rule lists and a finite AST
-- bounded by max_nodes, so every recursion strictly shrinks toward a leaf / Nil.
-- ============================================================================

-- type_of_env's input: the AST node to type, the TYPE environment (name span ->
-- type code) to resolve variable references against, and the source text the
-- name spans index into. Mirrors the interpreter's EvalEnvArg minus the program
-- (calls type to number unconditionally here, so no program threading is needed).
concept TypeArg
  @intention: "An Ast node + the type environment + the source text, for computing its type code"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:37
  fields:
    node : Ast
    tenv : Env
    src : text [..256]


-- bin_type's input: the binary operator code plus the ALREADY-COMPUTED type codes
-- of the two operands. A flat number-classifier (no recursion, no group field):
-- type_of_env types lhs and rhs first, then hands the (op, lt, rt) triple here.
concept BinTypeState
  @intention: "A binary op code + the two operand type codes, for classifying the result type"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:37
  fields:
    op : number [0, 64]
    lt : number [0, 8]
    rt : number [0, 8]


-- if_type's input: the type codes of an if's condition, then-branch, and
-- else-branch. A flat classifier (no recursion): type_of_env types all three
-- sub-expressions first, then hands the triple here for the well-typedness check.
concept IfTypeState
  @intention: "The condition/then/else type codes of an if, for classifying the result type"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:37
  fields:
    ct : number [0, 8]
    tt : number [0, 8]
    et : number [0, 8]


-- bin_type: classify the result type of a binary operation from its op code and
-- its two operand type codes (computed by type_of_env before the call). Arithmetic
-- ops require both operands number and yield number; comparisons require both
-- number and yield bool (v1: numeric comparison only — bool == bool is a future
-- brick); logic ops require both bool and yield bool. Any mismatch => ERROR (3),
-- and an unknown op also => ERROR. NON-recursive: a flat nested-if classifier,
-- bounded by 8 (it never recurses; the bound is the trivial leaf budget).
rule bin_type
  @intention: "Result type code of a binary op given its operand type codes (3 = ill-typed)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:37
  input:
    b : BinTypeState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = if b.op == 13 then (if b.lt == 0 and b.rt == 0 then 0 else 3) else if b.op == 14 then (if b.lt == 0 and b.rt == 0 then 0 else 3) else if b.op == 15 then (if b.lt == 0 and b.rt == 0 then 0 else 3) else if b.op == 16 then (if b.lt == 0 and b.rt == 0 then 0 else 3) else if b.op == 17 then (if b.lt == 0 and b.rt == 0 then 0 else 3) else if b.op == 1 then (if b.lt == 0 and b.rt == 0 then 1 else 3) else if b.op == 6 then (if b.lt == 0 and b.rt == 0 then 1 else 3) else if b.op == 19 then (if b.lt == 0 and b.rt == 0 then 1 else 3) else if b.op == 20 then (if b.lt == 0 and b.rt == 0 then 1 else 3) else if b.op == 5 then (if b.lt == 0 and b.rt == 0 then 1 else 3) else if b.op == 4 then (if b.lt == 0 and b.rt == 0 then 1 else 3) else if b.op == 30 then (if b.lt == 1 and b.rt == 1 then 1 else 3) else if b.op == 31 then (if b.lt == 1 and b.rt == 1 then 1 else 3) else 3
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [b.op, b.lt, b.rt]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 128


-- if_type: classify the result type of a conditional from the type codes of its
-- condition, then-branch, and else-branch. Well-typed iff the condition is bool
-- (ct == 1), both branches have the SAME type (tt == et), and that type is not
-- ERROR (tt != 3); the result type is then that branch type. Any failure => ERROR
-- (3). NON-recursive flat classifier, bounded by 8.
rule if_type
  @intention: "Result type code of an if given its sub-expression type codes (3 = ill-typed)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:37
  input:
    i : IfTypeState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = if i.ct == 1 and i.tt == i.et and i.tt != 3 then i.tt else 3
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [i.ct, i.tt, i.et]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 8


-- type_of_env: the dispatch. Mirrors eval_ast_env's match STRUCTURE arm-for-arm
-- but returns a TYPE code instead of a value. Leaves: AstNum => number (0),
-- AstBool => bool (1), AstErr / AstField / AstStr => ERROR (3), AstCall => number
-- (0, every rule returns number here). AstVar resolves its name in the type env
-- via env_lookup (the stored type code; 0 = number for unbound params). The unary
-- and binary forms recurse on their sub-nodes, threading the same tenv + src down,
-- then classify: AstNeg requires a number operand (else ERROR), AstNot a bool
-- operand (else ERROR), AstBin delegates to bin_type with the two recursively
-- computed operand types, AstIf delegates to if_type with the three recursively
-- computed sub-types. Bound-only termination + the native recursion breadcrumb:
-- each recursive call walks a strict sub-node of t.node, but t.node is a FIELD of
-- the packed input (not the input), so the `structural` proof does not fit — same
-- as eval_ast_env (see the header).
rule type_of_env
  @intention: "Compute an AST's type code, resolving variable references against a type environment"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:37
  input:
    t : TypeArg
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match t.node:
      AstNum(value) => 0
      AstBin(op, lhs, rhs) => bin_type(BinTypeState { op: op, lt: type_of_env(TypeArg { node: lhs, tenv: t.tenv, src: t.src }), rt: type_of_env(TypeArg { node: rhs, tenv: t.tenv, src: t.src }) })
      AstNeg(inner) => if type_of_env(TypeArg { node: inner, tenv: t.tenv, src: t.src }) == 0 then 0 else 3
      AstNot(inner) => if type_of_env(TypeArg { node: inner, tenv: t.tenv, src: t.src }) == 1 then 1 else 3
      AstVar(start, len) => env_lookup(EnvLookState { env: t.tenv, src: t.src, q_start: start, q_len: len })
      AstField(base, fstart, flen) => 3
      AstCall(callee_start, callee_len, args) => 0
      AstIf(cond, thn, els) => if_type(IfTypeState { ct: type_of_env(TypeArg { node: cond, tenv: t.tenv, src: t.src }), tt: type_of_env(TypeArg { node: thn, tenv: t.tenv, src: t.src }), et: type_of_env(TypeArg { node: els, tenv: t.tenv, src: t.src }) })
      AstBool(value) => 1
      AstStr(start, len) => 3
      AstErr => 3
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [t.node, t.tenv, t.src]
      calls : [type_of_env, env_lookup, bin_type, if_type]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- build_tenv's input: the remaining binding list, the type env built so far, and
-- the source text (each binding's RHS is TYPED against tenv_so_far, and AstVar
-- references in it resolve via src). Mirror of the interpreter's BuildEnvArg minus
-- the program field (type_of_env types calls to number without it).
concept BuildTArg
  @intention: "Remaining bindings + the type env built so far + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:37
  fields:
    binds : Binding
    tenv : Env
    src : text [..256]


-- build_tenv: fold the binding list (in source order) into a TYPE env. For each
-- BCons, compute the binding's RHS TYPE (type_of_env against the env built so far,
-- so `let b = 1 < 2` then `let c = b` sees b : bool), cons (name span, RHS type)
-- onto the FRONT, and recurse on the rest with the extended env. BNil returns the
-- accumulated env unchanged. Front-consing gives last-binding-wins shadowing in
-- env_lookup, exactly as build_env does for values. Bound-only termination + the
-- native recursion breadcrumb (packed input; the shrinking binding tail is a
-- field, not the input — see the header).
rule build_tenv
  @intention: "Fold a binding list into a type environment, typing each RHS against the env so far"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:37
  input:
    bt : BuildTArg
  output:
    out : Env
  logic:
    out = match bt.binds:
      BCons(name_start, name_len, value, rest) => build_tenv(BuildTArg { binds: rest, tenv: Env::ECons { name_start: name_start, name_len: name_len, val: type_of_env(TypeArg { node: value, tenv: bt.tenv, src: bt.src }), rest: bt.tenv }, src: bt.src })
      BNil => bt.tenv
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [bt.binds, bt.tenv, bt.src]
      calls : [build_tenv, type_of_env]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- tcheck_binds's input: the remaining binding list, the type env built so far, and
-- the source text. Mirrors build_tenv's threading but counts ill-typed RHSs rather
-- than accumulating an env.
concept TCheckBindsState
  @intention: "Remaining bindings + the type env built so far + the source text, for counting ill-typed RHSs"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:37
  fields:
    binds : Binding
    tenv : Env
    src : text [..256]


-- tcheck_binds: count the let RHSs whose TYPE is ERROR (3), threading the GROWING
-- type env so a let referencing an earlier one sees its type (e.g. `let b = 1 < 2`
-- then `let c = b and (2 < 3)` — c sees b : bool). For each BCons: type the RHS
-- against the env so far, add 1 to the count iff that type is ERROR, then recurse
-- on the rest with the env extended by (name span, RHS type) — exactly build_tenv's
-- extension step. The RHS type is computed twice (once for the count, once to
-- extend the env); type_of_env is pure, so the duplicate is correctness-neutral.
-- BNil contributes 0. Bound-only termination + the native recursion breadcrumb.
rule tcheck_binds
  @intention: "Count the let RHSs in a binding list whose type is ill-typed (ERROR)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:37
  input:
    tb : TCheckBindsState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match tb.binds:
      BCons(name_start, name_len, value, rest) => (if type_of_env(TypeArg { node: value, tenv: tb.tenv, src: tb.src }) == 3 then 1 else 0) + tcheck_binds(TCheckBindsState { binds: rest, tenv: Env::ECons { name_start: name_start, name_len: name_len, val: type_of_env(TypeArg { node: value, tenv: tb.tenv, src: tb.src }), rest: tb.tenv }, src: tb.src })
      BNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [tb.binds, tb.tenv, tb.src]
      calls : [type_of_env, tcheck_binds]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- tcheck_rule's input: one parsed rule declaration + the program source text.
concept TCheckRuleState
  @intention: "A parsed rule declaration + the program source text, for type-checking it"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:37
  fields:
    rd : RuleDecl
    src : text [..256]


-- tcheck_rule: type-check ONE rule. Split the body into its binding list and final
-- out-expression; build the FULL type env from all the lets (build_tenv over an
-- empty start env); count the ill-typed let RHSs (tcheck_binds, which threads the
-- same growing env so each RHS is typed in the right scope); type the result
-- expression against the full env; the rule's error count is the bad-bind count
-- plus 1 iff the result itself is ill-typed. Plain rule (uses `let`), mirroring
-- lint_rule's body-split shape. bound 4000 (it calls into the recursive checker
-- SCC, so it carries the SCC's bound rather than a trivial leaf budget).
rule tcheck_rule
  @intention: "Number of type errors in one rule (ill-typed let RHSs + ill-typed result; 0 if well-typed)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:37
  input:
    tr : TCheckRuleState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let body = rd_body(tr.rd)
    let binds = block_binds(body)
    let result = block_result(body)
    let tenv = build_tenv(BuildTArg { binds: binds, tenv: Env::ENil, src: tr.src })
    let bad_binds = tcheck_binds(TCheckBindsState { binds: binds, tenv: Env::ENil, src: tr.src })
    let result_ty = type_of_env(TypeArg { node: result, tenv: tenv, src: tr.src })
    out = bad_binds + (if result_ty == 3 then 1 else 0)
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [tr.rd, tr.src]
      calls : [rd_body, block_binds, block_result, build_tenv, tcheck_binds, type_of_env]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- tcheck_list's input: the rule list being folded + the program source text.
-- Mirrors LintCalleesState minus the `all` program field (this pass needs no
-- inter-rule resolution — each rule is type-checked in isolation).
concept TCheckListState
  @intention: "A rule list + the program source text, for folding the type check over the program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:37
  fields:
    iter : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- tcheck_list: fold tcheck_rule over the program, summing each rule's type-error
-- count. Mirror of lint_callees_list. Bound-only termination + the native
-- recursion breadcrumb (the shrinking rule-list tail is a field of the packed
-- input, not the input itself).
rule tcheck_list
  @intention: "Total number of type errors across every rule in a program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:37
  input:
    tl : TCheckListState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match tl.iter:
      RCons(head, tail) => tcheck_rule(TCheckRuleState { rd: head, src: tl.src }) + tcheck_list(TCheckListState { iter: tail, src: tl.src })
      RNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [tl.iter, tl.src]
      calls : [tcheck_rule, tcheck_list]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- type_check: the brick-19 money-shot driver. Tokenize the program source (with
-- indentation), parse the whole rule-decl sequence into a RuleList, then fold the
-- type check over it. Returns the TOTAL number of type errors (ill-typed let RHSs
-- + ill-typed rule results) in the program. 0 = every let RHS and every rule
-- result is well-typed.
--
--   type_check("rule f\n  logic:\n    out = 1 + 2")          = 0  (number + number)
--   type_check("rule f\n  logic:\n    out = 1 + (2 < 3)")    = 1  (number + bool)
--   type_check("rule f\n  logic:\n    out = if 5 then 1 else 2")        = 1 (non-bool cond)
--   type_check("rule f\n  logic:\n    out = if 1 < 2 then 3 else 4")    = 0 (bool cond, num branches)
--   type_check("rule f\n  logic:\n    let b = 1 < 2\n    out = if b then 1 else 2") = 0
--            (THE SHOWCASE: b is inferred bool from its RHS, so using it as a
--             condition is well-typed — proves the TYPE ENVIRONMENT works)
--   type_check("rule f\n  logic:\n    let n = 5\n    out = if n then 1 else 2")     = 1
--            (n is number, used as condition -> error: the type env distinguishes
--             it from the bool case above)
--   type_check("rule f\n  logic:\n    out = (1 < 2) and (3 < 4)")       = 0  (bool and bool)
--   type_check("rule f\n  logic:\n    out = (1 < 2) and 3")             = 1  (and with a number)
--
-- NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source). Takes a ScanState (source + pos): source is
-- argv arg 1, pos is argv arg 2 (always 0). Independent of the lint passes — a
-- type-correct program with an undefined callee lints 1 there and 0 here.
rule type_check
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, and count all type errors in a program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:37
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    out = tcheck_list(TCheckListState { iter: prog, src: s.source })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, tcheck_list]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 21: CALL-SITE ARGUMENT TYPE checking — where the parser (brick 20 typed
-- params) and the type checker (brick 19) finally meet.
--
-- The callee pass (brick 15) asks "does the called rule EXIST?". The arity pass
-- (brick 17) asks "does it pass the RIGHT NUMBER of arguments?". This pass asks
-- the next question: "does each argument's TYPE match the callee's DECLARED
-- parameter type?". A call `f(1 < 2)` to a rule `rule f(x : number)` is well-formed
-- for the callee pass (f exists) and the arity pass (1 arg, 1 param) but WRONG
-- here — a bool argument flows into a number parameter.
--
-- ORTHOGONAL to brick 19's type_check. An argument whose OWN type is already
-- ERROR (3) is brick 19's concern and is SKIPPED here (no double-counting — the
-- same discipline that keeps lint_arity from re-flagging what lint_callees flags).
-- A WELL-typed argument of the WRONG type (a bool where a number is declared) is
-- exactly what this pass catches.
--
-- TYPING THE ARGUMENT. The caller's type env is seeded with the caller's OWN
-- params' declared types (param_to_tenv) THEN extended with its let bindings
-- (build_tenv), so an argument that references a typed param of the caller is
-- typed correctly. THE SHOWCASE: `rule g(b : bool) ... out = f(b)` with
-- `rule f(x : number)` flags `b` — b is bool by g's declaration, passed to f's
-- number param.
--
-- THE LOCKSTEP. Per call, walk the argument list and the callee's parameter list
-- together (argtype_args). For each (arg, param) pair, count a mismatch iff the
-- param EXISTS (phead_ty != 9) AND the arg's type differs from the param's type
-- AND the arg's type is not ERROR (3). When one list runs out, pairing stops —
-- count mismatches are lint_arity's concern, not this pass's. Untyped params
-- default to number (0) — brick 20's convention — so a bool passed to an untyped
-- param IS flagged (documented behaviour).
--
-- CALLEE RESOLUTION. find_rule (brick 18) resolves the callee name span against
-- the whole program; on no match it returns the SENTINEL MkRule with PNil params,
-- so an undefined callee yields no pairs and no arg-type errors (lint_callees
-- flags the missing callee separately). A call's RESULT type stays number (0):
-- there is no return-type syntax yet, so type_of_env's AstCall arm is unchanged —
-- this brick adds a SEPARATE counting pass, it does NOT touch type_of_env.
--
-- TERMINATION. argtype_ast + argtype_args + argtype_binds form a recursive
-- group/text SCC (like the interpreter's eval_ast_env + the type checker's
-- type_of_env), calling into type_of_env. Each recursive call walks a strict
-- sub-node / shorter tail, but that shrinking value is a FIELD of a packed input
-- concept (not the input itself), so the `structural` proof does not fit — they
-- carry bound-only termination and ACCEPT the mandatory native recursion
-- breadcrumb. The backstops are the same: finite Env / binding / param / rule
-- lists and a finite AST bounded by max_nodes.
-- ============================================================================

-- param_to_tenv: convert a rule's ParamList into a TYPE env (Env), storing each
-- parameter's DECLARED type code in the entry's `val` slot. Mirror of brick 16's
-- param_to_binding, but for the type checker: where param_to_binding consed a
-- dummy AstNum value (it only ever needed the NAME span), this carries the type
-- code so an argument referencing a typed param of the CALLER resolves to that
-- param's declared type via env_lookup. The resulting env is the rule's INITIAL
-- type scope, then build_tenv extends it with the lets. Structural recursion on
-- the PCons tail (Phase C), like param_to_binding / param_list_len.
rule param_to_tenv
  @intention: "Convert a parameter list into a type environment (params at their declared types)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:39
  input:
    pl : ParamList
  output:
    out : Env
  logic:
    out = match pl:
      PCons(name_start, name_len, ty, rest) => Env::ECons { name_start: name_start, name_len: name_len, val: ty, rest: param_to_tenv(rest) }
      PNil => Env::ENil
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [pl]
      calls : [param_to_tenv]
    termination:
      bound : 4000
      structural : pl


-- phead_ty: the DECLARED type code of the HEAD parameter of a ParamList — or the
-- sentinel 9 (no such param) when the list is empty. The lockstep walk in
-- argtype_args uses 9 to detect "the callee has no more parameters", so the extra
-- arguments of an over-long call are NOT paired (their count mismatch is
-- lint_arity's concern). Distinguishable from every real type code (0/1/2).
-- Non-recursive accessor, like rl_head_params.
rule phead_ty
  @intention: "The declared type code of a parameter list's head param (sentinel 9 if empty)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:39
  input:
    pl : ParamList
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match pl:
      PCons(name_start, name_len, ty, rest) => ty
      PNil => 9
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [pl]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- ptail: the TAIL of a ParamList (the parameters after the head) — or PNil when
-- the list is empty. The other half of the lockstep: argtype_args advances the
-- param list with ptail in step with the argument tail, so the n-th argument is
-- paired with the n-th parameter. Non-recursive accessor, like rl_head_params.
rule ptail
  @intention: "The tail of a parameter list (PNil if empty)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:39
  input:
    pl : ParamList
  output:
    out : ParamList
  logic:
    out = match pl:
      PCons(name_start, name_len, ty, rest) => rest
      PNil => ParamList::PNil
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [pl]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- argtype_args's input: the call's argument list to walk in LOCKSTEP with the
-- callee's parameter list, plus the caller's type env (so each argument is typed
-- in the caller's scope), the source text, and the program rule list (so a nested
-- call inside an argument resolves its own callee). The two lists advance together
-- (args via the ArgCons tail, params via ptail).
concept ArgTypeArgsState
  @intention: "A call's argument list + the callee's param list + caller type env + source + program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:39
  fields:
    args : ArgList
    params : ParamList
    tenv : Env
    src : text [..256]
    prog : RuleList


-- The Ast-walking input: the AST node to walk for call sites, the caller's type
-- env (used to type each argument), the source text, and the program rule list
-- (callee scope for find_rule). Same shape as brick 19's TypeArg plus a `prog`
-- field — argtype needs the program to resolve each call's callee, where the
-- type checker only ever typed calls to number.
concept ArgTypeState
  @intention: "An Ast node + caller type env + source text + program rule list, for the arg-type walk"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:39
  fields:
    node : Ast
    tenv : Env
    src : text [..256]
    prog : RuleList


-- argtype_binds's input: the binding list whose RHSes are walked for call sites,
-- the type env built so far (each RHS is typed against it, and a later let's RHS
-- sees an earlier let's type), the source text, and the program rule list. Mirror
-- of brick 19's BuildTArg/TCheckBindsState shape plus `prog`.
concept ArgTypeBindsState
  @intention: "A binding list + the type env so far + source text + program rule list, for the arg-type walk"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:39
  fields:
    binds : Binding
    tenv : Env
    src : text [..256]
    prog : RuleList


-- argtype_rule's input: ONE parsed rule declaration + the FULL program rule list
-- (so each call resolves its callee against every rule) + the program source text.
concept ArgTypeRuleState
  @intention: "A rule declaration + the full program rule list + the source text, for arg-type checking it"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:39
  fields:
    rd : RuleDecl
    prog : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- argtype_list's input: the rule list being ITERATED (`iter` advances each step,
-- one rule checked per step) + the FULL program rule list (`all`, fixed, so every
-- call resolves its callee against every rule) + the source text. The iter/all
-- split mirrors lint_callees_list: argtype_rule always receives `all`, never the
-- shrinking `iter`, so callee resolution stays program-wide.
concept ArgTypeListState
  @intention: "The rule list being iterated + the full program rule list + the source text"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:39
  fields:
    iter : RuleList
    all : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- argtype_args: walk a call's argument list in LOCKSTEP with the callee's
-- parameter list, summing three contributions per (arg, param) pair:
--   * the MISMATCH count for this pair: 1 iff the param exists (phead_ty != 9)
--     AND the argument's type (typed against the caller's env) differs from the
--     param's declared type AND the argument's type is not ERROR (3 — that is
--     brick 19's concern, skipped here to avoid double-counting). Parenthesized
--     because Verbose has no operator precedence: the `if ... then 1 else 0` is
--     the leftmost summand. type_of_env(head) appears three times — it is pure,
--     so the repetition is correctness-neutral.
--   * argtype_ast over the argument itself, so a NESTED call inside an argument
--     (f(g(1 < 2))) has its own call sites checked.
--   * argtype_args over the tails: the argument tail paired with ptail(params),
--     advancing both lists one step.
-- ArgNil ends the walk (0). When the param list runs out first, phead_ty returns
-- 9, so the extra arguments contribute no mismatch (their count is lint_arity's
-- concern). a.args is a FIELD of the packed input, so bound + native breadcrumb.
rule argtype_args
  @intention: "Total arg-type mismatches across a call's arguments, paired against the callee's params"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:39
  input:
    a : ArgTypeArgsState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match a.args:
      ArgCons(head, tail) => (if phead_ty(a.params) != 9 and type_of_env(TypeArg { node: head, tenv: a.tenv, src: a.src }) != phead_ty(a.params) and type_of_env(TypeArg { node: head, tenv: a.tenv, src: a.src }) != 3 then 1 else 0) + argtype_ast(ArgTypeState { node: head, tenv: a.tenv, src: a.src, prog: a.prog }) + argtype_args(ArgTypeArgsState { args: tail, params: ptail(a.params), tenv: a.tenv, src: a.src, prog: a.prog })
      ArgNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.args, a.params, a.tenv, a.src, a.prog]
      calls : [phead_ty, type_of_env, argtype_ast, ptail, argtype_args]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- argtype_ast: walk an Ast and count, at EVERY call site, the arguments whose type
-- mismatches the callee's declared parameter type. Mirrors count_badcall_ast's
-- structural walk, but the load-bearing arm is AstCall:
--   * AstCall(callee_start, callee_len, args) => argtype_args over the call's
--     arguments, paired against the callee's params. The callee is resolved with
--     find_rule (the sentinel MkRule on no match has PNil params -> no pairs ->
--     no errors, so an undefined callee is silently skipped here — lint_callees
--     flags it). rd_params reads the matched rule's parameter list.
--   * AstBin sums lhs + rhs; AstNeg / AstNot descend; AstIf sums cond + thn + els;
--     AstField walks its base (the field name carries no call).
--   * AstVar / AstNum / AstStr / AstBool / AstErr carry no call site -> 0.
-- Every recursive call threads the same tenv (caller scope) + src + prog. a.node
-- is a FIELD of the packed input, so bound + the mandatory native breadcrumb.
rule argtype_ast
  @intention: "Total arg-type mismatches in an AST, resolving each call's callee against the program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:39
  input:
    a : ArgTypeState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match a.node:
      AstNum(value) => 0
      AstBool(value) => 0
      AstVar(start, len) => 0
      AstStr(start, len) => 0
      AstErr => 0
      AstBin(op, lhs, rhs) => argtype_ast(ArgTypeState { node: lhs, tenv: a.tenv, src: a.src, prog: a.prog }) + argtype_ast(ArgTypeState { node: rhs, tenv: a.tenv, src: a.src, prog: a.prog })
      AstNeg(inner) => argtype_ast(ArgTypeState { node: inner, tenv: a.tenv, src: a.src, prog: a.prog })
      AstNot(inner) => argtype_ast(ArgTypeState { node: inner, tenv: a.tenv, src: a.src, prog: a.prog })
      AstField(base, fstart, flen) => argtype_ast(ArgTypeState { node: base, tenv: a.tenv, src: a.src, prog: a.prog })
      AstIf(cond, thn, els) => argtype_ast(ArgTypeState { node: cond, tenv: a.tenv, src: a.src, prog: a.prog }) + argtype_ast(ArgTypeState { node: thn, tenv: a.tenv, src: a.src, prog: a.prog }) + argtype_ast(ArgTypeState { node: els, tenv: a.tenv, src: a.src, prog: a.prog })
      AstCall(callee_start, callee_len, args) => argtype_args(ArgTypeArgsState { args: args, params: rd_params(find_rule(FindRuleState { rules: a.prog, src: a.src, q_start: callee_start, q_len: callee_len })), tenv: a.tenv, src: a.src, prog: a.prog })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.node, a.tenv, a.src, a.prog]
      calls : [argtype_ast, argtype_args, rd_params, find_rule]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- argtype_binds: for each binding in the list, walk its RHS for call sites
-- (argtype_ast against the type env built SO FAR), then recurse on the rest with
-- the env extended by (name span, RHS type) — so a later let's RHS references an
-- earlier let at its inferred type, exactly build_tenv's extension step. The RHS
-- type for the env extension is computed via type_of_env (pure). BNil contributes
-- 0. b.binds is a FIELD of the packed input, so bound + native breadcrumb.
rule argtype_binds
  @intention: "Total arg-type mismatches across every binding's RHS, threading the growing type env"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:39
  input:
    a : ArgTypeBindsState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match a.binds:
      BCons(name_start, name_len, value, rest) => argtype_ast(ArgTypeState { node: value, tenv: a.tenv, src: a.src, prog: a.prog }) + argtype_binds(ArgTypeBindsState { binds: rest, tenv: Env::ECons { name_start: name_start, name_len: name_len, val: type_of_env(TypeArg { node: value, tenv: a.tenv, src: a.src }), rest: a.tenv }, src: a.src, prog: a.prog })
      BNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.binds, a.tenv, a.src, a.prog]
      calls : [argtype_ast, type_of_env, argtype_binds]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- argtype_rule: the arg-type mismatch count for ONE rule. Seed the type env with
-- the rule's OWN params at their declared types (param_to_tenv), so an argument
-- referencing a caller param is typed correctly. Split the body into its bindings
-- and result; build the FULL env from the lets on top of the param env
-- (build_tenv); count call-site arg-type mismatches in the let RHSs (argtype_binds
-- threading the same growing env starting from the param env) PLUS in the result
-- expression (argtype_ast against the full env). Both halves resolve callees
-- against the FULL program list `a.prog`. Plain rule (uses `let`), mirroring
-- tcheck_rule's body-split shape. bound 4000 (it calls into the recursive SCC).
rule argtype_rule
  @intention: "Number of call-site arg-type mismatches in one rule (0 if every argument fits its param)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:39
  input:
    a : ArgTypeRuleState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let params = rd_params(a.rd)
    let ptenv = param_to_tenv(params)
    let body = rd_body(a.rd)
    let binds = block_binds(body)
    let result = block_result(body)
    let full_tenv = build_tenv(BuildTArg { binds: binds, tenv: ptenv, src: a.src })
    let in_binds = argtype_binds(ArgTypeBindsState { binds: binds, tenv: ptenv, src: a.src, prog: a.prog })
    out = in_binds + argtype_ast(ArgTypeState { node: result, tenv: full_tenv, src: a.src, prog: a.prog })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.rd, a.prog, a.src]
      calls : [rd_params, param_to_tenv, rd_body, block_binds, block_result, build_tenv, argtype_binds, argtype_ast]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- argtype_list: fold argtype_rule over the program, summing each rule's arg-type
-- mismatch count. Mirror of lint_callees_list: `iter` advances each step (a field
-- of the packed input, so bound + breadcrumb), while `all` and `src` are threaded
-- unchanged so every rule resolves its callees against the same full program.
rule argtype_list
  @intention: "Total call-site arg-type mismatches across every rule in a program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:39
  input:
    a : ArgTypeListState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match a.iter:
      RCons(head, tail) => argtype_rule(ArgTypeRuleState { rd: head, prog: a.all, src: a.src }) + argtype_list(ArgTypeListState { iter: tail, all: a.all, src: a.src })
      RNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.iter, a.all, a.src]
      calls : [argtype_rule, argtype_list]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- argtype_check: the brick-21 money-shot driver. Tokenize the program source (with
-- indentation), parse the whole rule-decl sequence into a RuleList, then fold the
-- arg-type check over it with `iter = all = the parsed program` so every call
-- resolves its callee against the entire program. Returns the TOTAL number of
-- call-site arguments whose type does NOT match the callee's declared parameter
-- type. 0 = every argument fits its parameter's type.
--
--   argtype_check("rule main\n  logic:\n    out = f(5)\nrule f(x : number)\n  logic:\n    out = x")       = 0
--            (number arg to number param)
--   argtype_check("rule main\n  logic:\n    out = f(1 < 2)\nrule f(x : number)\n  logic:\n    out = x")    = 1
--            (bool arg to number param)
--   argtype_check("rule main\n  logic:\n    out = f(1 < 2)\nrule f(x : bool)\n  logic:\n    out = if x then 1 else 0") = 0
--            (bool arg to bool param)
--   argtype_check("rule g(b : bool)\n  logic:\n    out = f(b)\nrule f(x : number)\n  logic:\n    out = x") = 1
--            (THE SHOWCASE: b is bool by g's declaration, passed to f's number param)
--   argtype_check("rule g(b : number)\n  logic:\n    out = f(b)\nrule f(x : number)\n  logic:\n    out = x") = 0
--            (b is number — the well-typed version of the showcase)
--   argtype_check("rule main\n  logic:\n    out = add(5, 1 < 2)\nrule add(x : number, y : number)\n  logic:\n    out = x + y") = 1
--            (two args, the second a bool against a number param)
--   argtype_check("rule main\n  logic:\n    out = add(1 < 2, 3 < 4)\nrule add(x : number, y : number)\n  logic:\n    out = x + y") = 2
--            (both args bool against number params)
--   argtype_check("rule main\n  logic:\n    out = f(g(1 < 2))\nrule f(x : number)\n  logic:\n    out = x\nrule g(y : number)\n  logic:\n    out = y") = 1
--            (g's arg 1<2 is bool vs g's number param; f's arg g(...) is number(0) -> ok)
--   argtype_check("rule main\n  logic:\n    out = h(1 < 2)")                                              = 0
--            (h does not exist -> sentinel PNil params -> no pair; lint_callees flags h)
--
-- NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source). Takes a ScanState (source + pos): source is
-- argv arg 1, pos is argv arg 2 (always 0). Orthogonal to brick 19's type_check —
-- an argument that is itself ill-typed is type_check's concern (skipped here), a
-- well-typed argument of the wrong type is this pass's concern (skipped there).
rule argtype_check
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, and count all call-site arguments whose type mismatches the callee's param"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:39
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    out = argtype_list(ArgTypeListState { iter: prog, all: prog, src: s.source })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, argtype_list]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 22: the FULL PIPELINE — the self-hosting compiler's main(). Every prior
-- driver (lint_program, lint_callees, lint_arity, type_check, argtype_check)
-- tokenizes and parses the source on its OWN, then runs one analysis. This driver
-- tokenizes and parses the program EXACTLY ONCE, then runs ALL of them over the
-- single shared RuleList. That is the consolidation: one front end, every check,
-- in one pass over one AST. The return value is the TOTAL diagnostic count across
-- all five analyses — 0 iff the program passes every check the compiler knows how
-- to make.
--
-- The five analyses, summed over the same parsed `prog`:
--   * lint_list           — undefined variables AND use-before-def (brick 13/14).
--   * lint_callees_list   — calls to rules that do not exist (brick 15).
--   * lint_arity_list     — calls with the wrong number of arguments (brick 17).
--   * tcheck_list         — ill-typed expressions, {number,bool} system (brick 19).
--   * argtype_list        — call args whose type mismatches the declared param (brick 21).
-- Each list-rule already takes a RuleList; check_program just hands them all the
-- same one. The categories are orthogonal by construction (an undefined callee is
-- not an arity error; an arg that is itself ill-typed is type_check's, not
-- argtype's) so the sum double-counts nothing — every diagnostic is one unit.
--
--   check_program("rule add(x : number, y : number)\n  logic:\n    out = x + y\nrule main\n  logic:\n    out = add(1, 2)") = 0
--            (clean: callee exists, arity 2/2, args number/number, no undef, well-typed)
--   check_program("rule f\n  logic:\n    out = x + y")                = 2   (x and y undefined)
--   check_program("rule f\n  logic:\n    out = 1 + (2 < 3)")          = 1   (number + bool)
--   check_program("rule main\n  logic:\n    out = g(1)")              = 1   (g does not exist)
--   check_program("rule f(a)\n  logic:\n    out = 1\nrule main\n  logic:\n    out = f(1, 2)") = 1  (arity 1 vs 2)
--   check_program("rule f(x : number)\n  logic:\n    out = z\nrule main\n  logic:\n    out = f(1 < 2)") = 2
--            (z undefined in f, AND a bool arg to f's number param — two categories at once)
--
-- NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source). Takes a ScanState (source + pos): source is
-- argv arg 1, pos is argv arg 2 (always 0). This is the closest thing yet to a
-- "verbosec written in Verbose" entry point — lex, parse, and verify, in one call.
rule check_program
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse once, run all five analyses, and return the total diagnostic count"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:40
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let e_undef = lint_list(LintListState { rl: prog, src: s.source })
    let e_callee = lint_callees_list(LintCalleesState { iter: prog, all: prog, src: s.source })
    let e_arity = lint_arity_list(LintArityState { iter: prog, all: prog, src: s.source })
    let e_type = tcheck_list(TCheckListState { iter: prog, src: s.source })
    let e_argtype = argtype_list(ArgTypeListState { iter: prog, all: prog, src: s.source })
    out = e_undef + e_callee + e_arity + e_type + e_argtype
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, lint_list, lint_callees_list, lint_arity_list, tcheck_list, argtype_list]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 23: a STRUCTURED diagnostic. Brick 22's check_program returns the TOTAL
-- error count over the whole program — a single number. This brick LOCALIZES the
-- first failure: which rule (by 0-based index, source order) and which CATEGORY of
-- error it is. The category is decided per rule by `rule_category`, in a fixed
-- precedence order (the FIRST failing analysis wins, so a rule with several
-- problems reports exactly one — the earliest in this list):
--   0 = clean (no diagnostics)
--   1 = undefined variable / use-before-def      (lint_rule)
--   2 = undefined callee                          (badcall_rule)
--   3 = wrong arity                               (badarity_rule)
--   4 = ill-typed expression                      (tcheck_rule)
--   5 = call-argument type mismatch               (argtype_rule)
-- `find_diag` then walks the program with a running index and returns the FIRST
-- rule whose category != 0, as a Diag { rule_index, category }. A clean program
-- yields Diag { rule_index: 9999, category: 0 } (9999 = "no bad rule"). The two
-- drivers `first_bad_rule` / `first_bad_category` expose the two fields to argv.
-- The five per-rule analyses are reused verbatim from bricks 13-21; this brick
-- only composes them, the same way check_program composes the five list-rules.
-- ============================================================================

-- rule_category's input: ONE parsed rule declaration + the FULL program rule list
-- (`prog`, so the rule's calls resolve against every rule for the callee / arity /
-- arg-type passes) + the source text. Same shape as BadCallRuleState / ArgTypeRuleState
-- but named generically because it feeds ALL five per-rule analyses, not one.
concept RuleCatState
  @intention: "A rule declaration + the full program rule list + the source text, for categorizing its first error"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:41
  fields:
    rd : RuleDecl
    prog : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- find_diag's input: the rule list being ITERATED (`iter` advances each step, one
-- rule categorized per step) + the FULL program rule list (`all`, fixed, so each
-- rule's calls resolve against every rule) + the source text + the running 0-based
-- index of the rule at the head of `iter`. The iter/all split mirrors
-- lint_callees_list / argtype_list: rule_category always receives `all`, never the
-- shrinking `iter` tail. `idx` is the source position reported in the Diag.
concept FindDiagState
  @intention: "The rule list being walked + the full program + the source + the running rule index"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:41
  fields:
    iter : RuleList
    all : RuleList
    src : text [..256]
    idx : number [0, 4096]


-- rule_category: the FIRST failing category of ONE rule, in the fixed precedence
-- order documented above. A flat if/else chain of calls to the five per-rule
-- analyses — NON-recursive (each per-rule rule is itself recursive, but this rule
-- just calls them in order and returns the first nonzero category's code). The
-- precedence is purely the source order of the chain: lint (1) before callee (2)
-- before arity (3) before type (4) before arg-type (5). bound is a termination
-- BUDGET for the non-recursive if-chain (the verifier counts the actual operation
-- count of the chain, not a recursion depth); 1024 comfortably exceeds it.
rule rule_category
  @intention: "The first failing analysis category of one rule (precedence-ordered), 0 if clean"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:41
  input:
    rc : RuleCatState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = if lint_rule(LintRuleState { rd: rc.rd, src: rc.src }) > 0 then 1 else if badcall_rule(BadCallRuleState { rd: rc.rd, rules: rc.prog, src: rc.src }) > 0 then 2 else if badarity_rule(BadArityRuleState { rd: rc.rd, rules: rc.prog, src: rc.src }) > 0 then 3 else if tcheck_rule(TCheckRuleState { rd: rc.rd, src: rc.src }) > 0 then 4 else if argtype_rule(ArgTypeRuleState { rd: rc.rd, prog: rc.prog, src: rc.src }) > 0 then 5 else 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [rc.rd, rc.prog, rc.src]
      calls : [lint_rule, badcall_rule, badarity_rule, tcheck_rule, argtype_rule]
    termination:
      bound : 1024


-- find_diag: walk the program rule list, categorizing each rule, and return the
-- FIRST one whose category > 0 as MkDiag(idx, category); on RNil (every rule
-- clean) return the sentinel MkDiag(9999, 0). Recurses on the tail with idx+1,
-- mirroring find_rule's front-to-back walk but returning a Diag GROUP VALUE rather
-- than a RuleDecl (same group-return ABI). rule_category is called twice per
-- failing head — once for the guard, once for the reported value — which is fine
-- because it is pure (no effects, same inputs => same number). Bound-only
-- termination + the native recursion breadcrumb (the shrinking `iter` tail is a
-- field of the packed input, not the input itself).
rule find_diag
  @intention: "The first rule (by index) whose category is nonzero, as a Diag; sentinel MkDiag(9999,0) if all clean"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:41
  input:
    fd : FindDiagState
  output:
    out : Diag
  logic:
    out = match fd.iter:
      RCons(head, tail) => if rule_category(RuleCatState { rd: head, prog: fd.all, src: fd.src }) > 0 then Diag::MkDiag { rule_index: fd.idx, category: rule_category(RuleCatState { rd: head, prog: fd.all, src: fd.src }), span_start: 9999, span_len: 0 } else find_diag(FindDiagState { iter: tail, all: fd.all, src: fd.src, idx: fd.idx + 1 })
      RNil => Diag::MkDiag { rule_index: 9999, category: 0, span_start: 9999, span_len: 0 }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [fd.iter, fd.all, fd.src, fd.idx]
      calls : [rule_category, find_diag]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- diag_index: the rule index of a Diag. Bare-group accessor, same idiom as
-- rd_body / block_binds (input is a bare group value `d : Diag`).
rule diag_index
  @intention: "The 0-based rule index carried by a Diag"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:41
  input:
    d : Diag
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match d:
      MkDiag(rule_index, category, span_start, span_len) => rule_index
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [d]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- diag_cat: the error category of a Diag. Mirror of diag_index.
rule diag_cat
  @intention: "The error category code carried by a Diag"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:41
  input:
    d : Diag
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match d:
      MkDiag(rule_index, category, span_start, span_len) => category
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [d]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- diag_span_start: the offending name's start byte offset carried by a Diag (brick
-- 26). 9999 for non-located diagnostics (categories 2-5, every sentinel). Mirror of
-- diag_index, reading the third field.
rule diag_span_start
  @intention: "The offending name's start byte offset carried by a Diag (9999 if not located)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:44
  input:
    d : Diag
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match d:
      MkDiag(rule_index, category, span_start, span_len) => span_start
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [d]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- diag_span_len: the offending name's byte length carried by a Diag (brick 26). 0
-- for non-located diagnostics. Mirror of diag_span_start, reading the fourth field.
rule diag_span_len
  @intention: "The offending name's byte length carried by a Diag (0 if not located)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:44
  input:
    d : Diag
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match d:
      MkDiag(rule_index, category, span_start, span_len) => span_len
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [d]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
-- BRICK 23 DRIVERS. Both tokenize + parse the source ONCE (same front end as
-- check_program), run find_diag over the parsed program, and expose ONE field of
-- the resulting Diag to argv. NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source). Take a ScanState
-- (source + pos): source is argv arg 1, pos is argv arg 2 (always 0).
--
-- Category codes (precedence order — first failing analysis wins per rule):
--   0 = clean   1 = undef-var/use-before-def   2 = undef-callee
--   3 = arity   4 = ill-typed                  5 = arg-type-mismatch
--
-- Worked examples (index, category):
--   clean      "rule add(x : number, y : number)\n  logic:\n    out = x + y\nrule main\n  logic:\n    out = add(1, 2)" -> 9999, 0
--   undef r1   "rule a\n  logic:\n    out = 1\nrule b\n  logic:\n    out = x"          -> 1, 1
--   callee r0  "rule main\n  logic:\n    out = g(1)"                                   -> 0, 2
--   arity r1   "rule f(a)\n  logic:\n    out = 1\nrule main\n  logic:\n    out = f(1, 2)" -> 1, 3
--   type r0    "rule f\n  logic:\n    out = 1 + (2 < 3)"                               -> 0, 4
--   argtype r0 "rule main\n  logic:\n    out = f(1 < 2)\nrule f(x : number)\n  logic:\n    out = x" -> 0, 5
--   precedence "rule f(x : number)\n  logic:\n    out = z\nrule main\n  logic:\n    out = f(1 < 2)" -> 0, 1
--              (rule f at index 0 has undefined z => category 1 wins over main's arg-type at index 1)
--   ordering   "rule a\n  logic:\n    out = 1\nrule b\n  logic:\n    out = 2\nrule c\n  logic:\n    out = w" -> 2, 1
rule first_bad_rule
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, find the first diagnostic, and return its 0-based rule index (9999 if clean)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:41
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let d = find_diag(FindDiagState { iter: prog, all: prog, src: s.source, idx: 0 })
    out = diag_index(d)
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, find_diag, diag_index]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- first_bad_category: the companion of first_bad_rule — same front end and same
-- find_diag walk, but returns the Diag's CATEGORY rather than its index (0 if the
-- program is clean). Together the two drivers report the (where, what) pair of the
-- program's first diagnostic.
rule first_bad_category
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, find the first diagnostic, and return its error category (0 if clean)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:41
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let d = find_diag(FindDiagState { iter: prog, all: prog, src: s.source, idx: 0 })
    out = diag_cat(d)
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, find_diag, diag_cat]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 24: report ALL diagnostics, not just the first. Brick 23's find_diag stops
-- at the FIRST failing rule and returns one Diag. This brick walks the WHOLE program
-- and builds a DiagList — a cons-list with ONE Diag per (rule, failing-category)
-- pair. A rule that is undefined-AND-ill-typed yields TWO entries (category 1 then
-- category 4); a clean rule contributes nothing. Within a rule the categories appear
-- in ascending order (1..5); rules appear in source order. The result is the full
-- categorized report.
--
-- The five per-rule analyses (each takes one RuleDecl, returns a count; >0 means that
-- category is present in that rule) are reused verbatim from bricks 13-21 — the same
-- five rule_category composes in brick 23, but here EVERY nonzero category is kept,
-- not just the first:
--   1 = undef-var/use-before-def   (lint_rule)
--   2 = undef-callee               (badcall_rule)
--   3 = arity                      (badarity_rule)
--   4 = ill-typed                  (tcheck_rule)
--   5 = arg-type-mismatch          (argtype_rule)
--
-- GRANULARITY (document carefully — this is the key distinction from brick 22):
-- diag_count counts (rule, category) PAIRS, NOT individual problems. A rule with TWO
-- undefined variables is ONE diag (category 1 is present once), whereas brick 22's
-- check_program counts it as 2 (it sums the raw per-analysis counts). So
-- all_diags_count <= check_program in general; they coincide only when no rule has
-- multiple instances of one category. This is intentional: DiagList is a CATEGORIZED
-- report (where + what-kind), check_program is a raw problem TALLY.
-- ============================================================================

-- rule_diags's input: ONE parsed rule declaration + the FULL program rule list
-- (`prog`, so the rule's calls resolve against every rule for the callee / arity /
-- arg-type passes) + the source text + the rule's 0-based index (`idx`, stamped into
-- each Diag this rule produces). Same shape as RuleCatState (brick 23) but carries
-- the index so rule_diags can construct Diags directly instead of leaving the index
-- to the caller.
concept RuleDiagsState
  @intention: "A rule declaration + the full program + the source + the rule's 0-based index, for listing all its diagnostics"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:42
  fields:
    rd : RuleDecl
    prog : RuleList
    src : text [..256]
    idx : number [0, 4096]


-- prog_diags's input: the rule list being ITERATED (`iter` advances each step, one
-- rule's diags appended per step) + the FULL program rule list (`all`, fixed, so each
-- rule's calls resolve against every rule) + the source + the running 0-based index of
-- the rule at the head of `iter`. The iter/all split mirrors find_diag's FindDiagState
-- and lint_callees_list / argtype_list: rule_diags always receives `all`, never the
-- shrinking `iter` tail.
concept ProgDiagsState
  @intention: "The rule list being walked + the full program + the source + the running rule index, for the whole-program diagnostic list"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:42
  fields:
    iter : RuleList
    all : RuleList
    src : text [..256]
    idx : number [0, 4096]


-- diag_append's input: two DiagLists. Standard cons-list append concatenates the
-- diags of one rule (`a`) in front of the diags of the rest of the program (`b`),
-- preserving order. Same shape as any binary list operation.
concept DiagAppendState
  @intention: "Two diagnostic lists to concatenate (the head rule's diags in front of the rest's)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:42
  fields:
    a : DiagList
    b : DiagList


-- diag_nth's input: a DiagList + a 0-based index `n`. nth_diag_rule / nth_diag_cat
-- walk `n` cells in and read one field off the head Diag (rule index / category),
-- returning a sentinel when n runs past the end of the list.
concept DiagNthState
  @intention: "A diagnostic list + a 0-based index, for reading the n-th diagnostic's rule index or category"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:42
  fields:
    list : DiagList
    n : number [0, 4096]


-- rule_diags: the DiagList of ALL failing categories for ONE rule, in ASCENDING
-- category order (1,2,3,4,5). NON-recursive — it just calls the five per-rule
-- analyses and conses a Diag for each nonzero one. The trick to get ascending order
-- out of a head-conses-onto-front cons-list is to build the TAIL FIRST: d5 is the
-- innermost (category 5), then d4 conses category 4 onto d5, ... d1 conses category 1
-- onto d2. So when category 1 is present it ends up at the FRONT and category 5 at the
-- back — exactly source/ascending order. Each per-rule analysis returns a COUNT; >0
-- means that category is present (once, regardless of how many instances — see the
-- granularity note above). bound is a termination BUDGET for the non-recursive
-- let-chain (the verifier counts the chain's actual operation count, which is large
-- here because each guard calls a recursive analysis); start at 1024 and raise if the
-- verifier reports the bound is short.
-- Brick 26: the category-1 (undef-var) Diag now carries the offending name's SPAN.
-- usp = undef_span_rule(...) is computed ONCE above the d5..d1 chain (cheap + pure;
-- only USED when category 1 fires); d1's MkDiag fills span_start/span_len from usp via
-- span_start(usp) / span_len(usp).
-- Brick 27: the category-2 (undef-callee) Diag now ALSO carries the offending callee
-- name's SPAN. csp = badcall_span_rule(...) is computed ONCE above the chain (same
-- cheap + pure shape as usp; only USED when category 2 fires); d2's MkDiag fills its
-- span from span_start(csp) / span_len(csp). Categories 3/4/5 (d3..d5) and every
-- sentinel keep span_start: 9999, span_len: 0 ("not located") — those analyses are
-- whole-rule properties, not name spans, so only undef-var and undef-callee point at
-- a token (a later brick may locate the rest).
rule rule_diags
  @intention: "The diagnostic list of one rule: one Diag per failing category, ascending order (1..5), empty if clean"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:42
  input:
    rds : RuleDiagsState
  output:
    out : DiagList
  logic:
    let usp = undef_span_rule(UndefSpanRuleState { rd: rds.rd, src: rds.src })
    let csp = badcall_span_rule(BadCallSpanRuleState { rd: rds.rd, rules: rds.prog, src: rds.src })
    let d5 = if argtype_rule(ArgTypeRuleState { rd: rds.rd, prog: rds.prog, src: rds.src }) > 0 then DiagList::DCons { diag: Diag::MkDiag { rule_index: rds.idx, category: 5, span_start: 9999, span_len: 0 }, rest: DiagList::DNil } else DiagList::DNil
    let d4 = if tcheck_rule(TCheckRuleState { rd: rds.rd, src: rds.src }) > 0 then DiagList::DCons { diag: Diag::MkDiag { rule_index: rds.idx, category: 4, span_start: 9999, span_len: 0 }, rest: d5 } else d5
    let d3 = if badarity_rule(BadArityRuleState { rd: rds.rd, rules: rds.prog, src: rds.src }) > 0 then DiagList::DCons { diag: Diag::MkDiag { rule_index: rds.idx, category: 3, span_start: 9999, span_len: 0 }, rest: d4 } else d4
    let d2 = if badcall_rule(BadCallRuleState { rd: rds.rd, rules: rds.prog, src: rds.src }) > 0 then DiagList::DCons { diag: Diag::MkDiag { rule_index: rds.idx, category: 2, span_start: span_start(csp), span_len: span_len(csp) }, rest: d3 } else d3
    let d1 = if lint_rule(LintRuleState { rd: rds.rd, src: rds.src }) > 0 then DiagList::DCons { diag: Diag::MkDiag { rule_index: rds.idx, category: 1, span_start: span_start(usp), span_len: span_len(usp) }, rest: d2 } else d2
    out = d1
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [rds.rd, rds.prog, rds.src, rds.idx]
      calls : [argtype_rule, tcheck_rule, badarity_rule, badcall_rule, lint_rule, undef_span_rule, badcall_span_rule, span_start, span_len]
    termination:
      bound : 1024


-- diag_append: standard cons-list append. Walks `a`, re-consing each diag in order
-- onto the result of appending the rest of `a` to `b`; when `a` is exhausted (DNil)
-- the result is `b`. Preserves order: a's diags come out before b's. Recurses on a's
-- tail. Bound-only termination + the native recursion breadcrumb (the shrinking `a`
-- tail is a field of the packed input, not the input itself).
rule diag_append
  @intention: "Concatenate two diagnostic lists, the first's diags in front of the second's, order-preserving"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:42
  input:
    da : DiagAppendState
  output:
    out : DiagList
  logic:
    out = match da.a:
      DCons(diag, rest) => DiagList::DCons { diag: diag, rest: diag_append(DiagAppendState { a: rest, b: da.b }) }
      DNil => da.b
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [da.a, da.b]
      calls : [diag_append]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- prog_diags: walk the whole program, building each rule's DiagList (rule_diags) and
-- appending it IN FRONT of the diags of the rest of the program (prog_diags on the
-- tail). The running index `idx` is the 0-based source position of the head rule; it
-- advances by 1 on each tail recursion so each rule's Diags carry the right index.
-- The append-then-recurse shape keeps program order: rule 0's diags first, then rule
-- 1's, etc. On RNil (no more rules) the report is DNil. Recurses on the tail; calls
-- diag_append + rule_diags per step. Bound-only termination + the native recursion
-- breadcrumb.
rule prog_diags
  @intention: "The whole program's diagnostic list: each rule's diags in source order, ascending category within a rule"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:42
  input:
    pds : ProgDiagsState
  output:
    out : DiagList
  logic:
    out = match pds.iter:
      RCons(head, tail) => diag_append(DiagAppendState { a: rule_diags(RuleDiagsState { rd: head, prog: pds.all, src: pds.src, idx: pds.idx }), b: prog_diags(ProgDiagsState { iter: tail, all: pds.all, src: pds.src, idx: pds.idx + 1 }) })
      RNil => DiagList::DNil
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [pds.iter, pds.all, pds.src, pds.idx]
      calls : [diag_append, rule_diags, prog_diags]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- diag_count: the LENGTH of a DiagList — the number of (rule, category) pairs in the
-- report. 0 = a fully clean program. NOT the same as check_program's count (which
-- tallies raw problems): a rule with two undefined variables adds 1 here (category 1
-- present once) but 2 to check_program. Bare-group input (`dl : DiagList`), same idiom
-- as count_cells over a TokenList. Recurses on the tail; bound-only termination + the
-- native recursion breadcrumb.
rule diag_count
  @intention: "The number of diagnostics in a report (rule-category pairs, not raw problem instances)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:42
  input:
    dl : DiagList
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match dl:
      DCons(diag, rest) => 1 + diag_count(rest)
      DNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [dl]
      calls : [diag_count]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- nth_diag_rule: the rule index of the n-th diagnostic (0-based), or the sentinel
-- 9999 if n runs past the end of the report. Walks n cells in: when n reaches 0,
-- read diag_index off the head; otherwise recurse on the tail with n-1. The 9999
-- sentinel matches brick 23's "no bad rule" convention. Recurses on the tail; calls
-- diag_index at the base. Bound-only termination + the native recursion breadcrumb.
rule nth_diag_rule
  @intention: "The rule index of the n-th diagnostic in a report (sentinel 9999 if out of bounds)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:42
  input:
    dn : DiagNthState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match dn.list:
      DCons(diag, rest) => if dn.n == 0 then diag_index(diag) else nth_diag_rule(DiagNthState { list: rest, n: dn.n - 1 })
      DNil => 9999
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [dn.list, dn.n]
      calls : [diag_index, nth_diag_rule]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- nth_diag_cat: the category of the n-th diagnostic (0-based), or the sentinel 0 if
-- n runs past the end of the report (0 = "clean / no category", matching brick 23's
-- category convention). Mirror of nth_diag_rule, reading diag_cat instead. Recurses
-- on the tail; calls diag_cat at the base. Bound-only termination + the native
-- recursion breadcrumb.
rule nth_diag_cat
  @intention: "The error category of the n-th diagnostic in a report (sentinel 0 if out of bounds)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:42
  input:
    dn : DiagNthState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match dn.list:
      DCons(diag, rest) => if dn.n == 0 then diag_cat(diag) else nth_diag_cat(DiagNthState { list: rest, n: dn.n - 1 })
      DNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [dn.list, dn.n]
      calls : [diag_cat, nth_diag_cat]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- nth_diag_span_start: the offending name's start byte offset of the n-th diagnostic
-- (brick 26), or the sentinel 9999 if n runs past the end of the report (matching the
-- "not located" convention). Mirror of nth_diag_rule, reading diag_span_start instead.
-- Recurses on the tail; calls diag_span_start at the base.
rule nth_diag_span_start
  @intention: "The offending name's start byte offset of the n-th diagnostic (sentinel 9999 if out of bounds)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:44
  input:
    dn : DiagNthState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match dn.list:
      DCons(diag, rest) => if dn.n == 0 then diag_span_start(diag) else nth_diag_span_start(DiagNthState { list: rest, n: dn.n - 1 })
      DNil => 9999
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [dn.list, dn.n]
      calls : [diag_span_start, nth_diag_span_start]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- nth_diag_span_len: the offending name's byte length of the n-th diagnostic (brick
-- 26), or 0 if n runs past the end of the report. Mirror of nth_diag_span_start,
-- reading diag_span_len. Recurses on the tail; calls diag_span_len at the base.
rule nth_diag_span_len
  @intention: "The offending name's byte length of the n-th diagnostic (0 if out of bounds)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:44
  input:
    dn : DiagNthState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match dn.list:
      DCons(diag, rest) => if dn.n == 0 then diag_span_len(diag) else nth_diag_span_len(DiagNthState { list: rest, n: dn.n - 1 })
      DNil => 0
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [dn.list, dn.n]
      calls : [diag_span_len, nth_diag_span_len]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
-- BRICK 24 DRIVERS. All three tokenize + parse the source ONCE (same front end as
-- check_program / first_bad_rule), build the whole-program DiagList via prog_diags,
-- and expose one observable to argv. NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source). Take a ScanState
-- (source + pos): source is argv arg 1, pos is argv arg 2. For all_diags_count, pos is
-- ignored (always 0); for the nth_diag_at_* drivers, pos DOUBLES as the index n.
--
-- Category codes (a rule may carry SEVERAL, in ascending order):
--   1 = undef-var/use-before-def   2 = undef-callee   3 = arity
--   4 = ill-typed                  5 = arg-type-mismatch
--
-- WORKED EXAMPLES (granularity is the headline — counts are rule-category PAIRS):
--   clean       "rule add(x : number, y : number)\n  logic:\n    out = x + y\nrule main\n  logic:\n    out = add(1, 2)"
--                 all_diags_count = 0   (every rule clean)
--   granularity "rule f\n  logic:\n    out = x + y"
--                 all_diags_count = 1   (TWO undefined vars, but ONE category-1 diag);
--                 nth_diag_at_rule n=0 -> 0, nth_diag_at_cat n=0 -> 1.
--                 CONTRAST: check_program on the SAME source = 2 (it tallies x and y
--                 separately). all_diags_count <= check_program, always.
--   two-cats    "rule f\n  logic:\n    out = z + (1 < 2)"
--                 all_diags_count = 2   (undef z => cat 1, number+bool => cat 4, ONE rule);
--                 nth(0) = (rule 0, cat 1), nth(1) = (rule 0, cat 4).
--   two-rules   "rule a\n  logic:\n    out = x\nrule b\n  logic:\n    out = y"
--                 all_diags_count = 2; nth(0) = (0, 1), nth(1) = (1, 1).
--   quad        "rule f(a : number)\n  logic:\n    out = z + 1\nrule main\n  logic:\n    out = f(1 < 2, 3) + g(9)"
--                 all_diags_count = 4 (undef z in rule 0 => (0,1); rule 1 has undefined
--                 callee g => (1,2), arity 2-vs-1 on f => (1,3), bool arg to f's number
--                 param => (1,5)); nth(0)=(0,1), nth(1)=(1,2), nth(2)=(1,3), nth(3)=(1,5).
rule all_diags_count
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse once, and return the number of diagnostics (rule-category pairs) in the whole program"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:42
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    out = diag_count(prog_diags(ProgDiagsState { iter: prog, all: prog, src: s.source, idx: 0 }))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, diag_count, prog_diags]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- nth_diag_at_rule: the rule index of the n-th diagnostic, where n is taken from
-- argv arg 2 (s.pos doubles as the index). Front end + prog_diags identical to
-- all_diags_count; nth_diag_rule reads the n-th cell. 9999 if n is out of bounds.
rule nth_diag_at_rule
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, build the diagnostic list, and return the n-th diagnostic's rule index (n from argv)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:42
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    out = nth_diag_rule(DiagNthState { list: prog_diags(ProgDiagsState { iter: prog, all: prog, src: s.source, idx: 0 }), n: s.pos })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, nth_diag_rule, prog_diags]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- nth_diag_at_cat: the companion of nth_diag_at_rule — same front end and same
-- prog_diags, but returns the n-th diagnostic's CATEGORY (0 if n is out of bounds).
-- Together the two drivers expose the (where, what-kind) pair of any diagnostic in the
-- complete report, indexed by n from argv.
rule nth_diag_at_cat
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, build the diagnostic list, and return the n-th diagnostic's error category (n from argv)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:42
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    out = nth_diag_cat(DiagNthState { list: prog_diags(ProgDiagsState { iter: prog, all: prog, src: s.source, idx: 0 }), n: s.pos })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, nth_diag_cat, prog_diags]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
-- BRICK 26 DRIVERS. The LOCATED full report. Same front end + prog_diags as the
-- brick-24 nth_diag_at_* drivers, but expose the n-th diagnostic's SOURCE SPAN so the
-- report says WHERE, not just which-rule / what-kind. Only undefined-variable
-- diagnostics (category 1) carry a real span; every other category (2-5) and every
-- out-of-bounds n reads the sentinel (start 9999, len 0): "not located". NATIVE-ONLY
-- (multi-line source). ScanState: source is argv arg 1, n is argv arg 2 (s.pos).
--
-- WORKED EXAMPLES (spans are whitespace-dependent; the LEN and the sentinel are stable):
--   single undef "rule f\n  logic:\n    out = foo + 1"
--                 nth_diag_at_span_start n=0 -> 26 (offset of foo), n=0 len -> 3.
--                 Cross-check: undef_span_start_of on the SAME source = 26 too.
--   quad         "rule f(a : number)\n  logic:\n    out = z + 1\nrule main\n  logic:\n    out = f(1 < 2, 3) + g(9)"
--                 diag 0 = (rule 0, cat 1, LOCATED): span_len n=0 -> 1 (z is one char),
--                 span_start n=0 -> offset of z. diag 1/2/3 = cats 2/3/5, span SENTINEL:
--                 span_start n=1 -> 9999, span_len n=1 -> 0 (NOT located).
--   clean        "rule add(x : number, y : number)\n  logic:\n    out = x + y\nrule main\n  logic:\n    out = add(1, 2)"
--                 empty list: span_start n=0 -> 9999, span_len n=0 -> 0.
rule nth_diag_at_span_start
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, build the diagnostic list, and return the n-th diagnostic's offending-name start offset (n from argv)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:44
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    out = nth_diag_span_start(DiagNthState { list: prog_diags(ProgDiagsState { iter: prog, all: prog, src: s.source, idx: 0 }), n: s.pos })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, nth_diag_span_start, prog_diags]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- nth_diag_at_span_len: companion of nth_diag_at_span_start — same front end and same
-- prog_diags, but returns the n-th diagnostic's offending-name byte LENGTH (0 if n is
-- out of bounds or the diagnostic is not located). Together the two drivers expose the
-- (start, len) span of any located diagnostic in the complete report, indexed by n.
rule nth_diag_at_span_len
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, build the diagnostic list, and return the n-th diagnostic's offending-name byte length (n from argv)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:44
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    out = nth_diag_span_len(DiagNthState { list: prog_diags(ProgDiagsState { iter: prog, all: prog, src: s.source, idx: 0 }), n: s.pos })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source, s.pos]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, nth_diag_span_len, prog_diags]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- ============================================================================
-- BRICK 25: column-level location for undefined variables. Bricks 13/14 COUNTED
-- undefined-variable references (lint_rule -> a number); this brick walks the SAME
-- traversal in the SAME scope discipline but returns the (start, len) SPAN of the
-- FIRST unbound AstVar — the byte range a diagnostic points at. The undef_span_*
-- family mirrors count_undef_* arm-for-arm, swapping "+ (sum)" for span_or
-- ("first non-sentinel wins"). The sentinel for "no undefined variable here" is
-- MkSpan(9999, 0); span_or treats start == 9999 as "empty".
--
-- TRAVERSAL ORDER (must match count_undef exactly so the FIRST span found is the
-- first count_undef would have tallied):
--   * within a rule: the let-bindings' RHSs (source order, ordered/prefix scope)
--     come BEFORE the result expression — undef_span_rule does in_binds first.
--   * within an expression: left-to-right — AstBin lhs before rhs, AstIf cond
--     before thn before els, AstCall args head before tail. span_or(a, b) returns
--     a unless a is the sentinel, so the leftmost real span wins.
--   * across rules: program order (undef_span_list head before tail).
--
-- The observables the drivers expose:
--   * undef_span_start_of -> the byte offset of the first unbound name (9999 if none)
--   * undef_span_len_of   -> its byte length (0 if none)
--   * undef_span_char     -> byte_at(source, start) = the first character of the name
--     ('x'=120, 'y'=121, 'z'=122, 'w'=119, 'a'=97, 'b'=98, 'f'=102, 'q'=113); on the
--     sentinel start 9999, byte_at is out of bounds and ABORTS (sys_exit(1)) — the
--     native byte_at is fail-closed on OOB, so a clean program has no first byte to
--     point at. Test cleanliness via undef_span_start_of (== 9999), not the char.
-- ============================================================================

-- span_start: the start byte offset of a Span. Bare-group accessor, same idiom as
-- diag_index / rd_body (input is a bare group value `s : Span`).
rule span_start
  @intention: "The start byte offset carried by a Span"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  input:
    s : Span
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match s:
      MkSpan(start, len) => start
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- span_len: the byte length of a Span. Mirror of span_start.
rule span_len
  @intention: "The byte length carried by a Span"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  input:
    s : Span
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    out = match s:
      MkSpan(start, len) => len
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s]
      calls : []
    termination:
      bound : 16


-- span_or's input: two candidate Spans. The "first non-sentinel" combinator that
-- replaces the "+ (sum)" of the count version: in count_undef, two subtrees'
-- counts ADD; here the first subtree's span WINS unless it is the empty sentinel,
-- in which case the second is taken. This is what makes the leftmost undefined
-- variable the reported one.
concept SpanOrState
  @intention: "Two candidate Spans, to pick the first non-sentinel"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  fields:
    a : Span
    b : Span


-- span_or: pick the first non-sentinel Span. The sentinel is MkSpan(9999, 0); a
-- start of 9999 means "no span here", so when so.a is the sentinel we fall through
-- to so.b (which may itself be the sentinel — span_or composes associatively).
rule span_or
  @intention: "The first of two Spans that is not the no-result sentinel (start 9999)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  input:
    so : SpanOrState
  output:
    out : Span
  logic:
    out = if span_start(so.a) == 9999 then so.b else so.a
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [so.a, so.b]
      calls : [span_start]
    termination:
      bound : 32


-- undef_span_ast's input: one Ast node + the rule's binding scope + the source
-- text (spans index into it). Same triple as UndefAstState (the count version);
-- the only difference is the RETURN type (Span, not number).
concept UndefSpanAstState
  @intention: "An Ast node + the binding scope + the source text, for locating its first undefined variable"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  fields:
    node : Ast
    binds : Binding
    src : text [..256]


-- undef_span_ast: walk an Ast and return the SPAN of the first AstVar reference
-- whose name is NOT name_bound in the scope. Mirrors count_undef_ast arm-for-arm:
--   * AstVar(start, len) => the span (start, len) if unbound, else the sentinel.
--   * AstBin walks lhs THEN rhs via span_or (lhs wins on a tie — left-to-right).
--   * AstNeg/AstNot/AstField recurse into their single child.
--   * AstCall walks its ARGUMENT list (undef_span_args); the callee name is a
--     callee-resolution concern (brick 15), not a variable reference, so it is
--     not probed here — identical to count_undef_ast.
--   * AstIf walks cond, thn, els left-to-right via nested span_or.
--   * leaves (AstNum/AstBool/AstStr/AstErr) have no variable => the sentinel.
-- Mutually recursive with undef_span_args. Bound-only termination + the mandatory
-- native recursion breadcrumb (the shrinking node is a FIELD of the packed input,
-- not the input itself — same posture as count_undef_ast / shape_ast).
rule undef_span_ast
  @intention: "The span of the first undefined-variable reference inside an Ast (sentinel MkSpan(9999,0) if none)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  input:
    a : UndefSpanAstState
  output:
    out : Span
  logic:
    out = match a.node:
      AstNum(value) => Span::MkSpan { start: 9999, len: 0 }
      AstBool(value) => Span::MkSpan { start: 9999, len: 0 }
      AstStr(start, len) => Span::MkSpan { start: 9999, len: 0 }
      AstErr => Span::MkSpan { start: 9999, len: 0 }
      AstVar(start, len) => if name_bound(NameBoundState { binds: a.binds, src: a.src, q_start: start, q_len: len }) == 0 then Span::MkSpan { start: start, len: len } else Span::MkSpan { start: 9999, len: 0 }
      AstBin(op, lhs, rhs) => span_or(SpanOrState { a: undef_span_ast(UndefSpanAstState { node: lhs, binds: a.binds, src: a.src }), b: undef_span_ast(UndefSpanAstState { node: rhs, binds: a.binds, src: a.src }) })
      AstNeg(inner) => undef_span_ast(UndefSpanAstState { node: inner, binds: a.binds, src: a.src })
      AstNot(inner) => undef_span_ast(UndefSpanAstState { node: inner, binds: a.binds, src: a.src })
      AstField(base, fstart, flen) => undef_span_ast(UndefSpanAstState { node: base, binds: a.binds, src: a.src })
      AstCall(callee_start, callee_len, args) => undef_span_args(UndefSpanArgsState { args: args, binds: a.binds, src: a.src })
      AstIf(cond, thn, els) => span_or(SpanOrState { a: span_or(SpanOrState { a: undef_span_ast(UndefSpanAstState { node: cond, binds: a.binds, src: a.src }), b: undef_span_ast(UndefSpanAstState { node: thn, binds: a.binds, src: a.src }) }), b: undef_span_ast(UndefSpanAstState { node: els, binds: a.binds, src: a.src }) })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.node, a.binds, a.src]
      calls : [name_bound, span_or, undef_span_ast, undef_span_args]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- undef_span_args's input: a call's argument list + the rule's binding scope + the
-- source text. Same triple as UndefArgsState (the count version), Span return.
concept UndefSpanArgsState
  @intention: "A call's argument list + the binding scope + the source text, for locating its first undefined variable"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  fields:
    args : ArgList
    binds : Binding
    src : text [..256]


-- undef_span_args: walk a call's ArgList, returning the span of the first undefined
-- variable found across its arguments (head before tail, via span_or). Mirrors
-- count_undef_args; mutually recursive with undef_span_ast (a call's arguments are
-- themselves Asts). Bound-only termination + the native recursion breadcrumb (the
-- shrinking `args` tail is a field of the packed input).
rule undef_span_args
  @intention: "The span of the first undefined-variable reference across a call's arguments (sentinel if none)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  input:
    a : UndefSpanArgsState
  output:
    out : Span
  logic:
    out = match a.args:
      ArgCons(head, tail) => span_or(SpanOrState { a: undef_span_ast(UndefSpanAstState { node: head, binds: a.binds, src: a.src }), b: undef_span_args(UndefSpanArgsState { args: tail, binds: a.binds, src: a.src }) })
      ArgNil => Span::MkSpan { start: 9999, len: 0 }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.args, a.binds, a.src]
      calls : [span_or, undef_span_ast, undef_span_args]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- undef_span_binds's input: the binding list being ITERATED + the PREFIX of earlier
-- bindings (the use-before-def scope) + the source text. Same triple as
-- UndefBindsOrderedState (the count version), Span return.
concept UndefSpanBindsState
  @intention: "The binding list being walked + the prefix of earlier bindings + the source text, for use-before-def location"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  fields:
    iter : Binding
    prefix : Binding
    src : text [..256]


-- undef_span_binds: for each binding in `iter`, locate the first undefined variable
-- in its RHS expression scoped to the PREFIX of bindings that appear EARLIER (proper
-- let-ordering: a forward or self reference in a let RHS is flagged). Mirrors
-- count_undef_binds_ordered: the prefix grows by the current binding before
-- recursing on the tail, so the next binding sees this one but not vice versa. The
-- current binding's RHS is checked BEFORE the tail (source order), via span_or.
-- Bound-only termination + the native recursion breadcrumb (the shrinking `iter`
-- tail is a field of the packed input).
rule undef_span_binds
  @intention: "The span of the first undefined-OR-use-before-def variable across a binding list's RHSs (sentinel if none)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  input:
    a : UndefSpanBindsState
  output:
    out : Span
  logic:
    out = match a.iter:
      BCons(name_start, name_len, value, rest) => span_or(SpanOrState { a: undef_span_ast(UndefSpanAstState { node: value, binds: a.prefix, src: a.src }), b: undef_span_binds(UndefSpanBindsState { iter: rest, prefix: Binding::BCons { name_start: name_start, name_len: name_len, value: value, rest: a.prefix }, src: a.src }) })
      BNil => Span::MkSpan { start: 9999, len: 0 }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.iter, a.prefix, a.src]
      calls : [span_or, undef_span_ast, undef_span_binds]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- undef_span_rule's input: one rule declaration + the program source text. Same
-- shape as LintRuleState (the count version), Span return.
concept UndefSpanRuleState
  @intention: "A rule declaration + the program source text, for locating its first undefined variable"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  fields:
    rd : RuleDecl
    src : text [..256]


-- undef_span_rule: the span of the first undefined-OR-use-before-def variable in ONE
-- rule. Mirrors lint_rule: build the scope (params as the base prefix; params
-- appended to the full binding list for the result), then check the bindings'
-- ordered RHSs FIRST, then the result expression — span_or keeps the in_binds span
-- if there is one (the let RHSs precede the result in source order). Bound-only
-- termination + the native recursion breadcrumb.
rule undef_span_rule
  @intention: "The span of the first undefined-OR-use-before-def reference in one rule (params in scope; sentinel if clean)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  input:
    a : UndefSpanRuleState
  output:
    out : Span
  logic:
    let body = rd_body(a.rd)
    let binds = block_binds(body)
    let result = block_result(body)
    let pbinds = param_to_binding(rd_params(a.rd))
    let scope = append_bindings(BindAppendState { a: pbinds, b: binds })
    let in_binds = undef_span_binds(UndefSpanBindsState { iter: binds, prefix: pbinds, src: a.src })
    out = span_or(SpanOrState { a: in_binds, b: undef_span_ast(UndefSpanAstState { node: result, binds: scope, src: a.src }) })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.rd, a.src]
      calls : [rd_body, block_binds, block_result, rd_params, param_to_binding, append_bindings, undef_span_binds, span_or, undef_span_ast]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- undef_span_list's input: the rule list being folded + the program source text.
-- Same shape as LintListState (the count version), Span return.
concept UndefSpanListState
  @intention: "A rule list + the program source text, for locating the program's first undefined variable"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  fields:
    rl : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- undef_span_list: the span of the first undefined-OR-use-before-def variable across
-- every rule in the program, in program order. Mirrors lint_list: the head rule is
-- checked BEFORE the tail (via span_or), so the earliest rule's earliest undefined
-- variable wins. Bound-only termination + the native recursion breadcrumb (the
-- shrinking `rl` tail is a field of the packed input).
rule undef_span_list
  @intention: "The span of the program's first undefined-variable reference, in program order (sentinel if clean)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  input:
    a : UndefSpanListState
  output:
    out : Span
  logic:
    out = match a.rl:
      RCons(head, tail) => span_or(SpanOrState { a: undef_span_rule(UndefSpanRuleState { rd: head, src: a.src }), b: undef_span_list(UndefSpanListState { rl: tail, src: a.src }) })
      RNil => Span::MkSpan { start: 9999, len: 0 }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.rl, a.src]
      calls : [span_or, undef_span_rule, undef_span_list]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
-- BRICK 27: the undefined-CALLEE span family. Mirrors the count_badcall_* family
-- (brick "category 2") arm-for-arm, swapping "+ (sum)" for span_or and returning
-- the offending callee NAME span instead of a count. Where count_badcall returns
-- "how many call sites name a rule that does not exist", badcall_span returns the
-- SPAN of the FIRST such callee — in the same traversal order count_badcall sums:
-- binds before result, left-to-right within an expression, and (the load-bearing
-- arm) the OUTER call's callee BEFORE descending into its args. The sentinel for
-- "no bad callee here" is MkSpan(9999, 0); span_or treats start == 9999 as empty.
--
-- This is the analogue of the brick-25 undef_span_* family, but SIMPLER on the
-- rule level: undefined-callee scope is program-wide, so badcall_span_rule does
-- NOT build a param scope or thread a binding prefix — it just checks the binds
-- then the result, both against the same program RuleList (exactly as badcall_rule
-- does for the count). The Ast/args/binds walkers mirror their count_badcall twins.
-- ----------------------------------------------------------------------------


-- badcall_span_ast's input: one Ast node + the program's RuleList (callee scope) +
-- the source text (spans index into it). Same triple as BadCallState (the count
-- version); the only difference is the RETURN type (Span, not number).
concept BadCallSpanState
  @intention: "An Ast node + the program rule list (callee scope) + the source text, for locating its first undefined callee"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:45
  fields:
    node : Ast
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- badcall_span_args's input: a call's argument list + the program's RuleList
-- (callee scope) + the source text. Mirrors BadCallArgsState; Span return.
concept BadCallSpanArgsState
  @intention: "A call-argument list + the program rule list (callee scope) + the source text, for locating its first undefined callee"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:45
  fields:
    args : ArgList
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- badcall_span_binds's input: the binding list whose RHSes are walked + the
-- program's RuleList (callee scope) + the source text. Mirrors BadCallBindsState;
-- Span return. As with the count version there is no prefix — callee scope is
-- program-wide, so every RHS sees the FULL program rule list.
concept BadCallSpanBindsState
  @intention: "A binding list + the program rule list (callee scope) + the source text, for locating its first undefined callee"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:45
  fields:
    binds : Binding
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- badcall_span_rule's input: ONE rule declaration + the FULL program RuleList (the
-- checked rule may call itself or any other rule) + the source text. Mirrors
-- BadCallRuleState; Span return.
concept BadCallSpanRuleState
  @intention: "A rule declaration + the full program rule list + the source text, for locating its first undefined callee"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:45
  fields:
    rd : RuleDecl
    rules : RuleList
    src : text [..256]


-- badcall_span_ast: walk an Ast and return the SPAN of the first AstCall whose
-- callee name is NOT rule_named in the program. Mirrors count_badcall_ast's
-- structural walk, swapping "+ (sum)" for span_or:
--   * AstCall(callee_start, callee_len, args) => if the callee does NOT exist
--     (rule_named == 0) report ITS name span IMMEDIATELY (MkSpan(callee_start,
--     callee_len)); only if the callee EXISTS descend into the args via
--     badcall_span_args. This "callee before args" order matches count_badcall and
--     reports the OUTER/first undefined callee (e.g. in g(h(1)) with g undefined,
--     g's span wins; with g defined and h undefined, we descend and h's span wins).
--   * AstBin walks lhs THEN rhs via span_or (lhs wins on a tie — left-to-right).
--   * AstNeg / AstNot / AstField descend into their single child.
--   * AstIf walks cond, thn, els left-to-right via nested span_or.
--   * AstVar / AstNum / AstStr / AstBool / AstErr carry no callee -> sentinel.
-- Mutually recursive with badcall_span_args. a.node is a FIELD of the packed input
-- (not the input), so bound + the mandatory native recursion breadcrumb.
rule badcall_span_ast
  @intention: "The span of the first undefined-callee reference in an AST, given the program's rule list (sentinel if clean)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:45
  input:
    a : BadCallSpanState
  output:
    out : Span
  logic:
    out = match a.node:
      AstNum(value) => Span::MkSpan { start: 9999, len: 0 }
      AstBool(value) => Span::MkSpan { start: 9999, len: 0 }
      AstVar(start, len) => Span::MkSpan { start: 9999, len: 0 }
      AstStr(start, len) => Span::MkSpan { start: 9999, len: 0 }
      AstErr => Span::MkSpan { start: 9999, len: 0 }
      AstBin(op, lhs, rhs) => span_or(SpanOrState { a: badcall_span_ast(BadCallSpanState { node: lhs, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }), b: badcall_span_ast(BadCallSpanState { node: rhs, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }) })
      AstNeg(inner) => badcall_span_ast(BadCallSpanState { node: inner, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstNot(inner) => badcall_span_ast(BadCallSpanState { node: inner, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstField(base, fstart, flen) => badcall_span_ast(BadCallSpanState { node: base, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstCall(callee_start, callee_len, args) => if rule_named(RuleNamedState { rules: a.rules, src: a.src, q_start: callee_start, q_len: callee_len }) == 0 then Span::MkSpan { start: callee_start, len: callee_len } else badcall_span_args(BadCallSpanArgsState { args: args, rules: a.rules, src: a.src })
      AstIf(cond, thn, els) => span_or(SpanOrState { a: span_or(SpanOrState { a: badcall_span_ast(BadCallSpanState { node: cond, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }), b: badcall_span_ast(BadCallSpanState { node: thn, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }) }), b: badcall_span_ast(BadCallSpanState { node: els, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }) })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.node, a.rules, a.src]
      calls : [rule_named, span_or, badcall_span_ast, badcall_span_args]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- badcall_span_args: walk a call's ArgList, returning the span of the first
-- undefined callee found across its arguments (head before tail, via span_or).
-- Mirrors count_badcall_args; mutually recursive with badcall_span_ast (a call's
-- arguments are themselves Asts that may contain more calls). Recurses over the
-- tail (a field of the input), so bound + breadcrumb; rules + src threaded down.
rule badcall_span_args
  @intention: "The span of the first undefined callee across every argument of a call (sentinel if clean)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:45
  input:
    a : BadCallSpanArgsState
  output:
    out : Span
  logic:
    out = match a.args:
      ArgCons(head, tail) => span_or(SpanOrState { a: badcall_span_ast(BadCallSpanState { node: head, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }), b: badcall_span_args(BadCallSpanArgsState { args: tail, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }) })
      ArgNil => Span::MkSpan { start: 9999, len: 0 }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.args, a.rules, a.src]
      calls : [span_or, badcall_span_ast, badcall_span_args]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- badcall_span_binds: for each binding in the list, locate the first undefined
-- callee in its RHS `value` (against the FULL program rule list), then recurse on
-- `rest`. The current binding's RHS is checked BEFORE the tail (source order), via
-- span_or. Mirrors count_badcall_binds; no prefix (callee scope is program-wide).
-- Recurses over the binding tail (a field of the input), so bound + breadcrumb.
rule badcall_span_binds
  @intention: "The span of the first undefined callee across every binding's RHS (sentinel if clean)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:45
  input:
    a : BadCallSpanBindsState
  output:
    out : Span
  logic:
    out = match a.binds:
      BCons(name_start, name_len, value, rest) => span_or(SpanOrState { a: badcall_span_ast(BadCallSpanState { node: value, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }), b: badcall_span_binds(BadCallSpanBindsState { binds: rest, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }) })
      BNil => Span::MkSpan { start: 9999, len: 0 }
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.binds, a.rules, a.src]
      calls : [span_or, badcall_span_ast, badcall_span_binds]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- badcall_span_rule: the span of the first undefined callee in ONE rule. Mirrors
-- badcall_rule (the count), but SIMPLER than undef_span_rule (the var-span version)
-- because callee scope is program-wide — there is no param scope and no binding
-- prefix to thread. Split the body Block into its binding list and result, then:
--   * badcall_span_binds over the bindings (every let RHS's callees), THEN
--   * badcall_span_ast over the result expression's callees.
-- span_or keeps the in_binds span if there is one (the let RHSs precede the result
-- in source order). Both halves resolve callees against the SAME full program
-- RuleList `a.rules`. Bound-only termination.
--
-- Worked examples (offsets into the source text, 0-based bytes):
--   `rule main\n  logic:\n    out = g(1)`         -> MkSpan(<offset of g>, 1)
--   `rule main\n  logic:\n    out = foobar(1)`    -> MkSpan(<offset of foobar>, 6)
--   `rule f\n  logic:\n    out = z + 1\nrule main\n  logic:\n    out = f(1, 2) + g(9)`
--                                                  -> for rule main: MkSpan(<offset of g>, 1)
--                                                     (f is defined, so f(1, 2) is clean;
--                                                      the result walk descends past f into g)
--   a rule whose every callee exists (incl. self / forward refs) -> MkSpan(9999, 0).
rule badcall_span_rule
  @intention: "The span of the first undefined-callee reference in one rule (callees resolved program-wide; sentinel if clean)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:45
  input:
    a : BadCallSpanRuleState
  output:
    out : Span
  logic:
    let body = rd_body(a.rd)
    let binds = block_binds(body)
    let result = block_result(body)
    out = span_or(SpanOrState { a: badcall_span_binds(BadCallSpanBindsState { binds: binds, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }), b: badcall_span_ast(BadCallSpanState { node: result, rules: a.rules, src: a.src }) })
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [a.rd, a.rules, a.src]
      calls : [rd_body, block_binds, block_result, badcall_span_binds, span_or, badcall_span_ast]
    termination:
      bound : 4000


-- ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
-- BRICK 25 DRIVERS. All three tokenize + parse the source ONCE (same front end as
-- lint_program), run undef_span_list over the parsed program, and expose ONE
-- observable of the resulting Span to argv. NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source). Take a
-- ScanState (source + pos): source is argv arg 1, pos is argv arg 2 (always 0).
--
-- The sentinel: a clean program yields MkSpan(9999, 0). Reading span_start gives
-- 9999 and span_len gives 0 — both are stable "nothing here" values. undef_span_char
-- does byte_at(source, 9999): the native byte_at is FAIL-CLOSED on an out-of-bounds
-- index (jae .abort -> sys_exit(1)), so on a clean program undef_span_char ABORTS
-- with exit status 1 and no stdout rather than printing a value. That is the correct
-- posture for a char accessor: there is no first byte of a name that does not exist,
-- so the only honest answers are "the byte" (a real undefined variable) or "abort"
-- (no undefined variable to point at). Use span_start == 9999 (undef_span_start_of)
-- to test cleanliness; undef_span_char is meaningful ONLY when there IS a diagnostic.
--
-- The char observable: undef_span_char returns byte_at(source, start), i.e. the
-- FIRST byte of the offending name. Worked examples:
--   clean       "rule add(x : number, y : number)\n  logic:\n    out = x + y\nrule main\n  logic:\n    out = add(1, 2)" -> start 9999, len 0, char ABORTS (exit 1, no first byte)
--   undef x     "rule f\n  logic:\n    out = x + y"                  -> char 120 ('x'), len 1 (lhs of +, leftmost)
--   undef y     "rule f\n  logic:\n    out = 1 + y"                  -> char 121 ('y'), len 1 (1 is a leaf, y is the first var)
--   multi-char  "rule f\n  logic:\n    out = foo + 1"               -> char 102 ('f'), len 3 (name "foo")
--   use-bef-def "rule f\n  logic:\n    let p = q + 1\n    let q = 2\n    out = p" -> char 113 ('q'), len 1
--               (q is unbound in p's RHS; binding RHSs are checked before the result)
--   across      "rule a\n  logic:\n    out = 1\nrule b\n  logic:\n    out = zzz"  -> char 122 ('z'), len 3 (rule 1's zzz; rule 0 clean)
--   in arg      "rule main\n  logic:\n    out = f(w)\nrule f(x : number)\n  logic:\n    out = x" -> char 119 ('w'), len 1
--               (w undefined in main; f's param x is in scope only inside f)
-- ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

-- undef_span_start_of: the byte offset of the program's first undefined variable
-- (9999 if clean). Front end + undef_span_list identical to the other two drivers;
-- span_start reads the field off the resulting Span.
rule undef_span_start_of
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, find the first undefined variable, and return its start byte offset (9999 if clean)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    out = span_start(undef_span_list(UndefSpanListState { rl: prog, src: s.source }))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, span_start, undef_span_list]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- undef_span_len_of: the byte length of the program's first undefined variable's
-- name (0 if clean). Same front end and undef_span_list as undef_span_start_of;
-- span_len reads the length field.
rule undef_span_len_of
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, find the first undefined variable, and return its name byte length (0 if clean)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    out = span_len(undef_span_list(UndefSpanListState { rl: prog, src: s.source }))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, span_len, undef_span_list]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- undef_span_char: the FIRST byte of the offending name — byte_at(source, start).
-- This is the stable, source-independent observable: it does not depend on the byte
-- offset of the name (which shifts with whitespace), only on the name's first
-- character. On the sentinel start 9999, byte_at is out of bounds and the native
-- byte_at ABORTS (sys_exit(1)) rather than returning a value — so this driver is
-- meaningful only when there IS an undefined variable; test cleanliness via
-- undef_span_start_of. Same front end and undef_span_list as the other two drivers.
rule undef_span_char
  @intention: "Tokenize, parse, find the first undefined variable, and return its name's first byte (aborts if clean)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:43
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = begin_tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    let prog = parse_program(ProgramState { toks: toks, src: s.source, pos: 0 })
    out = byte_at(s.source, span_start(undef_span_list(UndefSpanListState { rl: prog, src: s.source })))
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [begin_tokenize, parse_program, span_start, undef_span_list]
    termination:
      bound : 256


-- Entry driver: tokenize the source (from argv) and count the cons cells. The
-- money-shot observable for brick 8a: count_cells_src("1 + 2\n3 * 4") = 8
-- (tokens 1 + 2 Newline 3 * 4 then trailing Eof). Newline-bearing sources are
-- NATIVE-ONLY (the interpreter's JSON reader does not decode \n into a real
-- byte 10 — it passes the two bytes backslash-n verbatim), so multi-line counts
-- are checked via argv $'a\nb'; single-line counts cross-check native vs the
-- interpreter through the JSON fixture, exactly like brick 5/7's comma/string
-- cases. count_cells_src takes a ScanState (matching the .json fixture shape),
-- so it is the LAST rule in the file — the conventional "primary" the example
-- sweep test (all_examples_with_json_run_without_panicking) exercises against
-- the JSON records.
rule count_cells_src
  @intention: "Tokenize a source and count its token cons cells (multi-line aware)"
  @source: vexprparse.intent:26
  input:
    s : ScanState
  output:
    out : number
  logic:
    let toks = tokenize(ScanState { source: s.source, pos: 0 })
    out = count_cells(toks)
  proofs:
    purity:
      reads : [s.source]
      calls : [tokenize, count_cells]
    termination:
      bound : 256

